{"title_page": "Rex Hartwig", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian tennis player}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n| name                          = Rex Hartwig\n| image                         = Rex Hartwig.png\n| image_size                    =\n| caption                       =\n| fullname                      = Rex Noel Hartwig\n| country                       = {{flagu|Australia}}\n| residence                     =\n| birth_date                    = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1929|09|02}}\n| birth_place                   = [[Culcairn, New South Wales]], Australia\n| death_date                    =\n| death_place                   =\n| height                        =\n| turnedpro                     = 1950 (amateur tour)\n| retired                       = 1962\n| plays                         = Right-handed (1-handed backhand)\n| careerprizemoney              =\n| tennishofyear                 =\n| tennishofid                   =\n| singlesrecord                 =\n| singlestitles                 =\n| highestsinglesranking         = No. 5 (1954<small>, [[The Daily Telegraph|Lance Tingay]]</small>)<ref name=\"USLTAEncyclopedia\">United States Lawn Tennis Association (1972). ''Official Encyclopedia of Tennis'' (First Edition), p. 426.</ref>\n| AustralianOpenresult          = F ([[1954 Australian Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1954]])\n| FrenchOpenresult              = 4R ([[1953 French Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1953]], [[1954 French Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1954]])\n| Wimbledonresult               = QF ([[1954 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1954]])\n| USOpenresult                  = F ([[1954 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1954]])\n| Othertournaments              = \n| Olympicssresult               =\n| doublesrecord                 =\n| doublestitles                 =\n| highestdoublesranking         =\n| grandslamsdoublesresults      = \n| AustralianOpenDoublesresult   = '''W''' (1954)\n| FrenchOpenDoublesresult       =\n| WimbledonDoublesresult        = '''W''' (1954, 1955)\n| USOpenDoublesresult           = '''W''' (1953)\n| OthertournamentsDoubles       = \n| OlympicsDoublesresult         = <!-- optional -->\n| Mixed                         = <!-- optional, adds mixed information-->\n| mixedtitles                   =\n| mixedrecord                   =\n| highestmixedranking           =\n| AustralianOpenMixedresult     = '''W''' (1953, 1954)\n| FrenchOpenMixedresult         = F (1954)\n| WimbledonMixedresult          = QF (1954)\n| USOpenMixedresult             =\n |Team                          = yes\n| DavisCupresult                = '''W''' ([[1953 Davis Cup|1953]], [[1955 Davis Cup|1955]] )\n}}\n\n'''Rex Noel Hartwig''' (born 2 September 1929) is an Australian former [[tennis]] player.<ref name=\"age1\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=vKwTAAAAIBAJ&sjid=XccDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6917,3281613|title=N.S.W. Tennis Title To Rex Hartwig in Three Sets|last=Harper|first=Jack|date=23 November 1954|work=The Age|publisher=Google News Archive}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nRex Hartwig was born on  2 September 1929 in [[Culcairn, New South Wales]]. Both parents played tennis and at age 10 Hartwig played and won in a local tournament with his father. When he was 13 he began competing in afternoon competitions and took a job managing tennis courts in [[Albury]]. He formed a doubles team with Allan Kendall jr. and the team won the NSW, Victorian and Australian Junior titles.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rex Hartwig|url=http://tennishistory.com.au/2011/03/rex-hartwig/|publisher=Australian Tennis History|date=16 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Allan Kendall: Ace at tennis was smash on children's TV|url=http://www.smh.com.au/comment/obituaries/allan-kendall-ace-at-tennis-was-smash-on-childrens-tv-20140130-31p9a.html|accessdate=January 31, 2014|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|author=Malcolm Brown}}</ref>\n\n==Tennis career==\nHartwig was ranked World No. 5 in both 1954 and 1955 by [[Lance Tingay]] of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''.<ref name=\"USLTAEncyclopedia\"/>\n\n;Wimbledon\nHe won the doubles in [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] twice: In 1954 with [[Mervyn Rose]] and in 1955 with [[Lew Hoad]].<ref name=\"wimbledon1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/roll_of_honour/mens-doubles.html|title=Men's Doubles Finals 1884\u20132008|work=Wimbledon Website|publisher=All England Lawn Tennis Club|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103214301/http://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/roll_of_honour/mens-doubles.html|archivedate=3 November 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"sarasota1\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=PAUdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=w4oEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2216,946696|title=Rex Hartwig Inks Pro Tennis Pact|date=9 November 1955|work=Sarasota Journal|publisher=Google News Archive}}</ref>\n\n;Australian championships\nIn 1953 he also won the doubles with Mervyn Rose and the mixed doubles with [[Julia Sampson Hayward]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article47566482 |title=Rose-Hartwig \"Best In World Doubles\". |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=30 January 1954  |page=11 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In 1954 he again won the mixed doubles title in [[Australian Open|Melbourne]], this time partnering [[Thelma Coyne Long]].<ref name=\"australianopen1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.australianopen.com/en_AU/event_guide/history/men_s_doubles.html|title=Men's Doubles Champions|work=Australian Open|publisher=Tennis Australia|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100310151723/http://www.australianopen.com/en_AU/event_guide/history/men_s_doubles.html|archivedate=10 March 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"australianopen2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.australianopen.com/en_AU/event_guide/history/mixed_doubles.html|title=Mixed Doubles Champions|work=Australian Open|publisher=Tennis Australia|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101012013459/http://www.australianopen.com/en_AU/event_guide/history/mixed_doubles.html|archivedate=12 October 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"spokane1\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=6JkSAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ofYDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5466,925230|title=Hoad Criticized For Tennis Play|date=3 December 1954|work=Spokane Daily Chronicle|publisher=Google News Archive}}</ref>\n\n;US championships\nIn 1953 he won the doubles title at the [[US Open (tennis)|US Championships]] with Mervyn Rose, defeating [[Gardnar Mulloy]] and [[Bill Talbert]] in the final that lasted 77  minutes.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article100380370 |title=Rose, Hartwig Win U.S. Doubles Tennis Title. |newspaper=[[Goulburn Evening Post]] |location=NSW |date=24 August 1953 |page=3 Edition: Daily and Evening |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref name=\"usopen1\">{{cite web|url=http://2009.usopen.org/en_US/about/history/mdchamps.html|title=Champions \u2013  Men's Doubles Championships|work=US Open|publisher=United States Tennis Association}}</ref>\n\nPlaying singles he made the final in 1954 but lost to [[Vic Seixas]].<ref name=\"usopen2\">{{cite web|url=http://2009.usopen.org/en_US/about/history/mschamps.html?=SN|title=Champions \u2013 Men's Singles Championships|work=US Open|publisher=United States Tennis Association}}</ref>\n\n;Davis Cup\nHartwig was member of the [[Australian Davis Cup team]] in 1953, 1954 and 1955. In [[1953 Davis Cup|1953]] he played the doubles match with [[Lew Hoad]] in the [[1953 Davis Cup#Challenge Round|Challenge Round]] against the USA and lost to [[Vic Seixas]] and [[Tony Trabert]]. This would turn out to be Hartwig's only [[Davis Cup]] defeat. In [[1954 Davis Cup|1954]] he defeated Seixas in the Challenge Round that Australia lost to the USA. In [[1955 Davis Cup|1955]] he made a significant contribution towards Australia's Cup win, playing 11 matches in six ties and winning all of them. He compiled a 12\u20131 win\u2013loss record in the Davis Cup (6\u20130 singles, 6\u20131 doubles).<ref name=\"daviscup1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.daviscup.com/en/players/player/profile.aspx?playerid=10003618|title=Rex HARTWIG|work=Davis Cup Official Website|publisher=International Tennis Federation}}</ref><ref name=\"si1\">{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1130160/index.htm|title=Wanted: At Least Three Young Men|last=Talbert|first=William F.|date=5 September 1955|work=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=19 March 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"si2\">{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1129015/index.htm|title=No Year For Kings|last=Talbert|first=William F.|date=20 September 1954|work=Sports Illustrated}}</ref>\n\n;Other tournaments\nIn November 1954 Hartwig won the singles title at the [[Sydney International|New South Wales Championships]] in Sydney. In the final he defeated countryman [[Mervyn Rose]] in three straight sets.<ref>{{cite news|title=N.S.W. Tennis Title To Rex Hartwig In Three Sets|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=vKwTAAAAIBAJ&sjid=XccDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6868%2C3281596|newspaper=The Age|date=Nov 23, 1954}}</ref>\n\n;Professional\nIn November 1955 Hartwig turned professional by signing a contract with tennis promoter [[Jack Kramer]] for a fixed amount of $30,000 plus a percentage of the gate receipts of the professional tour.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rex Hartwig Inks Pro Tennis Pact|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=PAUdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=w4oEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2216%2C946696|newspaper=Sarasota Journal|date=Nov 9, 1955|page=7}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hopman Advised Me \u2013 Rex Hartwig|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=HhsRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=FpUDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5111%2C1452751|newspaper=The Age|date=Nov 10, 1955|page=12}}</ref>\n\n==Playing style==\nHartwig was known for his well-timed groundstrokes and his crisp and accurate volleys. Australian tennis player and coach [[Harry Hopman]] characterized Hartwig as a great stylist.<ref>{{cite web|title=Player Profiles \u2013 Rex Hartwig|url=http://www.tennis.com.au/player-profiles/rex-hartwig|publisher=Tennis Australia}}</ref>\n\n== Grand Slam finals ==\n\n=== Singles (2 runners-up) ===\n\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n!style=\"width:40px\"|Result\n!style=\"width:30px\"|Year\n!style=\"width:165px\"|Championship\n!style=\"width:50px\"|Surface\n!style=\"width:160px\"|Opponent\n!style=\"width:120px\" class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n|- style=\"background:#ffffcc\"\n| style=\"background:#FFA07A\"|Loss || 1954 || [[Australian Open|Australian Championships]] || Grass || {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Mervyn Rose]] || 2\u20136, 6\u20130, 4\u20136, 2\u20136\n|- style=\"background:#ccccff\"\n| style=\"background:#FFA07A\"|Loss || 1954 || [[US Open (tennis)|U.S. Championships]] || Grass || {{flagicon|USA|1912}} [[Vic Seixas]] || 6\u20133, 2\u20136, 4\u20136, 4\u20136\n|}\n\n=== Doubles  (4 titles \u2013 1 runner-up)===\n\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n!style=\"width:40px\"|Result\n!style=\"width:30px\"|Year\n!style=\"width:165px\"|Championship\n!style=\"width:50px\"|Surface\n!style=\"width:160px\"|Partner\n!style=\"width:160px\"|Opponents\n!style=\"width:120px\" class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n|- style=\"background:#ccffcc\"\n| style=\"background:#FFA07A\"|Loss || 1953 || [[Wimbledon Championships]] || Grass || {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Mervyn Rose]] || {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Lew Hoad]] <br/> {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Ken Rosewall]] || 4\u20136, 5\u20137, 6\u20134, 5\u20137\n|- style=\"background:#ccccff\"\n| style=\"background:#98FB98\"|Win || 1953 || [[US Open (tennis)|U.S. Championships]] || Grass || {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Mervyn Rose]] || {{flagicon|USA|1912}} [[Gardnar Mulloy]] <br/> {{flagicon|USA|1912}} [[Bill Talbert]] || 6\u20134, 4\u20136, 6\u20132, 6\u20134\n|- style=\"background:#ffffcc\"\n| style=\"background:#98FB98\"|Win || 1954 || [[Australian Open|Australian Championships]] || Grass || {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Mervyn Rose]] || {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Neale Fraser]] <br/> {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Clive Wilderspin]] || 6\u20133, 6\u20134, 6\u20132\n|- style=\"background:#ccffcc\"\n| style=\"background:#98FB98\"|Win || 1954 || [[Wimbledon Championships]] || Grass || {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Mervyn Rose]] || {{flagicon|USA|1912}} [[Vic Seixas]] <br/> {{flagicon|USA|1912}} [[Tony Trabert]] || 6\u20134, 6\u20134, 3\u20136, 6\u20134\n|- style=\"background:#ccffcc\"\n| style=\"background:#98FB98\"|Win || 1955 || [[Wimbledon Championships]] || Grass || {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Lew Hoad]] || {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Neale Fraser]] <br/> {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Ken Rosewall]] || 7\u20135, 6\u20134, 6\u20133\n|}\n\n=== Mixed doubles (2 titles, 2 runners-up)===\n\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n!style=\"width:40px\"|Result\n!style=\"width:30px\"|Year\n!style=\"width:165px\"|Championship\n!style=\"width:50px\"|Surface\n!style=\"width:160px\"|Partner\n!style=\"width:160px\"|Opponents\n!style=\"width:120px\" class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n|- style=\"background:#ffffcc\"\n| style=\"background:#98FB98\"|Win || 1953 || [[Australian Open|Australian Championships]] || Grass || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Julia Sampson Hayward|Julia Sampson]] || {{flagicon|USA|1912}} [[Maureen Connolly]] <br/> {{flagicon|USA|1912}} [[Ham Richardson]] || 6\u20134, 6\u20133\n|- style=\"background:#ccccff\"\n| style=\"background:#FFA07A\"|Loss || 1953 || [[US Open (tennis)|U.S. Championships]] || Grass || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Julia Sampson Hayward|Julia Sampson]] || {{flagicon|USA|1912}} [[Doris Hart]] <br/> {{flagicon|USA|1912}} [[Vic Seixas]] || 2\u20136, 6\u20134, 4\u20136\n|- style=\"background:#ffffcc\"\n| style=\"background:#98FB98\"|Win || 1954 || [[Australian Open|Australian Championships]] || Grass || {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Thelma Coyne Long]] || {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Beryl Penrose]] <br/> {{flagicon|AUS}} [[John Bromwich]] || 4\u20136, 6\u20131, 6\u20132\n|- style=\"background:#ebc2af\"\n| style=\"background:#FFA07A\"|Loss || 1954 || [[French Open (tennis)|French Championships]] || Clay || {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Jacqueline Patorni]] || {{flagicon|USA|1912}} [[Maureen Connolly]] <br/> {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Lew Hoad]] || 4\u20136, 3\u20136\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{ATP}}\n* {{ITF profile}}\n* {{Davis Cup player}}\n* {{Tennis Australia}}\n* [http://www.britishpathe.com/video/triumph-for-rose-and-hartwig-aka-australia-wins-do British Path\u00e9 filmreel \u2013 1953 US Championships Men's Doubles title]\n\n{{Australian Championships men's doubles champions}}\n{{Wimbledon men's doubles champions}}\n{{U.S. National Championships Men's doubles champions}}\n{{Australian Championships mixed doubles champions}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hartwig, Rex}}\n[[Category:Australian Championships (tennis) champions]]\n[[Category:Australian male tennis players]]\n[[Category:People from the Riverina]]\n[[Category:Tennis people from New South Wales]]\n[[Category:United States National champions (tennis)]]\n[[Category:Wimbledon champions (pre-Open Era)]]\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in mixed doubles]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in men's doubles]]\n[[Category:Professional tennis players before the Open Era]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in boys' doubles]]\n[[Category:Australian Championships (tennis) junior champions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian tennis player}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n| name                          = Rex Hartwig\n| image                         = Rex Hartwig.png\n| image_size                    =\n| caption                       =\n| fullname                      = Rex Noel Hartwig\n| country                       = {{flagu|Australia}}\n| residence                     =\n| birth_date                    = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1929|09|02}}\n| birth_place                   = [[Culcairn, New South Wales]], Australia\n| death_date                    =\n| death_place                   =\n| height                        =\n| turnedpro                     = 1950 (amateur tour)\n| retired                       = 1962\n| plays                         = Right-handed (1-handed backhand)\n| careerprizemoney              =\n| tennishofyear                 =\n| tennishofid                   =\n| singlesrecord                 =\n| singlestitles                 =\n| highestsinglesranking         = No. 5 (1954<small>, [[The Daily Telegraph|Lance Tingay]]</small>)<ref name=\"USLTAEncyclopedia\">United States Lawn Tennis Association (1972). ''Official Encyclopedia of Tennis'' (First Edition), p. 426.</ref>\n| AustralianOpenresult          = F ([[1954 Australian Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1954]])\n| FrenchOpenresult              = 4R ([[1953 French Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1953]], [[1954 French Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1954]])\n| Wimbledonresult               = QF ([[1954 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1954]])\n| USOpenresult                  = F ([[1954 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1954]])\n| Othertournaments              = \n| Olympicssresult               =\n| doublesrecord                 =\n| doublestitles                 =\n| highestdoublesranking         =\n| grandslamsdoublesresults      = \n| AustralianOpenDoublesresult   = '''W''' (1954)\n| FrenchOpenDoublesresult       =\n| WimbledonDoublesresult        = '''W''' (1954, 1955)\n| USOpenDoublesresult           = '''W''' (1953)\n| OthertournamentsDoubles       = \n| OlympicsDoublesresult         = <!-- optional -->\n| Mixed                         = <!-- optional, adds mixed information-->\n| mixedtitles                   =\n| mixedrecord                   =\n| highestmixedranking           =\n| AustralianOpenMixedresult     = '''W''' (1953, 1954)\n| FrenchOpenMixedresult         = F (1954)\n| WimbledonMixedresult          = QF (1954)\n| USOpenMixedresult             =\n |Team                          = yes\n| DavisCupresult                = '''W''' ([[1953 Davis Cup|1953]], [[1955 Davis Cup|1955]] )\n}}\n\n'''Rex Noel Hartwig''' (born 2 September 1929) is an Australian former [[tennis]] player.<ref name=\"age1\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=vKwTAAAAIBAJ&sjid=XccDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6917,3281613|title=N.S.W. Tennis Title To Rex Hartwig in Three Sets|last=Harper|first=Jack|date=23 November 1954|work=The Age|publisher=Google News Archive}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nRex Hartwig was born on  2 September 1929 in [[Culcairn, New South Wales]]. Both parents played tennis and at age 10 Hartwig played and won in a local tournament with his father. When he was 13 he began competing in afternoon competitions and took a job managing tennis courts in [[Albury]]. He formed a doubles team with Allan Kendall jr. and the team won the NSW, Victorian and Australian Junior titles.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rex Hartwig|url=http://tennishistory.com.au/2011/03/rex-hartwig/|publisher=Australian Tennis History|date=16 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Allan Kendall: Ace at tennis was smash on children's TV|url=http://www.smh.com.au/comment/obituaries/allan-kendall-ace-at-tennis-was-smash-on-childrens-tv-20140130-31p9a.html|accessdate=January 31, 2014|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|author=Malcolm Brown}}</ref>\n\n==Tennis career==\nHartwig was ranked World No. 5 in both 1954 and 1955 by [[Lance Tingay]] of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''.<ref name=\"USLTAEncyclopedia\"/>\n\n;Wimbledon\nHe won the doubles in [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] twice: In 1954 with [[Mervyn Rose]] and in 1955 with [[Lew Hoad]].<ref name=\"wimbledon1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/roll_of_honour/mens-doubles.html|title=Men's Doubles Finals 1884\u20132008|work=Wimbledon Website|publisher=All England Lawn Tennis Club|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103214301/http://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/roll_of_honour/mens-doubles.html|archivedate=3 November 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"sarasota1\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=PAUdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=w4oEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2216,946696|title=Rex Hartwig Inks Pro Tennis Pact|date=9 November 1955|work=Sarasota Journal|publisher=Google News Archive}}</ref>\n\n;Australian championships\nIn 1953 he also won the doubles with Mervyn Rose and the mixed doubles with [[Julia Sampson Hayward]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article47566482 |title=Rose-Hartwig \"Best In World Doubles\". |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=30 January 1954  |page=11 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In 1954 he again won the mixed doubles title in [[Australian Open|Melbourne]], this time partnering [[Thelma Coyne Long]].<ref name=\"australianopen1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.australianopen.com/en_AU/event_guide/history/men_s_doubles.html|title=Men's Doubles Champions|work=Australian Open|publisher=Tennis Australia|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100310151723/http://www.australianopen.com/en_AU/event_guide/history/men_s_doubles.html|archivedate=10 March 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"australianopen2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.australianopen.com/en_AU/event_guide/history/mixed_doubles.html|title=Mixed Doubles Champions|work=Australian Open|publisher=Tennis Australia|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101012013459/http://www.australianopen.com/en_AU/event_guide/history/mixed_doubles.html|archivedate=12 October 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"spokane1\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=6JkSAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ofYDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5466,925230|title=Hoad Criticized For Tennis Play|date=3 December 1954|work=Spokane Daily Chronicle|publisher=Google News Archive}}</ref>\n\n;US championships\nIn 1953 he won the doubles title at the [[US Open (tennis)|US Championships]] with Mervyn Rose, defeating [[Gardnar Mulloy]] and [[Bill Talbert]] in the final that lasted 77  minutes.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article100380370 |title=Rose, Hartwig Win U.S. Doubles Tennis Title. |newspaper=[[Goulburn Evening Post]] |location=NSW |date=24 August 1953 |page=3 Edition: Daily and Evening |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref name=\"usopen1\">{{cite web|url=http://2009.usopen.org/en_US/about/history/mdchamps.html|title=Champions \u2013  Men's Doubles Championships|work=US Open|publisher=United States Tennis Association}}</ref>\n\nPlaying singles he made the final in 1954 but lost to [[Vic Seixas]].<ref name=\"usopen2\">{{cite web|url=http://2009.usopen.org/en_US/about/history/mschamps.html?=SN|title=Champions \u2013 Men's Singles Championships|work=US Open|publisher=United States Tennis Association}}</ref>\n\n;Davis Cup\nHartwig was member of the [[Australian Davis Cup team]] in 1953, 1954 and 1955. In [[1953 Davis Cup|1953]] he played the doubles match with [[Lew Hoad]] in the [[1953 Davis Cup#Challenge Round|Challenge Round]] against the USA and lost to [[Vic Seixas]] and [[Tony Trabert]]. This would turn out to be Hartwig's only [[Davis Cup]] defeat. In [[1954 Davis Cup|1954]] he defeated Seixas in the Challenge Round that Australia lost to the USA. In [[1955 Davis Cup|1955]] he made a significant contribution towards Australia's Cup win, playing 11 matches in six ties and winning all of them. He compiled a 12\u20131 win\u2013loss record in the Davis Cup (6\u20130 singles, 6\u20131 doubles).<ref name=\"daviscup1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.daviscup.com/en/players/player/profile.aspx?playerid=10003618|title=Rex HARTWIG|work=Davis Cup Official Website|publisher=International Tennis Federation}}</ref><ref name=\"si1\">{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1130160/index.htm|title=Wanted: At Least Three Young Men|last=Talbert|first=William F.|date=5 September 1955|work=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=19 March 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"si2\">{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1129015/index.htm|title=No Year For Kings|last=Talbert|first=William F.|date=20 September 1954|work=Sports Illustrated}}</ref>\n\n;Other tournaments\nIn November 1954 Hartwig won the singles title at the [[Sydney International|New South Wales Championships]] in Sydney. In the final he defeated countryman [[Mervyn Rose]] in three straight sets.<ref>{{cite news|title=N.S.W. Tennis Title To Rex Hartwig In Three Sets|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=vKwTAAAAIBAJ&sjid=XccDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6868%2C3281596|newspaper=The Age|date=Nov 23, 1954}}</ref>\n\n;Professional\nIn November 1955 Hartwig turned professional by signing a contract with tennis promoter [[Jack Kramer]] for a fixed amount of $30,000 plus a percentage of the gate receipts of the professional tour.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rex Hartwig Inks Pro Tennis Pact|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=PAUdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=w4oEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2216%2C946696|newspaper=Sarasota Journal|date=Nov 9, 1955|page=7}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hopman Advised Me \u2013 Rex Hartwig|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=HhsRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=FpUDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5111%2C1452751|newspaper=The Age|date=Nov 10, 1955|page=12}}</ref>\n\n==Playing style==\nHartwig was known for his well-timed groundstrokes and his crisp and accurate volleys. Australian tennis player and coach [[Harry Hopman]] characterized Hartwig as a great stylist.<ref>{{cite web|title=Player Profiles \u2013 Rex Hartwig|url=http://www.tennis.com.au/player-profiles/rex-hartwig|publisher=Tennis Australia}}</ref>\n\n== Grand Slam finals ==\n\n=== Singles (2 runners-up) ===\n\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n!style=\"width:40px\"|Result\n!style=\"width:30px\"|Year\n!style=\"width:165px\"|Championship\n!style=\"width:50px\"|Surface\n!style=\"width:170px\"|Opponent\n!style=\"width:120px\" class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n|- style=\"background:#ffffcc\"\n| style=\"background:#FFA07A\"|Loss || 1954 || [[Australian Open|Australian Championships]] || Grass || {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Mervyn Rose]] || 2\u20136, 6\u20130, 4\u20136, 2\u20136\n|- style=\"background:#ccccff\"\n| style=\"background:#FFA07A\"|Loss || 1954 || [[US Open (tennis)|U.S. Championships]] || Grass || {{flagicon|USA|1912}} [[Vic Seixas]] || 6\u20133, 2\u20136, 4\u20136, 4\u20136\n|}\n\n=== Doubles  (4 titles \u2013 1 runner-up)===\n\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n!style=\"width:40px\"|Result\n!style=\"width:30px\"|Year\n!style=\"width:165px\"|Championship\n!style=\"width:50px\"|Surface\n!style=\"width:170px\"|Partner\n!style=\"width:170px\"|Opponents\n!style=\"width:120px\" class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n|- style=\"background:#ccffcc\"\n| style=\"background:#FFA07A\"|Loss || 1953 || [[Wimbledon Championships]] || Grass || {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Mervyn Rose]] || {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Lew Hoad]] <br/> {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Ken Rosewall]] || 4\u20136, 5\u20137, 6\u20134, 5\u20137\n|- style=\"background:#ccccff\"\n| style=\"background:#98FB98\"|Win || 1953 || [[US Open (tennis)|U.S. Championships]] || Grass || {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Mervyn Rose]] || {{flagicon|USA|1912}} [[Gardnar Mulloy]] <br/> {{flagicon|USA|1912}} [[Bill Talbert]] || 6\u20134, 4\u20136, 6\u20132, 6\u20134\n|- style=\"background:#ffffcc\"\n| style=\"background:#98FB98\"|Win || 1954 || [[Australian Open|Australian Championships]] || Grass || {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Mervyn Rose]] || {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Neale Fraser]] <br/> {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Clive Wilderspin]] || 6\u20133, 6\u20134, 6\u20132\n|- style=\"background:#ccffcc\"\n| style=\"background:#98FB98\"|Win || 1954 || [[Wimbledon Championships]] || Grass || {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Mervyn Rose]] || {{flagicon|USA|1912}} [[Vic Seixas]] <br/> {{flagicon|USA|1912}} [[Tony Trabert]] || 6\u20134, 6\u20134, 3\u20136, 6\u20134\n|- style=\"background:#ccffcc\"\n| style=\"background:#98FB98\"|Win || 1955 || [[Wimbledon Championships]] || Grass || {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Lew Hoad]] || {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Neale Fraser]] <br/> {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Ken Rosewall]] || 7\u20135, 6\u20134, 6\u20133\n|}\n\n=== Mixed doubles (2 titles, 2 runners-up)===\n\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n!style=\"width:40px\"|Result\n!style=\"width:30px\"|Year\n!style=\"width:165px\"|Championship\n!style=\"width:50px\"|Surface\n!style=\"width:170px\"|Partner\n!style=\"width:170px\"|Opponents\n!style=\"width:120px\" class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n|- style=\"background:#ffffcc\"\n| style=\"background:#98FB98\"|Win || 1953 || [[Australian Open|Australian Championships]] || Grass || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Julia Sampson Hayward|Julia Sampson]] || {{flagicon|USA|1912}} [[Maureen Connolly]] <br/> {{flagicon|USA|1912}} [[Ham Richardson]] || 6\u20134, 6\u20133\n|- style=\"background:#ccccff\"\n| style=\"background:#FFA07A\"|Loss || 1953 || [[US Open (tennis)|U.S. Championships]] || Grass || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Julia Sampson Hayward|Julia Sampson]] || {{flagicon|USA|1912}} [[Doris Hart]] <br/> {{flagicon|USA|1912}} [[Vic Seixas]] || 2\u20136, 6\u20134, 4\u20136\n|- style=\"background:#ffffcc\"\n| style=\"background:#98FB98\"|Win || 1954 || [[Australian Open|Australian Championships]] || Grass || {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Thelma Coyne Long]] || {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Beryl Penrose]] <br/> {{flagicon|AUS}} [[John Bromwich]] || 4\u20136, 6\u20131, 6\u20132\n|- style=\"background:#ebc2af\"\n| style=\"background:#FFA07A\"|Loss || 1954 || [[French Open (tennis)|French Championships]] || Clay || {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Jacqueline Patorni]] || {{flagicon|USA|1912}} [[Maureen Connolly]] <br/> {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Lew Hoad]] || 4\u20136, 3\u20136\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{ATP}}\n* {{ITF profile}}\n* {{Davis Cup player}}\n* {{Tennis Australia}}\n* [http://www.britishpathe.com/video/triumph-for-rose-and-hartwig-aka-australia-wins-do British Path\u00e9 filmreel \u2013 1953 US Championships Men's Doubles title]\n\n{{Australian Championships men's doubles champions}}\n{{Wimbledon men's doubles champions}}\n{{U.S. National Ch