{"title_page": "Shabib ibn Yazid al-Shaybani", "text_new": "'''Shab\u012bb ibn Yaz\u012bd ibn Nu\u02bfaym al-Shayb\u0101n\u012b''' (646/47 \u2013 697/98) was the leader of [[Khwarij|Kharijite]] rebellion against the [[Umayyad Caliphate]] in central [[Iraq (region)|Iraq]] between 696 and his death in 697/98.\n\n==Life==\n===Origins and early career===\nShabib was born in September/October of 646 or 647.<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\">Zettersteen, p. 164.</ref> He was the son of a certain [[Kufa]]n emigrant to [[Mosul]], Yazid ibn Nu'aym. They hailed from the [[Banu Shayban]] tribe, specifically the clan of Banu Hammam ibn Murra ibn Dhuhl.<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\"/> Yazid participated in the frontier raids against the [[Byzantine Empire]] under the command of [[Salman ibn Rabiah|Salman ibn Rabi'a al-Bahili]].<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\"/> During one of the raids, he gained a wife who bore him Shabib. The latter was apparently raised in Mosul or the nearby village of Satidama.<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\"/> He fought against the [[Kurds]] of the region as a member of the Muslim army, and for a time received a regular stipend, which was later terminated during the reign of Caliph [[Abd al-Malik ibn Marwan|Abd al-Malik]] ({{reign|685|705}}) because he did not respond to a call to arms.<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\"/>\n\n===Revolt===\nThere is little information about the Kharijite beliefs of Shabib, but his revolt against the Umayyads, who had reasserted control over [[Iraq (region)|Iraq]] in 691, was the object of fascination for medieval Muslim and Christian historians, which depict him as a \"fearless [[guerrilla]] leader\", according to the modern historian [[Karl Vilhelm Zetterst\u00e9en]].<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\"/> Though other early Muslim sources dispute it, the account of [[Abu Mikhnaf]] holds that Shabib began his career with the Kharijites as a soldier in the army of the Kharijite ascetic Salih ibn Musarrih, and succeeded him when the latter was slain at the village of al-Muddabaj in September 695.<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\"/> \n\nShabib led the remnants of Ibn Musarrih's army, which mostly consisted of Banu Shayban tribesmen, through Mosul and central Iraq, defeating Umayyad forces at [[Nahrawan]] and [[Khanaqin]] before attacking Kufa with 200 of his fighters.<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\"/> Afterward, in March 696, he landed blows against the Umayyad generals Za'ida ibn Qudama and Uthman ibn Qatan al-Harithi at the villages of Rudhbar and al-Batt, both located along the southern edge of the [[Nineveh plains|Mosul plains]].<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\"/> In mid-696, after three months of back-and-forth fighting, Shabib and 600 of his men took over [[al-Mada'in]] in central Iraq, defeating [[Attab ibn Warqa al-Riyahi]].<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\"/> At this point, the Kharijites threatened Kufa, one of the main garrison centers of Iraq.<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\"/> However, a thousands-strong Syrian army under [[Sufyan ibn al-Abrad al-Kalbi]] was deployed and decisively defeated Shabib outside of the city.<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\"/> Shabib withdrew and fought a skirmish in [[Anbar (town)|Anbar]], before proceeding with the remainder of his men through [[Jukha]], [[Kirman]] and [[Ahwaz]]. As he attempted to escape his Syrian pursuers, he drowned in the [[Dujayl Canal]] while trying to cross it.<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\"/> This occurred either in early 697 or in 697/98, depending on the source.<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\nShabib's son, Suhari, later launched a rebellion against the Umayyad governor of Iraq, [[Khalid al-Qasri]], in 737 and Kharijite risings in [[Upper Mesopotamia]] and the environs of Mosul continued intermittently throughout the Umayyad and early [[Abbasid Caliphate|Abbasid]] period.<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{EI2 |article=Shab\u012bb ibn Yaz\u012bd |last=Zetterst\u00e9en |first=K. V. |authorlink=Karl Vilhelm Zetterst\u00e9en |volume=9 |pages=164\u2013165}}\n\n[[Category:646 births]]\n[[Category:697 deaths]]\n[[Category:Banu Shayban]]\n[[Category:Iraq under the Umayyad Caliphate]]\n[[Category:Kharijites]]\n[[Category:People from Mosul]]\n[[Category:Rebellions against the Umayyad Caliphate]]\n[[Category:7th-century Arabs]]\n", "text_old": "'''Shab\u012bb ibn Yaz\u012bd ibn Nu\u02bfaym al-Shayb\u0101n\u012b''' (646/47 \u2013 697/98) was the leader of [[Khwarij|Kharijite]] rebellion against the [[Umayyad Caliphate]] in central [[Iraq (region)|Iraq]] between 696 and his death in 697/98.\n\n==Life==\n===Origins and early career===\nShabib was born in September/October of 646 or 647.<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\">Zettersteen, p. 164.</ref> He was the son of a certain [[Kufa]]n emigrant to [[Mosul]], Yazid ibn Nu'aym. They hailed from the [[Banu Shayban]] tribe, specifically the clan of Banu Hammam ibn Murra ibn Dhuhl.<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\"/> Yazid participated in the frontier raids against the [[Byzantine Empire]] under the command of [[Salman ibn Rabiah|Salman ibn Rabi'a al-Bahili]].<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\"/> During one of the raids, he gained a wife who bore him Shabib. The latter was apparently raised in Mosul or the nearby village of Satidama.<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\"/> He fought against the [[Kurds]] of the region as a member of the Muslim army, and for a time received a regular stipend, which was later terminated during the reign of Caliph [[Abd al-Malik ibn Marwan|Abd al-Malik]] ({{reign|685|705}}) because he did not respond to a call to arms.<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\"/>\n\n===Revolt===\nThere is little information about the Kharijite beliefs of Shabib, but his revolt against the Umayyads, who had reasserted control over [[Iraq (region)|Iraq]] in 691, was the object of fascination for medieval Muslim and Christian historians, which depict him as a \"fearless [[guerrilla]] leader\", according to the modern historian [[Karl Vilhelm Zetterst\u00e9en]].<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\"/> Though other early Muslim sources dispute it, the account of [[Abu Mikhnaf]] holds that Shabib began his career with the Kharijites as a soldier in the army of the Kharijite ascetic Salih ibn Musarrih, and succeeded him when the latter was slain at the village of al-Muddabaj in September 695.<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\"/> \n\nShabib led the remnants of Ibn Musarrih's army, which mostly consisted of Banu Shayban tribesmen, through Mosul and central Iraq, defeating Umayyad forces at [[Nahrawan]] and [[Khanaqin]] before attacking Kufa with 200 of his fighters.<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\"/> Afterward, in March 696, he landed blows against the Umayyad generals Za'ida ibn Qudama and Uthman ibn Qatan al-Harithi at the villages of Rudhbar and al-Batt, both located along the southern edge of the [[Nineveh plains|Mosul plains]].<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\"/> In mid-696, after three months of back-and-forth fighting, Shabib and 600 of his men took over [[al-Mada'in]] in central Iraq, defeating [[Attab ibn Warqa al-Riyahi]].<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\"/> At this point, the Kharijites threatened Kufa, one of the maingarrison centers of Iraq.<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\"/> However, a thousands-strong Syrian army under [[Sufyan ibn al-Abrad al-Kalbi]] was deployed and decisively defeated Shabib outside of the city.<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\"/> Shabib withdrew and fought a skirmish in [[Anbar (town)|Anbar]], before proceeding with the remainder of his men through [[Jukha]], [[Kirman]] and [[Ahwaz]]. As he attempted to escape his Syrian pursuers, he drowned in the [[Dujayl Canal]] while trying to cross it.<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\"/> This occurred either in early 697 or in 697/98, depending on the source.<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\nShabib's son, Suhari, later launched a rebellion against the Umayyad governor of Iraq, [[Khalid al-Qasri]], in 737 and Kharijite risings in [[Upper Mesopotamia]] and the environs of Mosul continued intermittently throughout the Umayyad and early [[Abbasid Caliphate|Abbasid]] period.<ref name=\"Zettersteen164\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{EI2 |article=Shab\u012bb ibn Yaz\u012bd |last=Zetterst\u00e9en |first=K. V. |authorlink=Karl Vilhelm Zetterst\u00e9en |volume=9 |pages=164\u2013165}}\n\n[[Category:646 births]]\n[[Category:697 deaths]]\n[[Category:Banu Shayban]]\n[[Category:Iraq under the Umayyad Caliphate]]\n[[Category:Kharijites]]\n[[Category:People from Mosul]]\n[[Category:Rebellions against the Umayyad Caliphate]]\n[[Category:7th-century Arabs]]\n", "name_user": "AhmadLX", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRevolt:+space", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shabib_ibn_Yazid_al-Shaybani"}
{"title_page": "Jordan Love", "text_new": "{{short description|American football quarterback}}\n<!-- DO NOT ADD BEFORE THE 2020 NFL DRAFT\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name                = Jordan Love\n| alt                 = \n| number              = --\n| current_team        = \n| position            = [[Quarterback]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1998|11|02}}\n| birth_place         = [[Bakersfield, California]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| height_ft           = 6\n| height_in           = 4\n| weight_lb           = 225\n| high_school         = [[Liberty High School (Bakersfield, California)|Liberty]] (Bakersfield, California)\n| college             = [[Utah State Aggies football|Utah State]]\n| draftyear           = 2020\n| draftround          = \n| draftpick           = \n| undraftedyear       = \n| pastteams           = \n* [[]] ({{NFL Year|2020}}\u2013present)\n| status              = Unsigned draft pick\n| highlights          = \n*Second-team All-MWC (2018)\n*New Mexico Bowl MVP ([[2018 New Mexico Bowl|2018]])\n| statleague          = NFL\n| statseason          = \n| statweek            = \n| statlabel1          = \n| statvalue1          = \n| statlabel2          = \n| statvalue2          = \n| statlabel3          = \n| statvalue3          = \n| nflnew              = \n| pfr                 = \n}}\n-->\n{{Infobox college football player\n|name=Jordan Love\n|school=Utah State Aggies\n|currentnumber=10\n|currentposition=[[Quarterback]]\n|bowlgames=\n*[[2018 New Mexico Bowl]]\n*[[2020 Senior Bowl]]\n|class={{redshirt}} Junior\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1998|11|2}}\n|birth_place=[[Bakersfield, California]]\n|heightft=6\n|heightin=4\n|weight_lb=225\n|highlights=\n*Second-team All-MWC (2018)\n*New Mexico Bowl MVP ([[2018 New Mexico Bowl|2018]])\n|highschool=[[Liberty High School (Bakersfield, California)|Liberty]] (Bakersfield, California)\n|major=Human Movement Science\n|pastschools=\n*[[Utah State Aggies football|Utah State]] (2016\u20132019)\n|espn=4036378\n}}\n\n'''Jordan Love''' (born November 2, 1998) is an [[American football]] [[quarterback]]. He played college football for the [[Utah State Aggies football|Utah State Aggies]].\n\n==Early years==\nJordan Love was born in [[Bakersfield, California]] on November 2, 1998. At the age of 14, Love's father, Orbin committed suicide.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jordan Love fulfilling his late father's vision |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001101587/article/utah-states-jordan-love-fulfilling-his-late-fathers-vision |publisher=NFL |accessdate=February 10, 2020}}</ref> Love attended [[Liberty High School (Bakersfield, California)|Liberty High School]]. As a senior, he passed for 2,148 yards and 24 [[touchdowns]] and rushed for 806 yards with eight touchdowns. After being told he could not play quarterback as a freshman, Love was named the starter by his senior year. He committed to play college football at [[Utah State University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cachevalleydaily.com/news/archive/2015/06/23/161ccb22-192b-11e5-bf8c-43d84855b203/|title=\"Dual-threat\" quarterback from California commits to USU|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nLove redshirted his first year at Utah State in 2016. As a redshirt freshman in 2017, he played in 12 games and started the final six.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bakersfield.com/sports/transformed-and-recharged-jordan-love-takes-off-as-freshman-qb/article_92f1e2e4-e5d0-11e7-821f-effdc3faa0bd.html|title=Transformed and recharged, Jordan Love takes off as freshman QB at Utah State|first=TREVOR HORN|last=thorn@bakersfield.com|website=The Bakersfield Californian}}</ref> He finished the season, completing 129 of 235 passes for 1,631 yards, eight touchdowns and six interceptions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900022375/utah-state-position-breakdown-jordan-love-looks-to-make-strides-as-undisputed-starting-qb.html|title=Utah State position breakdown: Jordan Love looks to make strides as undisputed starting QB|first=Lafe|last=Peavler|date=21 June 2018|website=DeseretNews.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900027319/utah-state-qb-jordan-love-a-completely-different-guy-headed-into-2018-season.html|title=Utah State QB Jordan Love a 'completely different guy' heading into 2018 season|first=Lafe|last=Peavler|date=8 August 2018|website=DeseretNews.com}}</ref> As a sophomore in 2018, Love started all 13 games, completing 267 of 417 passes for a school season record 3,567 yards with 32 touchdowns and six interceptions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900048926/usu-football-jordan-love-and-david-woodward-named-to-2019-touchdown-club-of-columbus-players-to-watch-list.html|title=USU football: Jordan Love and David Woodward named to 2019 Touchdown Club of Columbus Players to Watch List|date=3 January 2019|website=DeseretNews.com}}</ref> He was named the MVP of the [[2018 New Mexico Bowl]] after passing for 359 yards and four touchdowns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bakersfield.com/sports/bvarsity/liberty-graduate-leads-utah-state-to-blowout-bowl-win/article_33acd7ae-00c2-11e9-91a4-9bcb24e40661.html|title=Liberty graduate leads Utah State to blowout bowl win|first=STAFF AND WIRE|last=REPORT|website=The Bakersfield Californian}}</ref> Following the season's end, Love announced that he would forgo his senior year by declaring for the [[2020 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/28270139/utah-state-qb-jordan-love-declares-nfl-draft.html. |title=Utah State QB Jordan Love declares for NFL draft |date=December 10, 2019 |newspaper=ESPN |access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n{{NFL predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 3\u00be\n|       weight = 224\n|         dash = 4.74\n|    ten split =\n| twenty split =\n|      shuttle = 4.52\n|   cone drill = 7.21\n|     vertical = 35.5\n|     broad ft = 9\n|     broad in = 10\n|        bench =\n|     arm span = 32\u215d\n|    hand span = 10\u00bd\n|    wonderlic =\n|         note = All values from NFL Combine<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nfl.com/prospects/jordan-love?id=32194c4f-5613-0776-be4c-ce231b05c522 |title=Jordan Love Combine Profile |website=NFL.com |access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref> \n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Twitter}}\n*[https://utahstateaggies.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=3437 Utah State Aggies bio]\n\n{{Utah State Aggies quarterback navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Love, Jordan}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Bakersfield, California]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from California]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:Utah State Aggies football players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football quarterback}}\n<!-- DO NOT ADD BEFORE THE 2020 NFL DRAFT\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name                = Jordan Love\n| alt                 = \n| number              = --\n| current_team        = \n| position            = [[Quarterback]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1998|11|02}}\n| birth_place         = [[Bakersfield, California]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| height_ft           = 6\n| height_in           = 4\n| weight_lb           = 225\n| high_school         = [[Liberty High School (Bakersfield, California)|Liberty]] (Bakersfield, California)\n| college             = [[Utah State Aggies football|Utah State]]\n| draftyear           = 2020\n| draftround          = \n| draftpick           = \n| undraftedyear       = \n| pastteams           = \n* [[]] ({{NFL Year|2020}}\u2013present)\n| status              = Unsigned draft pick\n| highlights          = \n*Second-team All-MWC (2018)\n*New Mexico Bowl MVP ([[2018 New Mexico Bowl|2018]])\n| statleague          = NFL\n| statseason          = \n| statweek            = \n| statlabel1          = \n| statvalue1          = \n| statlabel2          = \n| statvalue2          = \n| statlabel3          = \n| statvalue3          = \n| nflnew              = \n| pfr                 = \n}}\n-->\n{{Infobox college football player\n|name=Jordan Love\n|school=Utah State Aggies\n|currentnumber=10\n|currentposition=[[Quarterback]]\n|bowlgames=\n*[[2018 New Mexico Bowl]]\n*[[2020 Senior Bowl]]\n|class={{redshirt}} Junior\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1998|11|2}}\n|birth_place=[[Bakersfield, California]]\n|heightft=6\n|heightin=4\n|weight_lb=225\n|highlights=\n*Second-team All-MWC (2018)\n*New Mexico Bowl MVP ([[2018 New Mexico Bowl|2018]])\n|highschool=[[Liberty High School (Bakersfield, California)|Liberty]] (Bakersfield, California)\n|major=Human Movement Science\n|pastschools=\n*[[Utah State Aggies football|Utah State]] (2016\u20132019)\n|espn=4036378\n}}\n\n'''Jordan Love''' (born November 2, 1998) is an [[American football]] [[quarterback]]. He played college foortball for the [[Utah State Aggies football|Utah State Aggies]].\n\n==Early years==\nJordan Love was born in [[Bakersfield, California]] on November 2, 1998. At the age of 14, Love's father, Orbin committed suicide.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jordan Love fulfilling his late father's vision |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001101587/article/utah-states-jordan-love-fulfilling-his-late-fathers-vision |publisher=NFL |accessdate=February 10, 2020}}</ref> Love attended [[Liberty High School (Bakersfield, California)|Liberty High School]]. As a senior, he passed for 2,148 yards and 24 [[touchdowns]] and rushed for 806 yards with eight touchdowns. After being told he could not play quarterback as a freshman, Love was named the starter by his senior year. He committed to play college football at [[Utah State University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cachevalleydaily.com/news/archive/2015/06/23/161ccb22-192b-11e5-bf8c-43d84855b203/|title=\"Dual-threat\" quarterback from California commits to USU|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nLove redshirted his first year at Utah State in 2016. As a redshirt freshman in 2017, he played in 12 games and started the final six.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bakersfield.com/sports/transformed-and-recharged-jordan-love-takes-off-as-freshman-qb/article_92f1e2e4-e5d0-11e7-821f-effdc3faa0bd.html|title=Transformed and recharged, Jordan Love takes off as freshman QB at Utah State|first=TREVOR HORN|last=thorn@bakersfield.com|website=The Bakersfield Californian}}</ref> He finished the season, completing 129 of 235 passes for 1,631 yards, eight touchdowns and six interceptions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900022375/utah-state-position-breakdown-jordan-love-looks-to-make-strides-as-undisputed-starting-qb.html|title=Utah State position breakdown: Jordan Love looks to make strides as undisputed starting QB|first=Lafe|last=Peavler|date=21 June 2018|website=DeseretNews.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900027319/utah-state-qb-jordan-love-a-completely-different-guy-headed-into-2018-season.html|title=Utah State QB Jordan Love a 'completely different guy' heading into 2018 season|first=Lafe|last=Peavler|date=8 August 2018|website=DeseretNews.com}}</ref> As a sophomore in 2018, Love started all 13 games, completing 267 of 417 passes for a school season record 3,567 yards with 32 touchdowns and six interceptions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900048926/usu-football-jordan-love-and-david-woodward-named-to-2019-touchdown-club-of-columbus-players-to-watch-list.html|title=USU football: Jordan Love and David Woodward named to 2019 Touchdown Club of Columbus Players to Watch List|date=3 January 2019|website=DeseretNews.com}}</ref> He was named the MVP of the [[2018 New Mexico Bowl]] after passing for 359 yards and four touchdowns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bakersfield.com/sports/bvarsity/liberty-graduate-leads-utah-state-to-blowout-bowl-win/article_33acd7ae-00c2-11e9-91a4-9bcb24e40661.html|title=Liberty graduate leads Utah State to blowout bowl win|first=STAFF AND WIRE|last=REPORT|website=The Bakersfield Californian}}</ref> Following the season's end, Love announced that he would forgo his senior year by declaring for the [[2020 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/28270139/utah-state-qb-jordan-love-declares-nfl-draft.html. |title=Utah State QB Jordan Love declares for NFL draft |date=December 10, 2019 |newspaper=ESPN |access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n{{NFL predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 3\u00be\n|       weight = 224\n|         dash = 4.74\n|    ten split =\n| twenty split =\n|      shuttle = 4.52\n|   cone drill = 7.21\n|     vertical = 35.5\n|     broad ft = 9\n|     broad in = 10\n|        bench =\n|     arm span = 32\u215d\n|    hand span = 10\u00bd\n|    wonderlic =\n|         note = All values from NFL Combine<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nfl.com/prospects/jordan-love?id=32194c4f-5613-0776-be4c-ce231b05c522 |title=Jordan Love Combine Profile |website=NFL.com |access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref> \n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Twitter}}\n*[https://utahstateaggies.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=3437 Utah State Aggies bio]\n\n{{Utah State Aggies quarterback navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Love, Jordan}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Bakersfield, California]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from California]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:Utah State Aggies football players]]\n", "name_user": "Dissident93", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jordan_Love"}
{"title_page": "1881 Men's Tennis tour", "text_new": "{{ Infobox tennis circuit season\n<!-- Details -->\n| name          = 1881 Men's Tennis tour\n| image         = William Charles Renshaw.jpg\n| image_caption = William Renshaw won most titles this year\n| image_alt     = \n| image_size    = 200px\n| duration      = 23 May \u2013 10 November\n| edition       = 5th\n| tournaments   = 32 (Amateur)\n| categories    = important (5 )<br/>  national (2) <br/> regional/state (10) <br/> county (5) <br/> local (10)\n<!-- Achievements -->\n| most_tournament_titles       = {{flagicon|ENG}} [[William Renshaw]] (4)\n| most_tournament_finals       = {{flagicon|ENG}} [[William Renshaw]] (4)\n| prize_money_leader           = \n| points_leader                = \n<!-- Awards -->\n| player_of_the_year            = \n| most_improved_player_of_the_year = \n| newcomer_of_the_year             = \n| comeback_player_of_the_year      = \n| previous = [[1880 Men's Tennis tour|1880]]\n| next     = [[1882 Men's Tennis tour|1882]]\n}}\nThe '''1881 Men's tennis tour''' <ref>{{cite web|title=Tennis season 1881|url=https://app.thetennisbase.com/?enlace=season&anno=1881&tipoMainTorneos=main&surface=&tipo_de_torneo=|website=thetennisbase.com|publisher=The Tennis Base, 2016|accessdate=9 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Archives|first1=Tennis|title=Tournaments 1881|url=http://www.tennisarchives.com/jaarwedstrijdenfiche.php|website=www.tennisarchives.com|publisher=Tennis Archives, 2016|accessdate=9 December 2016}}</ref> was composed of the fifth annual pre-open era tour now incorporated 32 tournaments staged in [[Australia]], [[Canada]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|Great Britain and Ireland]], and the [[United States]]. The [[1881 Wimbledon Championships]] was won by [[William Renshaw]]. This year also saw the inaugural and important [[1881 U.S. National Championships (tennis)|1881 U.S. National Championships]] held at [[Newport Casino]] which [[Richard Sears (tennis)|Richard Sears]] had won.  This was also the year that the [[USTA|United States National Lawn Tennis Association]],<ref>{{cite web|title=USTA HISTORY ARCHIVE|url=https://www.usta.com/About-USTA/Organization/History/USTA_history_archive/|website=usta.com|publisher=USTA|accessdate=17 July 2016}}</ref> which is the world's first national tennis association, was founded. Renshaw then had won two other big tournaments of the year picking up the [[Irish Open (tennis)|Irish Lawn Tennis Championships]] and [[Princes Club Championships]], whilst Richard Taswell Richardson wins the prestigious [[Manchester Open|Northern Championships]].<ref name=\"sports_around_world\">{{cite book |first1=John |last1=Nauright |first2=Charles |last2=Parrish|title=Sports around the world  : history, culture, and practice|date=2012|publisher=ABC-CLIO|location=Santa Barbara, Calif.|isbn=9781598843002|page=198}}</ref>\n\n==Calendar==\n'''Notes 1:''' Challenge Round: the final round of a tournament, in which the winner of a single-elimination phase faces the previous year's champion, who plays only that one match. The challenge round was used in the early history of tennis (from 1877 through 1921),<ref>{{cite web|title=Abolition of Challenge Rounds|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/EP19220320.2.111.2?query=Paris%20International%20Championships|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|publisher=EVENING POST, VOLUME CIII, ISSUE 65, 20 MARCH 1922|accessdate=6 October 2016}}</ref> in some tournaments not all.<center>* Indicates challenger</center>\n'''Notes 2''':''Tournaments in italics were events that were staged only onetime''\n\n===Key===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ffc;\"\n| '''Important tournaments''' <ref>{{cite book|last1=Mazak|first1=Karoly|title=The Concise History of Tennis, The complete tennis history from 1877|date=2016|publisher=Karoly  Mazak|pages=5\u201311|edition=6th|url=http://www.theconcisehistoryoftennis.com/|accessdate=9 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Nauright|first1=John|last2=Parrish|first2=Charles|title=Sports Around the World: History, Culture, and Practice|date=2012|publisher=ABC-CLIO|location=Santa Barbara, Calif.|isbn=9781598843002|page=198|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IkLYDgTnMxEC&pg=RA1-PA198}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Gillmeister|first1=Heiner|title=Tennis:Cultural History|date=1998|publisher=A&C Black|location=London|isbn=9780718501952|page=199|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=44Vu3DdHFvsC&pg=PA199}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Mazak|first1=Karoly|title=The Concise History of Tennis {{!}} The complete tennis history from 1877|date=2010|publisher=Karoly Mazak (Ph.D.)|page=3|edition=6th|url=http://www.theconcisehistoryoftennis.com/}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Lake|first1=Robert J.|title=A Social History of Tennis in Britain: Volume 5 of Routledge Research in Sports History|date=2014|publisher=Routledge |isbn=9781134445578|page=48|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8kyvBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA41}}</ref>\n|- style=\"background:#d0f0c0\"\n| National tournaments\n|- style=\"background:#dfe2e9\"\n| State Regional tournaments\n|- style=\"background:#fae7b5\"\n| County tournaments\n|-\n| Local tournaments\n|}\n\n===January to April===\n''No events''\n\n===May===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:85%;\" \n|-\n!width=\"75\"|Date\n!width=\"230\"|Tournament\n!width=\"210\"|Winner\n!width=\"210\"|All Comers' Finalist\n!width=\"170\"|Semifinalist\n!width=\"170\"|Quarterfinalist\n|-valign=top\n|rowspan=2| 23\u201329 May||style=\"background:#ffc;\" rowspan=2|'''[[Irish Lawn Tennis Championships]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Irish Championships 1881|url=http://www.tennisarchives.com/voorloopfiche.php?wedstrijdvoorloopid=511|website=tennisarchives.com|publisher=Tennis Archives|accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref><br />[[Dublin]], [[Ireland]]<br />Outdoor<br />Grass<br />[[Irish Lawn Tennis Championships|Singles]] - [[1881 Irish Lawn Tennis Championships|Doubles]]''' ||{{Flagicon|GBR}} [[William Renshaw]]<br /