\n[[Category:Films shot at Elstree Studios]]\n[[Category:Lucasfilm films|Star Wars Episode 6]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by John Williams]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Richard Marquand]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Howard Kazanjian]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by George Lucas]]\n[[Category:Guerrilla warfare in film]]\n", "name_user": "Brainulator9", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHome media:MOS compliance", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Return_of_the_Jedi"}
{"title_page": "Alma College (St. Thomas, Ontario)", "text_new": "{{coord|42.773315|N|81.190869|W|display=title}}\n{{Infobox historical event\n  |Event_Name     = '''Alma College'''\n  |Image_Name     = Alma_2006.JPG\n  |Image_Caption  = Romanesque style School designed by [[James Balfour (architect)|James Balfour]] 1877, destroyed by fire in 2008\n  |Location       = [[St. Thomas, Ontario]] \n  |Date           = Fire on May 28th 2008\n  |Result         = Destroyed by arson \n  |URL            = [http://www.almacollege.20m.com/index.html Alumnae home page]\n}}\n\n'''Alma College''' was a girls' private school in [[St. Thomas, Ontario]] in [[Canada]]. Built in 1878, the school was in operation between 1881 and 1988. The college closed in 1988 in part due to a teacher's strike.<ref name=\"Heikkila\">{{cite web|url=http://www.osstf.on.ca/Default.aspx?DN=f21c5ad8-5c6b-4827-abb8-707882d5e17b |title=Alma College: A chapter in OSSTF/FEESO History Goes up in Flames |last=Heikkila |first=Rod |date=Fall 2008 |publisher=OSSTF/FEESO |accessdate=February 23, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090313034816/http://www.osstf.on.ca/Default.aspx?DN=f21c5ad8-5c6b-4827-abb8-707882d5e17b |archivedate=13 March 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Primary school and music classes were still taught on campus until 1994.<ref name=\"Alma\">{{cite web|url=http://www.almacollege.20m.com/clippings/chronology.htm|title=History of Alma College|last=Daniszewski|first=Hank|date=January 2003|publisher=Alma College International Alumnae Association|accessdate=February 23, 2009}}</ref> Following its closure the school building was used as a set for several movie productions; ''[[Silent Hill (film)|Silent Hill]]'' (interior shots), its image is included in the 2009 film ''[[Orphan (2009 film)|Orphan]]''<ref name=\"stthomastimesjournal.com\">{{cite web |url=http://stthomastimesjournal.com/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=1640616 |title=Headlines: Not necessarily a bad thing . . . |publisher=St. Thomas Times-Journal |date=2009-07-04 |accessdate=2013-10-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120420224351/http://www.stthomastimesjournal.com/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=1640616 |archive-date=2012-04-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and the made-for-TV movie, ''Mr. Headmistress'' (1997).<ref name=\"Alma\" /> The building was destroyed by a fire on May 28, 2008.<ref name=\"Heikkila\" />\n\n== History (1877\u20131996) ==\n[[File:Governor General Roland Michener at Alma College graduation ceremonies 1972.jpg|thumb|Governor General [[Roland Michener]] attending the Alma College graduation ceremonies in 1972]]\nWith the economic boom of St. Thomas in the late 19th century, Bishop Albert Carmen proposed that a ladies' college be established. The school name derives from the late Alma Munro (Moore) (wife of then Sheriff Colin Munroe) and Mrs. Alma Munro Duffield, daughter of Colin and Alma.<ref name=\"Lechniak\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hauntedhamilton.com/31_article_almacollege.html |title=The History and Hauntings of Alma Ladies College |last=Lechniak-Cumerlato |first=Stephanie |publisher=hauntedhamilton.com |accessdate=March 19, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090704120808/http://www.hauntedhamilton.com/31_article_almacollege.html |archivedate=July 4, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nAlma college was officially opened in 1881 as a liberal arts college for women, teaching literature, arts and music.<ref name=\"Elgin\" /> By 1883, it had 165 students.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Alma Ladies' College|journal=The Week : A Canadian Journal of Politics, Literature, Science and Arts|date=11 Feb 1884|volume=1|issue=10|page=160|url=https://archive.org/stream/weekcanadianjour01toro#page/n81/mode/1up|accessdate=26 April 2013}}</ref>  The school's traditional colors were chosen based on each of these subjects: blue (literature), gold (art), and crimson (music).\n\n[[James Balfour (architect)|James Balfour]] designed the Alma Ladies College building (1878\u201381) and the additions (1888-89).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionaryofarchitectsincanada.org/architects/view/1022 |title=Biographical Dictionary of Architects in Canada 1800 - 1950 - Balfour, James |publisher=Dictionaryofarchitectsincanada.org |date= |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref> Construction was done by Henry Lindop of St. Thomas at an estimated total cost of about $50,000.<ref name=\"Lechniak\" /> Alma College's grounds featured a main building, a chapel, a hall ''cum'' gymnasium, and a unique outdoor amphitheater.<ref>{{cite journal\n | last =\n | first =\n | authorlink =\n | title =Alma College, St. Thomas, Ontario.\n | journal =Dominion Illustrated News (Montreal)\n | volume =3\n | issue =76\n | pages =372\n | location =\n | date =Dec 14, 1889\n | language =\n | url =\n | jstor =\n | issn =\n | doi =\n | id =\n | mr =\n | zbl =\n | jfm =\n | accessdate = }}</ref> In its later years the college was affiliated with the [[University of Western Ontario]], and was the first college in Canada to organize a department of domestic science.<ref name=\"Elgin\">{{cite web|url=http://www.elgin.ca/alma_college.htm |title=Alma College: The First 50 Years: 1881 - 1931 |publisher=Elgin County Archives |author=Students, Faculty of Information and Media Studies at the University of Western Ontario |accessdate=March 19, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080928232935/http://www.elgin.ca/alma_college.htm |archivedate=September 28, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nBetween 1918 and 1953 new athletic facilities, a chapel and the amphitheater were constructed. In 1959 a music building was constructed.<ref>Alma college fonds, Elgin county archives 1997</ref> By 1973 the school began to experience a significant financial struggle to continue operation.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web|first=Hank |last=Daniszewski |url=http://www.almacollege.20m.com/clippings/chronology.htm |title=History of Alma College |publisher=Almacollege.20m.com |date=2008-05-28 |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref> In 1975 a portion of the residence was opened as a satellite seniors home for a local long term care facility.<ref>Alma college fonds,  published 1997, Elgin county archives</ref>  That same year a co-ed elementary school was established on campus.\n\nIn October 1976 the college was designated a provincial historic site to celebrate the school's centennial.<ref>Alma college fonds, published 1997, Elgin county archives</ref> In 1987 Alma college teachers faced job security issues and were earning about half of what public high school teachers earned.<ref name=\"Heikkila\" />\n\nAfter failed negotiations with Alma's board, the Ontario Labour Relations Board (OLRB) approved the private school bargaining unit of Alma's teachers. In February 1988 the first strike by members of a private school in Ontario was called<ref name=\"Heikkila\" /> and in March replacement workers were used to teach classes at the school.<ref name=\"Heikkila\" /> The strike lasted just over 3 months with the OLRB ruling that the Alma Board was guilty of unfair labor practices. At the end of the academic year all teachers were told that their services were no longer needed as the school was closing. (The Alma bargaining movement would continue to be active until as late as 1998.)<ref name=\"Heikkila\" /> Primary and music classes continued until 1994. In 1994 a last effort to reopen the school was unsuccessful due to low enrollment.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\" />\n\n== Building demise  (1996\u20132008) ==\n[[Image:Alma amphi.JPG|thumb|right|200px|Alma College amphitheatre as of Summer 2008 after restoration. The amphitheatre has since been vandalized and fallen to disrepair <ref name=\"Thomas Times Journal p 1 & 3\">St Thomas Times Journal: Wednesday, Dec 17, 2008: p 1 & 3. By Kyle Rea</ref>\n]]\nThe school grounds and buildings were sold to private developers in 1996 for $1.5 million (CAD).<ref name=\"ReferenceB\" /> Alma College changed ownership several times after failed attempts to convert the grounds into a retirement home, a co-ed high school, or an otherwise general restoration of the buildings.\n\nInitially after closure the buildings were sold to Royal Cambridge in 1996. The developer initially planned to restore the buildings and open a co-ed school.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\" /> Shortly after the production of Mr Headmistress, an ABC made-for-TV movie was made where various outdoor improvements were made to the building as well as restoration of ground work surrounding the structure. Nearly one month after production of the film, Royal Cambridge defaulted on the mortgage payments for the property. This caused the building to be for sale once again.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\" /> A London development company led by Brian Squires purchased the College and developed plans to build a retirement community on the campus in 1998. Over the next 4 years he spent time preparing the site and arranging financing. At this point the school began to see a wave of vandalism due to general un-occupancy. By 2003 Squires applied for a demolition permit (suggested by the mayor and recorded) due to the fact that the Mayor at the time said the building could not be saved and the land is better suited for redevelopment. The Mayor commented the people of St.Thomas would eventually understand if the building was demolished.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\" /> Brian Squires  was devastated that the mayor would say such a thing after committing to help save it during the November elections. Brian Squires quickly filed for a demolition permit to prove the mayor was wrong in saying the people of St.Thomas would not be upset if such an  action was able to take place.. At the same time Brian Squires hired a structural engineer to confirm that it could be saved. The Mayors office was swamped with calls proving Brian Squires was right in saying the people of St.Thomas will care and they also want the building saved. This demolition permit was swiftly denied by the local municipality because of the structural report provided by Brian Squires.A demolition permit was never issued and the building was saved. Brian Squires continued to try and save the building putting all his resources into it. Shortly after that,  Brian Squires handed over control of the project to the Zubick family because of lack of interest from the family, municipality and bankers. The building was gutted; asbestos, general fixtures and walls were all removed leaving little but a timber frame inside the building. The ghostly innards were used for the film Silent Hill in 2005. Once again a demolition permit was issued for Alma college after more attempts to sell the building were unsuccessful.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\" /> In 2006 the Municipal Heritage Committee recommended that the demolition permit be denied, that city council prescribe minimum standards for maintenance of the building under section 35.3 of the Ontario Heritage Act. They also recommended that the city seek further financial assistance from the provincial Ministry of Heritage. This report would subsequently be buried by the ministry of culture only to reappear under the freedom of information act two years later and after the buildings eventual demise.<ref>citation in next section</ref> the city denied the demolition permit and the building was placed on the National top ten endangered historic sites in Canada.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\" />\n\nBy 2006 an offer was made by the Alma College foundation, a group of alumnae, university academics and community leaders in the hopes of reopening as a liberal arts college. Their offer was 750,000 dollars but was rejected by the Zubick family. With the building being allowed to fall into further disrepair the city council developed new property standards by laws in order to establish minimum standards. This new bylaw was protested and ruled to be too specific in wording and was overturned by the Ontario Supreme Court{{Citation needed|date=July 2009}}. The city eventually agreed to offer a demolition permit on the condition that the front drive way be preserved and the front fa\u00e7ade,<ref name=\"ReferenceB\" /> a sentiment that is still considered valid even though today the building was destroyed. In early 2008 The Ontario Municipal Board approved the demolition of Alma College. This would set off a rush to protect the building by many local activists. On May 28, 2008 a petition was set to be passed around at the Ontario Legislature to prevent the demolition of the building. In addition a rally to save the college was also planned that morning at the Main building of the school.\n\n==Fire and grounds destruction (2008\u2013present) ==\n[[Image:Alma building fire 1.jpg|thumb|left|400px|Fire at Alma College in May 2008. After the fire only a brick shell remained. It was subsequently demolished.]]\nAlma College caught fire on May 28, 2008. The fire was suspicious in nature. The smoke could be seen as far away as downtown London, Ontario.<ref name=\"lfpress.ca\">[http://www.lfpress.ca/newsstand/News/2008/05/28/5698856.html ]{{dead link|date=October 2013}}</ref> Shortly after the fire began the main building was completely engulfed. A significant amount of video coverage of the fire is available due to a student rally to save the building which took place shortly before the fire.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6bESrThA7SY |title=Alma College Up in Flames |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref> After the fire, both a municipal and provincial investigation were commenced immediately. The fire took place shortly after the Ontario Municipal Board issued a final order that approved its demolition.<ref name=\"lfpress.ca\" /> Just prior to the time of the fire local residents met with officials of Premier Dalton McGuinty's office in hopes of postponing an eventual demolition. Local response was swift to place blame on Ontario minister of Culture, [[Aileen Carroll]] at the time for not working hard enough to protect the building from demolition.<ref name=\"lfpress.ca\" /> Documentation released through the Ontario Freedom of Information and Protection of Privacy Act a month after the fire. This indicated a report from the Ontario Heritage Trust board addressed to the Ministry of Culture. The report outlined that the ministry should ensure that should Alma fall under the threat of demolition or alteration that would compromise the heritage character, integrity and attributes of the property, that it would be appropriate for the minister to designate Alma College, using the powers prescribed under the Ontario heritage Act, to protect the building.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.builtheritagenews.ca/newsletter_archive/56.html#13 |title=St. Thomas Times: Ontario Heritage Trust Report on Alma |first=Ian |last=McCallum |publisher=Builtheritagenews.ca |date=2008-10-07 |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref> At the time of the fire the building was completely open and exposed to numerous fire hazards. Timber members within the structure had no fire protection and numerous broken windows allowed a proper flow of ventilation only to encourage the fire.<ref>St Thomas Times Journal, August 13th 2009</ref> The main school building was destroyed by fire.<ref>{{cite web|last=Badore |first=Margaret |url=http://www.treehugger.com/files/2008/05/alma-college-burns-down.php |title=Another One Bites The Dust: Alma College Burns Down |publisher=TreeHugger |date=2008-05-28 |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref>  An investigation by the St Thomas city fire department found the blaze, which began in the building's rear stairwell, was the result of arson.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite web |first=Kyle |last=Rea |url=http://www.stthomastimesjournal.com/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=1692175 |title=Alma arson trial starts Monday |publisher=St. Thomas Times-Journal |date=2009-08-08 |accessdate=2013-10-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090813005228/http://www.stthomastimesjournal.com/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=1692175 |archive-date=2009-08-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The music building and chapel were not destroyed immediately by the fire. The response to the fire was fast enough that the local fire department was able to save the music building. However weathering, vandalism, and neglect continue to further damaging the surviving structures since the fire.<ref name=\"Thomas Times Journal p 1 & 3\" /> After the fire the remaining shell of the main building was torn down due to safety considerations by the municipal government of the city of St Thomas.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.canada.com/ottawacitizen/story.html?id=006d659a-d41c-415c-8ee5-a06caf1cc741 |title=Ontario: Two teens arrested after blaze at historic school |publisher=Canada.com |work=The Ottawa Citizen |date=2008-05-31 |accessdate=2013-10-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029184122/http://www.canada.com/ottawacitizen/story.html?id=006d659a-d41c-415c-8ee5-a06caf1cc741 |archive-date=2013-10-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Shortly after the fire two boys were arrested and charged with arson.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atv.ca/london/news_57727.aspx |accessdate=July 8, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090811010415/http://www.atv.ca/london/news_57727.aspx |archivedate=August 11, 2009 |title=Atv.ca }}</ref> The identity of both boys (aged 14 and 15 at the time of the fire) could not be revealed under the Youth Criminal Justice Act. The trial occurred on August 10\u201313 <ref name=\"ReferenceC\" /> and September 2\u20133, 2009. In a ruling on September 24, 2009, the two boys were found guilty of arson and sentenced to 240 hours of community service and 2 years parole.<ref>[http://lfpress.ca/newsstand/News/Local/2009/09/24/11099221.html ]{{dead link|date=October 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter the fire a short speech was given at the Ontario legislature by speaker [[Steve Peters (Ontario politician)|Steve Peters]] in memory of the building and loss to the culture of his home. The main building topped Heritages Canada's list for worst losses in 2008.<ref>[http://www.heritagecanada.org/eng/2009%20WlossesFinalListE.pdf ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716212319/http://www.heritagecanada.org/eng/2009%20WlossesFinalListE.pdf |date=July 16, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOne of the two arsonists who set Alma College on fire is Ivan Zinn.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ianscityscope.com/2017/06/21/nine-years-after-the-fire-a-brick-from-alma-college-initiates-healing-for-ivan-zinn/|title=Nine years after the fire, a brick from Alma College initiates healing for Ivan Zinn|date=2017-06-21|work=Ian's City Scope|access-date=2017-10-31|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Student life ==\n\nStudent run publications were always popular at Alma. In 1903 a quarterly magazine was developed entitled ALMA consisting of articles written by staff and students.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Alma college fonds, Elgin county archives, 1997</ref> The Almafilian was the colleges first student newspaper published monthly from 1886 to 1917, and then serving as the year book published annually until the schools closure.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" /> Various dramatic plays, banquets, recitals and dances were held annually on campus. In 1878 a metallic box time capsule was placed in a cornerstone of the building which would remain undisturbed until 2002. In the time capsule a copy of the local newspapers (St. Thomas and [[London (Ontario)|London]]) of the time were stored, church literature, photographs, postcards, and a list of people who contributed to the college's cornerstone. The [[time capsule]] today is housed in the [[Elgin County Archives]].\n\nThe amphitheater was a popular site for ceremonies including graduations and marriages. The school kept a marriage register from 1928 to 1994.<ref>Marriage register, Part of alma college fonds, Elgin county archives, 1997</ref> Each [[May Day]] from 1931 until 1988 the amphitheater was used for musical and dramatic performances.\n\n== International Alumnae Association ==\n\nAlma college's alumni association can be traced back to February 1901 as ''Alma's Daughters''.<ref name=\"Alma College Alumnae constitution\">Alma College Alumnae constitution</ref> The first organization of the alumnae consisted of former staff and students and was formed by Emma Sisk, a former governess of the College.<ref name=\"Alma College Alumnae constitution\" /> In 1908 the charter of the school was amended to include ''Alma's Daughters'' as the official alumni of the school by allowing them to elect members to the Alma college Board of Management.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">Elgin County archives, Alma College International Alumnae Assoc. Fonds. pdf article</ref> Due to increasing membership the Alumnae officially changed its name in 1931 to the Alma College Alumnae. various local chapters began to appear throughout Ontario shortly after and eventually international chapters developed such as the [[Bermuda]] chapter in 1988 <ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/> In its form today the ''Alma College International Alumnae association'' still gathers annually.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.almacollege.20m.com/reunion.htm |title=Alma College Alumnae Reunion |publisher=Almacollege.20m.com |date= |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref> The alumni has been very active in preserving the cultural heritage of artifacts related to the history of the building.<ref name=\"almacollege.20m.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.almacollege.20m.com/archives.htm |title=Alma College International Alumnae Association |publisher=Almacollege.20m.com |date=2004-03-05 |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref> These primarily are numerous artifacts and relics that were collected from previous alumni and from the school itself. In 1997 a group of Alumni investors purchased the remaining chattels and memorabilia. This was complemented by storage space being granted at the local community city hall by then mayor and past archivist, [[Steve Peters (Ontario politician)|Steve Peters]]. The archives were stored safely in the City hall until Steve Peters took provincial office, upon which the archives were moved to a temporary home. In 2002 The alumnae decided to move the archives to a more permanent home at The Elgin County Museum, located just outside St Thomas.<ref name=\"almacollege.20m.com\" /> Many historical records and photographs were published online by the museum. To date a description of the records can be found on the web, as well as a collection of photographs of the school in its early years at the Museum's website.<ref>[http://www.elgin.ca/alma_college.htm ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080928232935/http://www.elgin.ca/alma_college.htm |date=September 28, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Role in film ==\nAlma College was featured in three films after its closure in 1995. The first film was Mr HeadMistress, a made-for-TV movie by Disney which starred [[Katey Sagal]] in 1997.<ref>London free press, November 13th 1997</ref> The film used the main building as a backdrop and surroundings grounds. Some building maintenance was performed at this time in order to bring the building up to par for filming. After significant portions of building were gutted the interior became an ideal set for the horror film ''[[Silent Hill (film)|Silent Hill]]''. Even after its destruction, photographs and its likeness were included in the 2009 film ''[[Orphan (2009 film)|Orphan]]''.<ref name=\"stthomastimesjournal.com\" />  The film featured a painting of the building in flames.\n\n== Notable alumnae ==\n:*[[Frances Adaskin]] pianist and [[Order of Canada|Order of Canada CC]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.library.ubc.ca/archives/u_arch/adaskinf.html |accessdate=July 29, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080321204728/http://www.library.ubc.ca/archives/u_arch/adaskinf.html |archivedate=March 21, 2008 }}</ref>\n:*[[Jean Sutherland Boggs]] [[Order of Canada|Order of Canada CC]], [[Royal Society of Canada|FRSC]] is a [[Canada|Canadian]] academic, [[art historian]], and [[civil servant]].\n:*[[Steve Peters (Ontario politician)|Steve Peters]], generally considered an honorary alumnus{{by whom|date=March 2014}}, worked at Alma College. He was [[Speaker of the Legislative Assembly of Ontario|Speaker of the Ontario Legislature]] from 2007 to 2011\n:*[[Pamela Gordon (politician)|Pamela Gordon]], [[Premier of Bermuda]] 1997-98\n Judge Edra Sanders, Order of Canada\n\n==See also==\n*[[St. Thomas, Ontario]]\n*[[List of historic fires]]\n*[[Benjamin Fish Austin]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.almacollege.20m.com/index.html Alumnae home page]\n*[http://archive.zeros2heroes.com/content/comic/view/id/505939 Issue 1 of ALMA: Jumbo the Elephant webcomic]\n{{Commons}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct schools in Canada]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1881]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in St. Thomas, Ontario]]\n[[Category:School buildings in Canada destroyed by arson]]\n[[Category:1881 establishments in Ontario]]\n", "text_old": "{{coord|42.773315|N|81.190869|W|display=title}}\n{{Infobox historical event\n  |Event_Name     = '''Alma College'''\n  |Image_Name     = Alma_2006.JPG\n  |Image_Caption  = Romanesque style School designed by [[James Balfour (architect)|James Balfour]] 1877, destroyed by fire in 2008\n  |Location       = [[St. Thomas, Ontario]] \n  |Date           = Fire on May 28th 2008\n  |Result         = Destroyed by arson \n  |URL            = [http://www.almacollege.20m.com/index.html Alumnae home page]\n}}\n\n'''Alma College''' was a girls' private school in [[St. Thomas, Ontario]] in [[Canada]]. Built in 1878, the school was in operation between 1881 and 1988. The college closed in 1988 in part due to a teacher's strike.<ref name=\"Heikkila\">{{cite web|url=http://www.osstf.on.ca/Default.aspx?DN=f21c5ad8-5c6b-4827-abb8-707882d5e17b |title=Alma College: A chapter in OSSTF/FEESO History Goes up in Flames |last=Heikkila |first=Rod |date=Fall 2008 |publisher=OSSTF/FEESO |accessdate=February 23, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090313034816/http://www.osstf.on.ca/Default.aspx?DN=f21c5ad8-5c6b-4827-abb8-707882d5e17b |archivedate=13 March 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Primary school and music classes were still taught on campus until 1994.<ref name=\"Alma\">{{cite web|url=http://www.almacollege.20m.com/clippings/chronology.htm|title=History of Alma College|last=Daniszewski|first=Hank|date=January 2003|publisher=Alma College International Alumnae Association|accessdate=February 23, 2009}}</ref> Following its closure the school building was used as a set for several movie productions; ''[[Silent Hill (film)|Silent Hill]]'' (interior shots), its image is included in the 2009 film ''[[Orphan (2009 film)|Orphan]]''<ref name=\"stthomastimesjournal.com\">{{cite web |url=http://stthomastimesjournal.com/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=1640616 |title=Headlines: Not necessarily a bad thing . . . |publisher=St. Thomas Times-Journal |date=2009-07-04 |accessdate=2013-10-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120420224351/http://www.stthomastimesjournal.com/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=1640616 |archive-date=2012-04-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and the made-for-TV movie, ''Mr. Headmistress'' (1997).<ref name=\"Alma\" /> The building was destroyed by a fire on May 28, 2008.<ref name=\"Heikkila\" />\n\n== History (1877\u20131996) ==\n[[File:Governor General Roland Michener at Alma College graduation ceremonies 1972.jpg|thumb|Governor General [[Roland Michener]] attending the Alma College graduation ceremonies in 1972]]\nWith the economic boom of St. Thomas in the late 19th century, Bishop Albert Carmen proposed that a ladies' college be established. The school name derives from the late Alma Munro (Moore) (wife of then Sheriff Colin Munroe) and Mrs. Alma Munro Duffield, daughter of Colin and Alma.<ref name=\"Lechniak\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hauntedhamilton.com/31_article_almacollege.html |title=The History and Hauntings of Alma Ladies College |last=Lechniak-Cumerlato |first=Stephanie |publisher=hauntedhamilton.com |accessdate=March 19, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090704120808/http://www.hauntedhamilton.com/31_article_almacollege.html |archivedate=July 4, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nAlma college was officially opened in 1881 as a liberal arts college for women, teaching literature, arts and music.<ref name=\"Elgin\" /> By 1883, it had 165 students.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Alma Ladies' College|journal=The Week : A Canadian Journal of Politics, Literature, Science and Arts|date=11 Feb 1884|volume=1|issue=10|page=160|url=https://archive.org/stream/weekcanadianjour01toro#page/n81/mode/1up|accessdate=26 April 2013}}</ref>  The school's traditional colors were chosen based on each of these subjects: blue (literature), gold (art), and crimson (music).\n\n[[James Balfour (architect)]] designed the Alma Ladies College building (1878\u201381) and the additions (1888-89).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionaryofarchitectsincanada.org/architects/view/1022 |title=Biographical Dictionary of Architects in Canada 1800 - 1950 - Balfour, James |publisher=Dictionaryofarchitectsincanada.org |date= |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref> Construction was done by Henry Lindop of St. Thomas at an estimated total cost of about $50,000.<ref name=\"Lechniak\" /> Alma College's grounds featured a main building, a chapel, a hall ''cum'' gymnasium, and a unique outdoor amphitheater.<ref>{{cite journal\n | last =\n | first =\n | authorlink =\n | title =Alma College, St. Thomas, Ontario.\n | journal =Dominion Illustrated News (Montreal)\n | volume =3\n | issue =76\n | pages =372\n | location =\n | date =Dec 14, 1889\n | language =\n | url =\n | jstor =\n | issn =\n | doi =\n | id =\n | mr =\n | zbl =\n | jfm =\n | accessdate = }}</ref> In its later years the college was affiliated with the [[University of Western Ontario]], and was the first college in Canada to organize a department of domestic science.<ref name=\"Elgin\">{{cite web|url=http://www.elgin.ca/alma_college.htm |title=Alma College: The First 50 Years: 1881 - 1931 |publisher=Elgin County Archives |author=Students, Faculty of Information and Media Studies at the University of Western Ontario |accessdate=March 19, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080928232935/http://www.elgin.ca/alma_college.htm |archivedate=September 28, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nBetween 1918 and 1953 new athletic facilities, a chapel and the amphitheater were constructed. In 1959 a music building was constructed.<ref>Alma college fonds, Elgin county archives 1997</ref> By 1973 the school began to experience a significant financial struggle to continue operation.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web|first=Hank |last=Daniszewski |url=http://www.almacollege.20m.com/clippings/chronology.htm |title=History of Alma College |publisher=Almacollege.20m.com |date=2008-05-28 |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref> In 1975 a portion of the residence was opened as a satellite seniors home for a local long term care facility.<ref>Alma college fonds,  published 1997, Elgin county archives</ref>  That same year a co-ed elementary school was established on campus.\n\nIn October 1976 the college was designated a provincial historic site to celebrate the school's centennial.<ref>Alma college fonds, published 1997, Elgin county archives</ref> In 1987 Alma college teachers faced job security issues and were earning about half of what public high school teachers earned.<ref name=\"Heikkila\" />\n\nAfter failed negotiations with Alma's board, the Ontario Labour Relations Board (OLRB) approved the private school bargaining unit of Alma's teachers. In February 1988 the first strike by members of a private school in Ontario was called<ref name=\"Heikkila\" /> and in March replacement workers were used to teach classes at the school.<ref name=\"Heikkila\" /> The strike lasted just over 3 months with the OLRB ruling that the Alma Board was guilty of unfair labor practices. At the end of the academic year all teachers were told that their services were no longer needed as the school was closing. (The Alma bargaining movement would continue to be active until as late as 1998.)<ref name=\"Heikkila\" /> Primary and music classes continued until 1994. In 1994 a last effort to reopen the school was unsuccessful due to low enrollment.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\" />\n\n== Building demise  (1996\u20132008) ==\n[[Image:Alma amphi.JPG|thumb|right|200px|Alma College amphitheatre as of Summer 2008 after restoration. The amphitheatre has since been vandalized and fallen to disrepair <ref name=\"Thomas Times Journal p 1 & 3\">St Thomas Times Journal: Wednesday, Dec 17, 2008: p 1 & 3. By Kyle Rea</ref>\n]]\nThe school grounds and buildings were sold to private developers in 1996 for $1.5 million (CAD).<ref name=\"ReferenceB\" /> Alma College changed ownership several times after failed attempts to convert the grounds into a retirement home, a co-ed high school, or an otherwise general restoration of the buildings.\n\nInitially after closure the buildings were sold to Royal Cambridge in 1996. The developer initially planned to restore the buildings and open a co-ed school.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\" /> Shortly after the production of Mr Headmistress, an ABC made-for-TV movie was made where various outdoor improvements were made to the building as well as restoration of ground work surrounding the structure. Nearly one month after production of the film, Royal Cambridge defaulted on the mortgage payments for the property. This caused the building to be for sale once again.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\" /> A London development company led by Brian Squires purchased the College and developed plans to build a retirement community on the campus in 1998. Over the next 4 years he spent time preparing the site and arranging financing. At this point the school began to see a wave of vandalism due to general un-occupancy. By 2003 Squires applied for a demolition permit (suggested by the mayor and recorded) due to the fact that the Mayor at the time said the building could not be saved and the land is better suited for redevelopment. The Mayor commented the people of St.Thomas would eventually understand if the building was demolished.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\" /> Brian Squires  was devastated that the mayor would say such a thing after committing to help save it during the November elections. Brian Squires quickly filed for a demolition permit to prove the mayor was wrong in saying the people of St.Thomas would not be upset if such an  action was able to take place.. At the same time Brian Squires hired a structural engineer to confirm that it could be saved. The Mayors office was swamped with calls proving Brian Squires was right in saying the people of St.Thomas will care and they also want the building saved. This demolition permit was swiftly denied by the local municipality because of the structural report provided by Brian Squires.A demolition permit was never issued and the building was saved. Brian Squires continued to try and save the building putting all his resources into it. Shortly after that,  Brian Squires handed over control of the project to the Zubick family because of lack of interest from the family, municipality and bankers. The building was gutted; asbestos, general fixtures and walls were all removed leaving little but a timber frame inside the building. The ghostly innards were used for the film Silent Hill in 2005. Once again a demolition permit was issued for Alma college after more attempts to sell the building were unsuccessful.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\" /> In 2006 the Municipal Heritage Committee recommended that the demolition permit be denied, that city council prescribe minimum standards for maintenance of the building under section 35.3 of the Ontario Heritage Act. They also recommended that the city seek further financial assistance from the provincial Ministry of Heritage. This report would subsequently be buried by the ministry of culture only to reappear under the freedom of information act two years later and after the buildings eventual demise.<ref>citation in next section</ref> the city denied the demolition permit and the building was placed on the National top ten endangered historic sites in Canada.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\" />\n\nBy 2006 an offer was made by the Alma College foundation, a group of alumnae, university academics and community leaders in the hopes of reopening as a liberal arts college. Their offer was 750,000 dollars but was rejected by the Zubick family. With the building being allowed to fall into further disrepair the city council developed new property standards by laws in order to establish minimum standards. This new bylaw was protested and ruled to be too specific in wording and was overturned by the Ontario Supreme Court{{Citation needed|date=July 2009}}. The city eventually agreed to offer a demolition permit on the condition that the front drive way be preserved and the front fa\u00e7ade,<ref name=\"ReferenceB\" /> a sentiment that is still considered valid even though today the building was destroyed. In early 2008 The Ontario Municipal Board approved the demolition of Alma College. This would set off a rush to protect the building by many local activists. On May 28, 2008 a petition was set to be passed around at the Ontario Legislature to prevent the demolition of the building. In addition a rally to save the college was also planned that morning at the Main building of the school.\n\n==Fire and grounds destruction (2008\u2013present) ==\n[[Image:Alma building fire 1.jpg|thumb|left|400px|Fire at Alma College in May 2008. After the fire only a brick shell remained. It was subsequently demolished.]]\nAlma College caught fire on May 28, 2008. The fire was suspicious in nature. The smoke could be seen as far away as downtown London, Ontario.<ref name=\"lfpress.ca\">[http://www.lfpress.ca/newsstand/News/2008/05/28/5698856.html ]{{dead link|date=October 2013}}</ref> Shortly after the fire began the main building was completely engulfed. A significant amount of video coverage of the fire is available due to a student rally to save the building which took place shortly before the fire.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6bESrThA7SY |title=Alma College Up in Flames |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref> After the fire, both a municipal and provincial investigation were commenced immediately. The fire took place shortly after the Ontario Municipal Board issued a final order that approved its demolition.<ref name=\"lfpress.ca\" /> Just prior to the time of the fire local residents met with officials of Premier Dalton McGuinty's office in hopes of postponing an eventual demolition. Local response was swift to place blame on Ontario minister of Culture, [[Aileen Carroll]] at the time for not working hard enough to protect the building from demolition.<ref name=\"lfpress.ca\" /> Documentation released through the Ontario Freedom of Information and Protection of Privacy Act a month after the fire. This indicated a report from the Ontario Heritage Trust board addressed to the Ministry of Culture. The report outlined that the ministry should ensure that should Alma fall under the threat of demolition or alteration that would compromise the heritage character, integrity and attributes of the property, that it would be appropriate for the minister to designate Alma College, using the powers prescribed under the Ontario heritage Act, to protect the building.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.builtheritagenews.ca/newsletter_archive/56.html#13 |title=St. Thomas Times: Ontario Heritage Trust Report on Alma |first=Ian |last=McCallum |publisher=Builtheritagenews.ca |date=2008-10-07 |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref> At the time of the fire the building was completely open and exposed to numerous fire hazards. Timber members within the structure had no fire protection and numerous broken windows allowed a proper flow of ventilation only to encourage the fire.<ref>St Thomas Times Journal, August 13th 2009</ref> The main school building was destroyed by fire.<ref>{{cite web|last=Badore |first=Margaret |url=http://www.treehugger.com/files/2008/05/alma-college-burns-down.php |title=Another One Bites The Dust: Alma College Burns Down |publisher=TreeHugger |date=2008-05-28 |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref>  An investigation by the St Thomas city fire department found the blaze, which began in the building's rear stairwell, was the result of arson.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite web |first=Kyle |last=Rea |url=http://www.stthomastimesjournal.com/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=1692175 |title=Alma arson trial starts Monday |publisher=St. Thomas Times-Journal |date=2009-08-08 |accessdate=2013-10-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090813005228/http://www.stthomastimesjournal.com/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=1692175 |archive-date=2009-08-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The music building and chapel were not destroyed immediately by the fire. The response to the fire was fast enough that the local fire department was able to save the music building. However weathering, vandalism, and neglect continue to further damaging the surviving structures since the fire.<ref name=\"Thomas Times Journal p 1 & 3\" /> After the fire the remaining shell of the main building was torn down due to safety considerations by the municipal government of the city of St Thomas.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.canada.com/ottawacitizen/story.html?id=006d659a-d41c-415c-8ee5-a06caf1cc741 |title=Ontario: Two teens arrested after blaze at historic school |publisher=Canada.com |work=The Ottawa Citizen |date=2008-05-31 |accessdate=2013-10-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029184122/http://www.canada.com/ottawacitizen/story.html?id=006d659a-d41c-415c-8ee5-a06caf1cc741 |archive-date=2013-10-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Shortly after the fire two boys were arrested and charged with arson.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atv.ca/london/news_57727.aspx |accessdate=July 8, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090811010415/http://www.atv.ca/london/news_57727.aspx |archivedate=August 11, 2009 |title=Atv.ca }}</ref> The identity of both boys (aged 14 and 15 at the time of the fire) could not be revealed under the Youth Criminal Justice Act. The trial occurred on August 10\u201313 <ref name=\"ReferenceC\" /> and September 2\u20133, 2009. In a ruling on September 24, 2009, the two boys were found guilty of arson and sentenced to 240 hours of community service and 2 years parole.<ref>[http://lfpress.ca/newsstand/News/Local/2009/09/24/11099221.html ]{{dead link|date=October 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter the fire a short speech was given at the Ontario legislature by speaker [[Steve Peters (Ontario politician)|Steve Peters]] in memory of the building and loss to the culture of his home. The main building topped Heritages Canada's list for worst losses in 2008.<ref>[http://www.heritagecanada.org/eng/2009%20WlossesFinalListE.pdf ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716212319/http://www.heritagecanada.org/eng/2009%20WlossesFinalListE.pdf |date=July 16, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOne of the two arsonists who set Alma College on fire is Ivan Zinn.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ianscityscope.com/2017/06/21/nine-years-after-the-fire-a-brick-from-alma-college-initiates-healing-for-ivan-zinn/|title=Nine years after the fire, a brick from Alma College initiates healing for Ivan Zinn|date=2017-06-21|work=Ian's City Scope|access-date=2017-10-31|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Student life ==\n\nStudent run publications were always popular at Alma. In 1903 a quarterly magazine was developed entitled ALMA consisting of articles written by staff and students.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Alma college fonds, Elgin county archives, 1997</ref> The Almafilian was the colleges first student newspaper published monthly from 1886 to 1917, and then serving as the year book published annually until the schools closure.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" /> Various dramatic plays, banquets, recitals and dances were held annually on campus. In 1878 a metallic box time capsule was placed in a cornerstone of the building which would remain undisturbed until 2002. In the time capsule a copy of the local newspapers (St. Thomas and [[London (Ontario)|London]]) of the time were stored, church literature, photographs, postcards, and a list of people who contributed to the college's cornerstone. The [[time capsule]] today is housed in the [[Elgin County Archives]].\n\nThe amphitheater was a popular site for ceremonies including graduations and marriages. The school kept a marriage register from 1928 to 1994.<ref>Marriage register, Part of alma college fonds, Elgin county archives, 1997</ref> Each [[May Day]] from 1931 until 1988 the amphitheater was used for musical and dramatic performances.\n\n== International Alumnae Association ==\n\nAlma college's alumni association can be traced back to February 1901 as ''Alma's Daughters''.<ref name=\"Alma College Alumnae constitution\">Alma College Alumnae constitution</ref> The first organization of the alumnae consisted of former staff and students and was formed by Emma Sisk, a former governess of the College.<ref name=\"Alma College Alumnae constitution\" /> In 1908 the charter of the school was amended to include ''Alma's Daughters'' as the official alumni of the school by allowing them to elect members to the Alma college Board of Management.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">Elgin County archives, Alma College International Alumnae Assoc. Fonds. pdf article</ref> Due to increasing membership the Alumnae officially changed its name in 1931 to the Alma College Alumnae. various local chapters began to appear throughout Ontario shortly after and eventually international chapters developed such as the [[Bermuda]] chapter in 1988 <ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/> In its form today the ''Alma College International Alumnae association'' still gathers annually.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.almacollege.20m.com/reunion.htm |title=Alma College Alumnae Reunion |publisher=Almacollege.20m.com |date= |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref> The alumni has been very active in preserving the cultural heritage of artifacts related to the history of the building.<ref name=\"almacollege.20m.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.almacollege.20m.com/archives.htm |title=Alma College International Alumnae Association |publisher=Almacollege.20m.com |date=2004-03-05 |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref> These primarily are numerous artifacts and relics that were collected from previous alumni and from the school itself. In 1997 a group of Alumni investors purchased the remaining chattels and memorabilia. This was complemented by storage space being granted at the local community city hall by then mayor and past archivist, [[Steve Peters (Ontario politician)|Steve Peters]]. The archives were stored safely in the City hall until Steve Peters took provincial office, upon which the archives were moved to a temporary home. In 2002 The alumnae decided to move the archives to a more permanent home at The Elgin County Museum, located just outside St Thomas.<ref name=\"almacollege.20m.com\" /> Many historical records and photographs were published online by the museum. To date a description of the records can be found on the web, as well as a collection of photographs of the school in its early years at the Museum's website.<ref>[http://www.elgin.ca/alma_college.htm ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080928232935/http://www.elgin.ca/alma_college.htm |date=September 28, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Role in film ==\nAlma College was featured in three films after its closure in 1995. The first film was Mr HeadMistress, a made-for-TV movie by Disney which starred [[Katey Sagal]] in 1997.<ref>London free press, November 13th 1997</ref> The film used the main building as a backdrop and surroundings grounds. Some building maintenance was performed at this time in order to bring the building up to par for filming. After significant portions of building were gutted the interior became an ideal set for the horror film ''[[Silent Hill (film)|Silent Hill]]''. Even after its destruction, photographs and its likeness were included in the 2009 film ''[[Orphan (2009 film)|Orphan]]''.<ref name=\"stthomastimesjournal.com\" />  The film featured a painting of the building in flames.\n\n== Notable alumnae ==\n:*[[Frances Adaskin]] pianist and [[Order of Canada|Order of Canada CC]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.library.ubc.ca/archives/u_arch/adaskinf.html |accessdate=July 29, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080321204728/http://www.library.ubc.ca/archives/u_arch/adaskinf.html |archivedate=March 21, 2008 }}</ref>\n:*[[Jean Sutherland Boggs]] [[Order of Canada|Order of Canada CC]], [[Royal Society of Canada|FRSC]] is a [[Canada|Canadian]] academic, [[art historian]], and [[civil servant]].\n:*[[Steve Peters (Ontario politician)|Steve Peters]], generally considered an honorary alumnus{{by whom|date=March 2014}}, worked at Alma College. He was [[Speaker of the Legislative Assembly of Ontario|Speaker of the Ontario Legislature]] from 2007 to 2011\n:*[[Pamela Gordon (politician)|Pamela Gordon]], [[Premier of Bermuda]] 1997-98\n Judge Edra Sanders, Order of Canada\n\n==See also==\n*[[St. Thomas, Ontario]]\n*[[List of historic fires]]\n*[[Benjamin Fish Austin]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.almacollege.20m.com/index.html Alumnae home page]\n*[http://archive.zeros2heroes.com/content/comic/view/id/505939 Issue 1 of ALMA: Jumbo the Elephant webcomic]\n{{Commons}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct schools in Canada]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1881]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in St. Thomas, Ontario]]\n[[Category:School buildings in Canada destroyed by arson]]\n[[Category:1881 establishments in Ontario]]\n", "name_user": "Scwlong", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory (1877\u20131996):pipe", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alma_College_(St._Thomas,_Ontario)"}
{"title_page": "Union Street station (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)", "text_new": "{{For|the demolished station actually at Union Street & Fifth Avenue|Union Street (BMT Fifth Avenue Line)}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n\n{{Short description|New York City Subway station in Brooklyn}}\n{{Infobox NYCS\n| name = Union Street\n| font_color = black\n| bg_color = #FFC800\n| bg_color_2 = #874F17\n| image = Union Street - Northbound Platform.jpg\n| image_caption = Manhattan bound platform\n| address = Union Street &amp; [[Fourth Avenue (Brooklyn)|Fourth Avenue]]<br>Brooklyn, NY 11217<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/doh/downloads/pdf/epi/Brooklyn|title=Borough of Brooklyn, New York City|publisher=[[Government of New York City]]|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n| borough = [[Brooklyn]]\n| locale = [[Park Slope, Brooklyn|Park Slope]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|40.678108|N|73.98391|W|display=inline,title}}\n| lat_dir = N\n| lon_dir = W\n| division = BMT\n| line = [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]]\n| service = Fourth center local\n| service_header = Fourth center local header\n| connection = {{bus icon}} '''[[NYCT Bus]]''': {{NYC bus link|B37}} <small>(on [[Third Avenue (Brooklyn)|Third Avenue]])</small>; {{NYC bus link|B63}} <small>(on Fifth Avenue)</small><ref>{{cite NYC bus map|B}}</ref>\n| code = 028\n| accessible = planned\n| platforms = 2 [[side platform]]s\n| tracks = 4\n| structure = Underground\n| open_date = {{start date and age|June 22, 1915}}<ref name=\"Station Opening2\"/>\n| passengers = 2,090,848<ref name=\"ridership\">{{NYCS const|riderref}}</ref>\n| pass_year = 2018\n| pass_percent = 8.0\n| rank = 226<ref name=\"ridership\"/>\n| next_north = {{NYCS next | station=Atlantic Avenue\u2013Barclays Center | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | service=Fourth center local}}\n| next_south = {{NYCS next | station=Ninth Street | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | service=Fourth center local}}\n| legend = {{NYCS infobox legend|allexceptnights}}{{NYCS infobox legend|nightsonly}}{{NYCS infobox legend|rushonly}}{{NYCS infobox legend|rushpeak}}\n}}\n\n'''Union Street''' is a local [[metro station|station]] on the [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]] of the [[New York City Subway]]. It is located at the corner of [[Fourth Avenue (Brooklyn)|Fourth Avenue]] and Union Street in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]], serving the communities of [[Park Slope, Brooklyn|Park Slope]], [[Gowanus, Brooklyn|Gowanus]] and [[Carroll Gardens, Brooklyn|Carroll Gardens]]. It is served by the [[R (New York City Subway service)|R]] train at all times. The [[D (New York City Subway service)|D]] and [[N (New York City Subway service)|N]] trains also stop here during late nights, and some rush-hour [[W (New York City Subway service)|W]] trains stop here in the peak direction.\n\nThe Union Street station was constructed as part of the Fourth Avenue Line, which was approved in 1905. Construction on the segment of the line that includes Union Street started on December 20, 1909, and was completed in September 1912. The station opened on June 22, 1915 as part of the initial portion of the BMT Fourth Avenue Line to [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]]. The station's platforms were lengthened in 1925, and again in 1970. The station was also renovated in 1970 and in the mid-1990s.\n\n==History==\n===Construction and opening===\nThe Union Street station was constructed as part of the Fourth Avenue Line, the plan for which was initially adopted on June 1, 1905.<ref name=\":123\">{{Cite journal|last=Rogoff|first=David|date=May 1961|title=The Fourth Ave. Subway|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BzKvSWhrQBW4d3pvOGZaSERiZEhpQ24xT19DTktkQUVlLW5j/view|journal=New York Division Bulletin|publisher=Electric Railroaders' Association|volume=|pages=2\u201310|access-date=May 8, 2017|via=}}</ref> The Rapid Transit Commission was succeeded on July 1, 1907, by the [[New York Public Service Commission|New York State Public Service Commission]] (PSC), which approved the plan for the line in late 1907.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XoxBAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA18&dq=4th+Avenue+line#v=onepage&q=4th%20Avenue%20line&f=false|page=18|title=Fourth Avenue Subway, Brooklyn's New Transportation Line: A Part of the Dual System of Rapid Transit of the City of New York|date=June 19, 1915|publisher=Public Service Commission|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite news|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48901678/|title=Fourth Avenue Subway Is Sent To A Committee|last=|first=|date=March 20, 1908|work=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=May 4, 2017|pages=1\u20132|language=en}}</ref> The contract for the section of the line that included the Union Street station, Route 11A2, which extended from 10th Street to Sackett Street, was awarded on May 22, 1908, to E.E. Smith Construction Company for $2,296,234.93 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=2296234.93|start_year=1908|r=-3}}). The [[New York City Board of Estimate]] approved the contract on October 29, 1909.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/53922207/|title=Fourth Avenue Subway To Be Political Issue|date=December 11, 1908|work=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=May 4, 2017|page=1|language=en}}</ref> Construction on the segment started on December 20, 1909, and was completed in September 1912.<ref name=\":123\"/>\n\nAs part of negotiations between New York City, the [[Brooklyn Rapid Transit Company]] (BRT), and the [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company]] for the expansion of the city's transit network, the line was leased to a subsidiary of the BRT. The agreement, known as Contract 4 of the [[Dual Contracts]], was signed on March 19, 1913.<ref name=\":10\"/> Union Street opened on June 22, 1915 as part of the initial portion of the Fourth Avenue Line to [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]].<ref name=\"Station Opening2\">{{cite web|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48814840/|title=Through Tube to Coney, 48 Minutes: First Train on Fourth Avenue Route Beats West End Line Eleven Minutes|date=June 22, 1915|publisher=[[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]]|accessdate=June 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Station renovations ===\n\n==== 1920s ====\nOn June 27, 1922, the New York State Transit Commission directed its engineers to prepare plans to lengthen the platforms at 23 stations on the lines of the [[Brooklyn\u2013Manhattan Transit Corporation]] (BMT), the successor to the BRT, to accommodate eight-car trains. As part of the project, Union Street's platforms would have been lengthened from {{Convert|435|feet|meters}} to {{Convert|530|feet|meters}}.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Legislature|first=New York (State)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-ugaAQAAIAAJ&pg=RA3-PA100&dq=%22union+street%22+LENGTHENING&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj8_PLm7tboAhXBhOAKHVx0AzwQ6AEwA3oECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=%22union%20street%22%20LENGTHENING&f=false|title=Second Annual Report of the Transit Commission (For the Calendar Year 1922)|date=1923|publisher=New York State Transit Commission|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=100|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u5kT80_w6rYC&pg=PA1277&dq=%22union+street%22+%22530+feet%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjngqLU7dboAhVLTt8KHapMD8IQ6AEwCHoECAkQAg#v=onepage&q=%22union%20street%22%20%22530%20feet%22&f=false|title=Proceedings of the Transit Commission, State of New York Volume III From January 1 to December 31, 1923|date=1923|publisher=New York State Transit Commission|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=1277|language=en}}</ref> Progress on the extensions did not occur until February 16, 1925, when the [[New York City Board of Transportation]] (NYCBOT) directed its engineers to prepare plans to lengthen the platforms at this and eleven other stations along the Fourth Avenue Line. It estimated the project's cost to be $633,000 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=633000|start_year=1925|r=-3}}). The BMT had been ordered by the Transit Commission to lengthen these platforms since September 1923.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/02/17/archives/12-bm-t-stations-to-be-lengthehed-transportation-board-orders.html|title=12 B-M. T. Stations To Be Lengthened; Transportation Board Orders Engineers to Prepare Contracts for Brooklyn Work. Cost Put At $633,000 Letter to Commission Urges That Company Be Compelled to Buy New Cars.|last=|first=|date=February 17, 1925|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 4, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The NYCBOT received bids for the project on February 25, 1926.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48193500/the-brooklyn-citizen/|title=Board Receives Platform Bids For B.M.T. Lines. Six Companies Submit Prices for Extending Subway Stations|date=1926-02-26|work=The Brooklyn Citizen|access-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live|pages=5}}</ref> The contract was awarded to Corson Construction Company for $345,021 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=345021|start_year=1926|r=-3}}).<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48193684/the-standard-union/|title=Brooklyn Wins Big Improvement Fund|date=1926-03-18|work=Brooklyn Standard Union|access-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live|pages=20}}</ref>\n\n==== 1950s and 1960s ====\nIn July 1959, the [[New York City Transit Authority]] (NYCTA) announced that it would install [[fluorescent lighting]] at the Union Street station and five other stations along Fourth Avenue for between $175,000 and $200,000. Bids on the project were to be advertised on August 7, 1959 and completed by fall 1960.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47783394/bay-ridge-home-reporter/|title=Our Subway Stations To Be Brighter|date=1959-07-10|work=Bay Ridge Home Reporter|access-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1960s, the NYCTA started a project to lengthen station platforms on its lines in Southern Brooklyn to {{Convert|615|feet|meters|abbr=}} to accommodate 10-car trains.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=New York City Transit Authority Annual Report For The Year June 30, 1960|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=1960|isbn=|location=|pages=16\u201317}}</ref> On July 14, 1967, the NYCTA awarded a contract to conduct test borings at eleven stations on the Fourth Avenue Line, including Union Street, to W. M. Walsh Corporation for $6,585 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=6585|start_year=1967}}) in preparation of the construction of platform extensions.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=HJTVAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22Union+Street,+9th+Street,%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=borings+JULY|title=Minutes and Proceedings|date=1967|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=379\u2013380|language=en}}</ref> The NYCTA issued an invitation for bids on the project to extend the platforms at stations along the Fourth Avenue Line between [[Pacific Street station (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|Pacific Street]] and [[36th Street station (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|36th Street]], including those at Union Street, on March 28, 1969.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=-HNIAQAAIAAJ&dq=Group+XXX%E2%80%94Broadway-Fourth+Avenue+Line:+pacific+Street,+Union+Street,+9th+Street&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Group+XXX|title=Engineering News-record|date=1969|publisher=McGraw-Hill|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=63|language=en}}</ref> The contract was awarded to Horn Construction Company on May 13, 1969 for $7,381,890. Funding for the renovation projects came out of the NYCTA's 1969\u20131970 Capital Budget, costing $8,177,890 in total.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=c-gxGpL_JNQC&dq=%22Pacific+Street+to+36th+Street+stations%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=10-car|title=Proceedings of the New York City Transit Authority Relating to Matters Other Than Operation|date=1969|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=280, 435, 487|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs part of the renovation project, the station's platforms were extended {{Convert|85|feet|meters|abbr=}}<ref name=\":1\" /> to the north,<ref name=\":2\" /> and the station's elaborate mosaic tile walls were covered over with {{convert|8|by|16|in|cm|adj=on}} white cinderblock tiles. The latter change, which was also made to 15 other stations on the [[BMT Broadway Line|BMT Broadway]] and Fourth Avenue Line, was criticized for being dehumanizing. The NYCTA spokesman stated that the old tiles were in poor condition and that the change was made to improve the appearance of stations and provide uniformity. Furthermore, it did not consider the old mosaics to have \"any great artistic merit\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Burks|first=Edward C.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/02/21/archives/subways-colored-tile-gets-cover-up-job.html|title=Subways' Colored Tile Gets Cover\u2010Up Job|date=1970-02-21|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==== 1990s ====\n[[File:Union BMT track.jpg|thumb|175px|The colored tilework forms part of the station art installation|alt=]]\nThe station was renovated again from 1991 to 1994. The $2.397&nbsp;million contract for the project was awarded on February 28, 1991. During the closure of the Bay Ridge-bound platform, the glazed tiles at the station were heavily defaced with graffiti, and were cleaned prior to the station's reopening with a heavy duty cleaner, which damaged the glazing. A modification to the contract was approved on May 23, 1994. As part of the modification, new graffiti resistant ceramic tile was installed, signage, advertising panels, benches and trash bins were removed and reinstalled, exhaust systems were added in the porter rooms at both platforms, and the wall-mounted conductors board was replaced by a ceiling-mounted one. The modification cost $174,000, and change orders cost $111,004.<ref>{{Cite book|title=NYC Transit Committee Agenda May 1994|date=May 16, 1994|publisher=New York City Transit}}</ref>{{Rp|C-99, C-100}} The Brooklyn-bound platform was closed between July 15 and November 15, 1991,<ref>{{Cite news|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29284935/daily_news/|title=Attention Brooklyn-Bound N R Subway Riders: Union Street Station Is Closing July 15th to November 15th|last=|first=|date=July 12, 1991|work=New York Daily News|access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref> while the Manhattan-bound platform was closed between February 19 and June 20, 1992.<ref>{{Cite news|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29283657/daily_news/|title=Attention N, R Customers: Beginning June 20, 1992: Union Street Station Manhattan-bound platform reopens.|last=|first=|date=June 19, 1992|work=New York Daily News|access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29284140/daily_news/|title=Attention N & R Subway Customers: Union St Manhattan-bound platform is closing February 19th to June 19th.|last=|first=|date=February 18, 1992|work=New York Daily News|access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to upgrading the same elements that were replaced in the previous overhaul, floors and track wall tiling, the public announcement system, and safety treads along platform edges and track-beds were replaced. It also included an art installation by Emmett Wigglesworth called ''CommUnion''. It features twenty-two panels of various designs in the recessed area of the platform tiles above the station signs and other designs on the openings in the track walls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nycsubway.org/perl/show?1167|title=Showing Image 1167|last=Whitehorne|first=Wayne|date=January 15, 2000|website=www.nycsubway.org|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/aft/permanentart/permart.html?agency=n&line=R&station=22|title=Arts for Transit: CommUnion|work=MTA Arts for Transit|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|accessdate=June 2, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==== Proposed accessibility ====\nAs part of the 2015\u20132019 [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] Capital Program, $300&nbsp;million was allocated to enhance station access and provide ADA-accessibility at 15 stations chosen by New York City. Four stations were being evaluated for such improvements, including the Union Street station.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BJRM36BCciU|title=MTA Board - NYCT/Bus Committee Meeting - 02/20/2018|date=February 20, 2018|publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|accessdate=March 4, 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/capitaldashboard/allframenew_head.html?PROJNUM=t7160521&PLTYPE=1&DISPLAYALL=Y|title=T7160521 Station Capacity Enhancements at Union Street on the 4 Avenue Line - Design Only|website=mta.info|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Clear|left}}\n\n==Station layout==\n{{stack|float=right|\n{{NYCS 4-tracked local station\n|1=Atlantic Avenue\u2013Barclays Center\n|l1=Atlantic Av\n|2=Ninth Street\n|l2=9 St\n|code=BMT Fourth Avenue Line\n|color=yellow\n|textcolor=black\n|deg=330\n}}\n}}\n{{NYCS Platform Layout IND Fulton Street Line}}\n[[File:Union Street BMT Stairs.jpg|thumb|220px|Entrance|alt=]]\nThis underground station has four tracks and two [[side platform]]s.<ref name=\"tracks2\">{{NYCS const|trackref|trackbook}}</ref> The two center express tracks are used by the D and N trains during daytime hours.<ref name=\"ttd\">{{NYCS const|timetable|d}}</ref><ref name=\"ttn\">{{NYCS const|timetable|n}}</ref> A white tiled curtain wall separates the express tracks from the local tracks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/unionm/unionm3.jpg|title=Looking down the simple Manhattan-bound platform at Union Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=December 22, 2008|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBoth platforms are columnless except for a section at their extreme north ends,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/unionm/unionm3.jpg|title=Looking down the simple Manhattan-bound platform at Union Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=December 22, 2008|website=subwaynut.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> where they were extended in 1970 to accommodate 10-car trains. Here, the columns are cream colored I-beams. The ceiling is lower in this section.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/unionm/unionm6.jpg|title=The ceiling gets extremely low right at the northern end of the station at Union Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=December 22, 2008|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/unionm/unionm5.jpg|title=Another view down the simple Manhattan-bound side platform at Union Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=December 22, 2008|website=subwaynut.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the station's 1970 renovation, it was finished all in white and marble tile, and it had its own color scheme to allow regular passengers to identify the station based only on the color of the marble trimmings.<ref name=\":10\" /> Since the renovation, the station walls have consisted of white cinderblock tiles, except for small recesses in the walls, which contain gray-painted cinderblock tiles. The gray cinderblock field contains the station-name signs and white text pointing to the exits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/unionm/unionm4.jpg|title=A close up of a Union Street station sign on the platform wall, with the 1960s arrow pointing for the exit beneath it.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=December 22, 2008|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Exits===\nEach platform has one same-level [[fare control]] area in the center and there are no crossovers or crossunders to allow free transfer between directions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nycsubway.org/perl/show?122221|title=Bay Ridge-bound fare control|last=Tobar|first=Roberto C.|date=May 20, 2011|website=www.nycsubway.org|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> The Manhattan-bound side has a fare control area, a [[turnstile]] bank, token booth, and two street stairs. The stairs on the Manhattan-bound platform go up to the southeast corner of Union Street and Fourth Avenue while those on the Bay Ridge-bound platform goes up to the southwest corner. The Bay Ridge-bound side has a fare control area, a [[turnstile]] bank without a token booth, and two street stairs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/unionm/unionm11.jpg|title=Going down to the now unstaffed Bay Ridge-bound fare control area|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=May 9, 2013|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"MTA-ParkSlopeMap-2015\">{{cite web|title=MTA Neighborhood Maps: Park Slope|url=http://web.mta.info/maps/neighborhoods/bkn/B3_Park_Slope_2015.pdf|website=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|mta.info]]|publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|accessdate=August 2, 2015|date=2015}}</ref>\n\n{{Clear|left}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|position=right|Union Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)}}\n* {{NYCS ref|http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/stations?216:2870|BMT 4th Avenue|Union Street}}\n* The Subway Nut \u2014 [http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/unionm/index.php Union Street Pictures]\n* MTA's Arts For Transit \u2014 [https://web.archive.org/web/20110606073450/http://mta.info/mta/aft/permanentart/permart.html?agency=nyct&line=M&station=13&xdev=1339 Union Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)]\n* [https://maps.google.com/?ie=UTF8&ll=40.677115,-73.983328&spn=0,359.986567&z=17&lci=transit&layer=c&cbll=40.677228,-73.983256&panoid=21WG-nYiOCICM5t9pabhQg&cbp=12,336.54,,0,3.63 Union Street entrance from Google Maps Street View]\n* [https://www.google.com/maps/@40.6772079,-73.9830475,3a,75y,62.15h,83.78t/data=!3m7!1e1!3m5!1s-51z5J31USnI%2FWG3GwzS1EZI%2FAAAAAAAAYTo%2FRqvXDLDF-hww1DY9gHkftwOWZaiTYALUQCLIB!2e4!6s%2F%2Flh4.googleusercontent.com%2F-51z5J31USnI%2FWG3GwzS1EZI%2FAAAAAAAAYTo%2FRqvXDLDF-hww1DY9gHkftwOWZaiTYALUQCLIB%2Fw203-h100-p-k-no%2F!7i7168!8i3584!4m3!8m2!3m1!1e1 Platform from Google Maps Street View]\n\n{{NYCS stations navbox by service|lr=y}}\n{{NYCS stations navbox by line|4ave=yes}}\n\n[[Category:BMT Fourth Avenue Line stations]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1915]]\n[[Category:1915 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Park Slope]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations located underground]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the demolished station actually at Union Street & Fifth Avenue|Union Street (BMT Fifth Avenue Line)}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n\n{{Short description|New York City Subway station in Brooklyn}}\n{{Infobox NYCS\n| name = Union Street\n| font_color = black\n| bg_color = #FFC800\n| bg_color_2 = #874F17\n| image = Union Street - Northbound Platform.jpg\n| image_caption = Manhattan bound platform\n| address = Union Street &amp; [[Fourth Avenue (Brooklyn)|Fourth Avenue]]<br>Brooklyn, NY 11217<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/doh/downloads/pdf/epi/Brooklyn|title=Borough of Brooklyn, New York City|publisher=[[Government of New York City]]|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n| borough = [[Brooklyn]]\n| locale = [[Park Slope, Brooklyn|Park Slope]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|40.678108|N|73.98391|W|display=inline,title}}\n| lat_dir = N\n| lon_dir = W\n| division = BMT\n| line = [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]]\n| service = Fourth center local\n| service_header = Fourth center local header\n| connection = {{bus icon}} '''[[NYCT Bus]]''': {{NYC bus link|B37}} <small>(on [[Third Avenue (Brooklyn)|Third Avenue]])</small>; {{NYC bus link|B63}} <small>(on Fifth Avenue)</small><ref>{{cite NYC bus map|B}}</ref>\n| code = 028\n| accessible = planned\n| platforms = 2 [[side platform]]s\n| tracks = 4\n| structure = Underground\n| open_date = {{start date and age|June 22, 1915}}<ref name=\"Station Opening2\"/>\n| passengers = 2,090,848<ref name=\"ridership\">{{NYCS const|riderref}}</ref>\n| pass_year = 2018\n| pass_percent = 8.0\n| rank = 226<ref name=\"ridership\"/>\n| next_north = {{NYCS next | station=Atlantic Avenue\u2013Barclays Center | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | service=Fourth center local}}\n| next_south = {{NYCS next | station=Ninth Street | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | service=Fourth center local}}\n| legend = {{NYCS infobox legend|allexceptnights}}{{NYCS infobox legend|nightsonly}}{{NYCS infobox legend|rushonly}}{{NYCS infobox legend|rushpeak}}\n}}\n\n'''Union Street''' is a local [[metro station|station]] on the [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]] of the [[New York City Subway]]. It is located at the corner of [[Fourth Avenue (Brooklyn)|Fourth Avenue]] and Union Street in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]], serving the communities of [[Park Slope, Brooklyn|Park Slope]], [[Gowanus, Brooklyn|Gowanus]] and [[Carroll Gardens, Brooklyn|Carroll Gardens]]. It is served by the [[R (New York City Subway service)|R]] train at all times. The [[D (New York City Subway service)|D]] and [[N (New York City Subway service)|N]] trains also stop here during late nights, and some rush-hour [[W (New York City Subway service)|W]] trains stop here in the peak direction.\n\nThe Union Street station was constructed as part of the Fourth Avenue Line, which was approved in 1905. Construction on the segment of the line that includes Union Street started on December 20, 1909, and was completed in September 1912. The station opened on June 22, 1915 as part of the initial portion of the BMT Fourth Avenue Line to [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]]. The station's platforms were lengthened in 1925, and again in 1970. The station was also renovated in 1970 and in the mid-1990s.\n\n==History==\n===Construction and opening===\n[[File:Union Street BMT Stairs.jpg|thumb|220px|Entrance to the Manhattan-bound platform.|alt=|left]]\nThe Union Street station was constructed as part of the Fourth Avenue Line, the plan for which was initially adopted on June 1, 1905.<ref name=\":123\">{{Cite journal|last=Rogoff|first=David|date=May 1961|title=The Fourth Ave. Subway|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BzKvSWhrQBW4d3pvOGZaSERiZEhpQ24xT19DTktkQUVlLW5j/view|journal=New York Division Bulletin|publisher=Electric Railroaders' Association|volume=|pages=2\u201310|access-date=May 8, 2017|via=}}</ref> The Rapid Transit Commission was succeeded on July 1, 1907, by the [[New York Public Service Commission|New York State Public Service Commission]] (PSC), which approved the plan for the line in late 1907.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XoxBAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA18&dq=4th+Avenue+line#v=onepage&q=4th%20Avenue%20line&f=false|page=18|title=Fourth Avenue Subway, Brooklyn's New Transportation Line: A Part of the Dual System of Rapid Transit of the City of New York|date=June 19, 1915|publisher=Public Service Commission|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite news|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48901678/|title=Fourth Avenue Subway Is Sent To A Committee|last=|first=|date=March 20, 1908|work=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=May 4, 2017|pages=1\u20132|language=en}}</ref> The contract for the section of the line that included the Union Street station, Route 11A2, which extended from 10th Street to Sackett Street, was awarded on May 22, 1908, to E.E. Smith Construction Company for $2,296,234.93 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=2296234.93|start_year=1908|r=-3}}). The [[New York City Board of Estimate]] approved the contract on October 29, 1909.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/53922207/|title=Fourth Avenue Subway To Be Political Issue|date=December 11, 1908|work=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=May 4, 2017|page=1|language=en}}</ref> Construction on the segment started on December 20, 1909, and was completed in September 1912.<ref name=\":123\"/>\n\nAs part of negotiations between New York City, the [[Brooklyn Rapid Transit Company]] (BRT), and the [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company]] for the expansion of the city's transit network, the line was leased to a subsidiary of the BRT. The agreement, known as Contract 4 of the [[Dual Contracts]], was signed on March 19, 1913.<ref name=\":10\"/> Union Street opened on June 22, 1915 as part of the initial portion of the Fourth Avenue Line to [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]].<ref name=\"Station Opening2\">{{cite web|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48814840/|title=Through Tube to Coney, 48 Minutes: First Train on Fourth Avenue Route Beats West End Line Eleven Minutes|date=June 22, 1915|publisher=[[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]]|accessdate=June 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Station renovations ===\n\n==== 1920s ====\nOn June 27, 1922, the New York State Transit Commission directed its engineers to prepare plans to lengthen the platforms at 23 stations on the lines of the [[Brooklyn\u2013Manhattan Transit Corporation]] (BMT), the successor to the BRT, to accommodate eight-car trains. As part of the project, Union Street's platforms would have been lengthened from {{Convert|435|feet|meters}} to {{Convert|530|feet|meters}}.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Legislature|first=New York (State)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-ugaAQAAIAAJ&pg=RA3-PA100&dq=%22union+street%22+LENGTHENING&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj8_PLm7tboAhXBhOAKHVx0AzwQ6AEwA3oECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=%22union%20street%22%20LENGTHENING&f=false|title=Second Annual Report of the Transit Commission (For the Calendar Year 1922)|date=1923|publisher=New York State Transit Commission|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=100|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u5kT80_w6rYC&pg=PA1277&dq=%22union+street%22+%22530+feet%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjngqLU7dboAhVLTt8KHapMD8IQ6AEwCHoECAkQAg#v=onepage&q=%22union%20street%22%20%22530%20feet%22&f=false|title=Proceedings of the Transit Commission, State of New York Volume III From January 1 to December 31, 1923|date=1923|publisher=New York State Transit Commission|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=1277|language=en}}</ref> Progress on the extensions did not occur until February 16, 1925, when the [[New York City Board of Transportation]] (NYCBOT) directed its engineers to prepare plans to lengthen the platforms at this and eleven other stations along the Fourth Avenue Line. It estimated the project's cost to be $633,000 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=633000|start_year=1925|r=-3}}). The BMT had been ordered by the Transit Commission to lengthen these platforms since September 1923.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/02/17/archives/12-bm-t-stations-to-be-lengthehed-transportation-board-orders.html|title=12 B-M. T. Stations To Be Lengthened; Transportation Board Orders Engineers to Prepare Contracts for Brooklyn Work. Cost Put At $633,000 Letter to Commission Urges That Company Be Compelled to Buy New Cars.|last=|first=|date=February 17, 1925|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 4, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The NYCBOT received bids for the project on February 25, 1926.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48193500/the-brooklyn-citizen/|title=Board Receives Platform Bids For B.M.T. Lines. Six Companies Submit Prices for Extending Subway Stations|date=1926-02-26|work=The Brooklyn Citizen|access-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live|pages=5}}</ref> The contract was awarded to Corson Construction Company for $345,021 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=345021|start_year=1926|r=-3}}).<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48193684/the-standard-union/|title=Brooklyn Wins Big Improvement Fund|date=1926-03-18|work=Brooklyn Standard Union|access-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live|pages=20}}</ref>\n\n==== 1950s and 1960s ====\nIn July 1959, the [[New York City Transit Authority]] (NYCTA) announced that it would install [[fluorescent lighting]] at the Union Street station and five other stations along Fourth Avenue for between $175,000 and $200,000. Bids on the project were to be advertised on August 7, 1959 and completed by fall 1960.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47783394/bay-ridge-home-reporter/|title=Our Subway Stations To Be Brighter|date=1959-07-10|work=Bay Ridge Home Reporter|access-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1960s, the NYCTA started a project to lengthen station platforms on its lines in Southern Brooklyn to {{Convert|615|feet|meters|abbr=}} to accommodate 10-car trains.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=New York City Transit Authority Annual Report For The Year June 30, 1960|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=1960|isbn=|location=|pages=16\u201317}}</ref> On July 14, 1967, the NYCTA awarded a contract to conduct test borings at eleven stations on the Fourth Avenue Line, including Union Street, to W. M. Walsh Corporation for $6,585 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=6585|start_year=1967}}) in preparation of the construction of platform extensions.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=HJTVAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22Union+Street,+9th+Street,%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=borings+JULY|title=Minutes and Proceedings|date=1967|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=379\u2013380|language=en}}</ref> The NYCTA issued an invitation for bids on the project to extend the platforms at stations along the Fourth Avenue Line between [[Pacific Street station (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|Pacific Street]] and [[36th Street station (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|36th Street]], including those at Union Street, on March 28, 1969.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=-HNIAQAAIAAJ&dq=Group+XXX%E2%80%94Broadway-Fourth+Avenue+Line:+pacific+Street,+Union+Street,+9th+Street&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Group+XXX|title=Engineering News-record|date=1969|publisher=McGraw-Hill|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=63|language=en}}</ref> The contract was awarded to Horn Construction Company on May 13, 1969 for $7,381,890. Funding for the renovation projects came out of the NYCTA's 1969\u20131970 Capital Budget, costing $8,177,890 in total.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=c-gxGpL_JNQC&dq=%22Pacific+Street+to+36th+Street+stations%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=10-car|title=Proceedings of the New York City Transit Authority Relating to Matters Other Than Operation|date=1969|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=280, 435, 487|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs part of the renovation project, the station's platforms were extended {{Convert|85|feet|meters|abbr=}}<ref name=\":1\" /> to the north,<ref name=\":2\" /> and the station's elaborate mosaic tile walls were covered over with {{convert|8|by|16|in|cm|adj=on}} white cinderblock tiles. The latter change, which was also made to 15 other stations on the [[BMT Broadway Line|BMT Broadway]] and Fourth Avenue Line, was criticized for being dehumanizing. The NYCTA spokesman stated that the old tiles were in poor condition and that the change was made to improve the appearance of stations and provide uniformity. Furthermore, it did not consider the old mosaics to have \"any great artistic merit\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Burks|first=Edward C.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/02/21/archives/subways-colored-tile-gets-cover-up-job.html|title=Subways' Colored Tile Gets Cover\u2010Up Job|date=1970-02-21|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==== 1990s ====\n[[File:Union BMT track.jpg|thumb|175px|The colored tilework forms part of the station art installation|alt=]]\nThe station was renovated again from 1991 to 1994. The $2.397&nbsp;million contract for the project was awarded on February 28, 1991. During the closure of the Bay Ridge-bound platform, the glazed tiles at the station were heavily defaced with graffiti, and were cleaned prior to the station's reopening with a heavy duty cleaner, which damaged the glazing. A modification to the contract was approved on May 23, 1994. As part of the modification, new graffiti resistant ceramic tile was installed, signage, advertising panels, benches and trash bins were removed and reinstalled, exhaust systems were added in the porter rooms at both platforms, and the wall-mounted conductors board was replaced by a ceiling-mounted one. The modification cost $174,000, and change orders cost $111,004.<ref>{{Cite book|title=NYC Transit Committee Agenda May 1994|date=May 16, 1994|publisher=New York City Transit}}</ref>{{Rp|C-99, C-100}} The Brooklyn-bound platform was closed between July 15 and November 15, 1991,<ref>{{Cite news|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29284935/daily_news/|title=Attention Brooklyn-Bound N R Subway Riders: Union Street Station Is Closing July 15th to November 15th|last=|first=|date=July 12, 1991|work=New York Daily News|access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref> while the Manhattan-bound platform was closed between February 19 and June 20, 1992.<ref>{{Cite news|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29283657/daily_news/|title=Attention N, R Customers: Beginning June 20, 1992: Union Street Station Manhattan-bound platform reopens.|last=|first=|date=June 19, 1992|work=New York Daily News|access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29284140/daily_news/|title=Attention N & R Subway Customers: Union St Manhattan-bound platform is closing February 19th to June 19th.|last=|first=|date=February 18, 1992|work=New York Daily News|access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to upgrading the same elements that were replaced in the previous overhaul, floors and track wall tiling, the public announcement system, and safety treads along platform edges and track-beds were replaced. It also included an art installation by Emmett Wigglesworth called ''CommUnion''. It features twenty-two panels of various designs in the recessed area of the platform tiles above the station signs and other designs on the openings in the track walls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nycsubway.org/perl/show?1167|title=Showing Image 1167|last=Whitehorne|first=Wayne|date=January 15, 2000|website=www.nycsubway.org|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/aft/permanentart/permart.html?agency=n&line=R&station=22|title=Arts for Transit: CommUnion|work=MTA Arts for Transit|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|accessdate=June 2, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==== Proposed accessibility ====\nAs part of the 2015\u20132019 [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] Capital Program, $300&nbsp;million was allocated to enhance station access and provide ADA-accessibility at 15 stations chosen by New York City. Four stations were being evaluated for such improvements, including the Union Street station.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BJRM36BCciU|title=MTA Board - NYCT/Bus Committee Meeting - 02/20/2018|date=February 20, 2018|publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|accessdate=March 4, 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/capitaldashboard/allframenew_head.html?PROJNUM=t7160521&PLTYPE=1&DISPLAYALL=Y|title=T7160521 Station Capacity Enhancements at Union Street on the 4 Avenue Line - Design Only|website=mta.info|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Clear|left}}\n\n==Station layout==\n{{stack|float=right|\n{{NYCS 4-tracked local station\n|1=Atlantic Avenue\u2013Barclays Center\n|l1=Atlantic Av\n|2=Ninth Street\n|l2=9 St\n|code=BMT Fourth Avenue Line\n|color=yellow\n|textcolor=black\n|deg=330\n}}\n}}\n{{NYCS Platform Layout IND Fulton Street Line}}\n[[File:Union St art vc.jpg|thumb|View of station artwork.]]\nThis underground station has four tracks and two [[side platform]]s.<ref name=\"tracks2\">{{NYCS const|trackref|trackbook}}</ref> The R stops here at all times;<ref name=\"ttr\">{{NYCS const|timetable|r}}</ref> some rush-hour W trains stop here in the peak direction;<ref name=\"ttw\">{{NYCS const|timetable|w}}</ref> and the D and N stop here during late nights, but use the center express tracks to bypass the station during daytime hours.<ref name=\"ttd\">{{NYCS const|timetable|d}}</ref><ref name=\"ttn\">{{NYCS const|timetable|n}}</ref> A white tiled curtain wall separates the express tracks from the local tracks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/unionm/unionm3.jpg|title=Looking down the simple Manhattan-bound platform at Union Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=December 22, 2008|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBoth platforms are columnless except for a section at their extreme north ends,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/unionm/unionm3.jpg|title=Looking down the simple Manhattan-bound platform at Union Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=December 22, 2008|website=subwaynut.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> where they were extended in 1970 to accommodate 10-car trains. Here, the columns are cream colored I-beams. The ceiling is lower in this section.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/unionm/unionm6.jpg|title=The ceiling gets extremely low right at the northern end of the station at Union Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=December 22, 2008|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/unionm/unionm5.jpg|title=Another view down the simple Manhattan-bound side platform at Union Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=December 22, 2008|website=subwaynut.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the station's 1970 renovation, it was finished all in white and marble tile, and it had its own color scheme to allow regular passengers to identify the station based only on the color of the marble trimmings.<ref name=\":10\" /> Since the renovation, the station walls have consisted of white cinderblock tiles, except for small recesses in the walls, which contain gray-painted cinderblock tiles. The gray cinderblock field contains the station-name signs and white text pointing to the exits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/unionm/unionm4.jpg|title=A close up of a Union Street station sign on the platform wall, with the 1960s arrow pointing for the exit beneath it.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=December 22, 2008|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Exits===\nEach platform has one same-level [[fare control]] area in the center and there are no crossovers or crossunders to allow free transfer between directions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nycsubway.org/perl/show?122221|title=Bay Ridge-bound fare control|last=Tobar|first=Roberto C.|date=May 20, 2011|website=www.nycsubway.org|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> The Manhattan-bound side has a fare control area, a [[turnstile]] bank, token booth, and two street stairs. The stairs on the Manhattan-bound platform go up to the southeast corner of Union Street and Fourth Avenue while those on the Bay Ridge-bound platform goes up to the southwest corner. The Bay Ridge-bound side has a fare control area, a [[turnstile]] bank without a token booth, and two street stairs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/unionm/unionm11.jpg|title=Going down to the now unstaffed Bay Ridge-bound fare control area|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=May 9, 2013|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"MTA-ParkSlopeMap-2015\">{{cite web|title=MTA Neighborhood Maps: Park Slope|url=http://web.mta.info/maps/neighborhoods/bkn/B3_Park_Slope_2015.pdf|website=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|mta.info]]|publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|accessdate=August 2, 2015|date=2015}}</ref>\n\n{{Clear|left}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|position=right|Union Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)}}\n* {{NYCS ref|http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/stations?216:2870|BMT 4th Avenue|Union Street}}\n* The Subway Nut \u2014 [http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/unionm/index.php Union Street Pictures]\n* MTA's Arts For Transit \u2014 [https://web.archive.org/web/20110606073450/http://mta.info/mta/aft/permanentart/permart.html?agency=nyct&line=M&station=13&xdev=1339 Union Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)]\n* [https://maps.google.com/?ie=UTF8&ll=40.677115,-73.983328&spn=0,359.986567&z=17&lci=transit&layer=c&cbll=40.677228,-73.983256&panoid=21WG-nYiOCICM5t9pabhQg&cbp=12,336.54,,0,3.63 Union Street entrance from Google Maps Street View]\n* [https://www.google.com/maps/@40.6772079,-73.9830475,3a,75y,62.15h,83.78t/data=!3m7!1e1!3m5!1s-51z5J31USnI%2FWG3GwzS1EZI%2FAAAAAAAAYTo%2FRqvXDLDF-hww1DY9gHkftwOWZaiTYALUQCLIB!2e4!6s%2F%2Flh4.googleusercontent.com%2F-51z5J31USnI%2FWG3GwzS1EZI%2FAAAAAAAAYTo%2FRqvXDLDF-hww1DY9gHkftwOWZaiTYALUQCLIB%2Fw203-h100-p-k-no%2F!7i7168!8i3584!4m3!8m2!3m1!1e1 Platform from Google Maps Street View]\n\n{{NYCS stations navbox by service|lr=y}}\n{{NYCS stations navbox by line|4ave=yes}}\n\n[[Category:BMT Fourth Avenue Line stations]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1915]]\n[[Category:1915 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Park Slope]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations located underground]]\n", "name_user": "63.143.194.54", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Undid revision 952169638 byMaterialscientist(talk))", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Union_Street_station_(BMT_Fourth_Avenue_Line)"}
{"title_page": "25th Street station (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)", "text_new": "{{For|the demolished station actually at 36th Street & Fifth Avenue|36th Street (BMT Fifth Avenue Line)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Short description|New York City Subway station in Brooklyn}}\n{{Infobox NYCS\n| name = 25 Street\n| font_color = black\n| font_color_2 = white\n| bg_color = #FFC800\n| bg_color_2 = #874F17\n| image = 25th Street BMT Fourth Avenue 1279.JPG\n| image_caption = Southbound platform\n| address = 25th Street &amp; Fourth Avenue<br>Brooklyn, NY 11232<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/doh/downloads/pdf/epi/Brooklyn|title=Borough of Brooklyn, New York City|publisher=[[Government of New York City]]|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n| borough = [[Brooklyn]]\n| locale = [[Greenwood Heights, Brooklyn|Greenwood Heights]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|40.6605|N|73.998|W|display=inline,title}}\n| lat_dir = N\n| lon_dir = W\n| division = BMT\n| line = [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]]\n| service = Fourth center local\n| service_header = Fourth center local header\n| connection = {{bus icon}} '''[[NYCT Bus]]''': {{NYC bus link|B63}} <small>(on Fifth Avenue)</small>; {{NYC bus link|B37}} <small>(on [[Third Avenue (Brooklyn)|Third Avenue]])</small><ref>{{cite NYC bus map|B}}</ref>\n| platforms = 2 [[side platform]]s\n| tracks = 4\n| structure = Underground\n| open_date = {{start date and age|1915|June|22|p=y}}\n| wifi = yes\n| code = 031\n| passengers = 1,149,469<ref name=\"ridership\">{{NYCS const|riderref}}</ref>\n| pass_year = 2018\n| pass_percent = -16.3\n| rank = 333<ref name=\"ridership\"/>\n| next_north = {{NYCS next | station=Prospect Avenue | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | service=Fourth center local}}\n| next_south = {{NYCS next | station=36th Street | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | service=Fourth center local}}\n| legend = {{NYCS infobox legend|allexceptnights}}{{NYCS infobox legend|nightsonly}}{{NYCS infobox legend|rushonly}}{{NYCS infobox legend|rushpeak}}\n}}'''25th Street''' is a local [[metro station|station]] on the [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]] of the [[New York City Subway]]. Located at the intersection of 25th Street and Fourth Avenue in [[Greenwood Heights, Brooklyn]], it is served by the [[R (New York City Subway service)|R]] train at all times. The [[D (New York City Subway service)|D]] and [[N (New York City Subway service)|N]] trains also stop here during late nights, and some rush-hour [[W (New York City Subway service)|W]] trains stop here in the peak direction.\n\nThe 25th Street station was constructed as part of the Fourth Avenue Line, which was approved in 1905. Construction on the segment of the line that includes 25th Street started on December 20, 1909, and was completed in May 1912. The station opened on June 22, 1915 as part of the initial portion of the BMT Fourth Avenue Line to [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]]. The platforms were lengthened in 1925 and again during a renovation in 1968\u20131970.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Construction ===\nThe 25th Street station was constructed as part of the Fourth Avenue Line, the plan for which was initially adopted on June 1, 1905.<ref name=\":123\">{{Cite journal|last=Rogoff|first=David|date=May 1961|title=The Fourth Ave. Subway|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BzKvSWhrQBW4d3pvOGZaSERiZEhpQ24xT19DTktkQUVlLW5j/view|journal=New York Division Bulletin|publisher=Electric Railroaders' Association|volume=|pages=2\u201310|access-date=May 8, 2017|via=}}</ref> The Rapid Transit Commission was succeeded on July 1, 1907, by the [[New York Public Service Commission|New York State Public Service Commission]] (PSC), which approved the plan for the line in late 1907.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XoxBAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA18&dq=4th+Avenue+line#v=onepage&q=4th%20Avenue%20line&f=false|page=18|title=Fourth Avenue Subway, Brooklyn's New Transportation Line: A Part of the Dual System of Rapid Transit of the City of New York|date=June 19, 1915|publisher=Public Service Commission|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48901678/|title=Fourth Avenue Subway Is Sent To A Committee|date=March 20, 1908|work=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=May 4, 2017|pages=1\u20132|language=en}}</ref> The contract for the section of the line that included the 25th Street station, Route 11A3, which extended from 10th Street to 27th Street, was awarded on May 22, 1908, to Tidewater Building Company and Thomas B. Bryson for $2,043,162.31 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=2043162.31|start_year=1908|r=-3}}). The [[New York City Board of Estimate]] approved the contract on October 29, 1909.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/53922207/|title=Fourth Avenue Subway To Be Political Issue|date=December 11, 1908|work=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=May 4, 2017|page=1|language=en}}</ref> Construction on the segment started on December 20, 1909, and was completed in May 1912.<ref name=\":123\"/>\n\nAs part of negotiations between New York City, the [[Brooklyn Rapid Transit Company]] (BRT), and the [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company]] for the expansion of the city's transit network, the line was leased to a subsidiary of the BRT. The agreement, known as Contract 4 of the [[Dual Contracts]], was signed on March 19, 1913.<ref name=\":10\" /> 25th Street opened on June 22, 1915, as part of the initial portion of the Fourth Avenue Line to [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]].<ref name=\"Station Opening22\">{{cite web|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48814840/|title=Through Tube to Coney, 48 Minutes: First Train on Fourth Avenue Route Beats West End Line Eleven Minutes|date=June 22, 1915|publisher=[[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]]|accessdate=June 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Station renovations ===\n\n==== 1920s ====\nOn June 27, 1922, the New York State Transit Commission directed its engineers to prepare plans to lengthen the platforms at 23 stations on the lines of the [[Brooklyn\u2013Manhattan Transit Corporation]] (BMT), the successor to the BRT, to accommodate eight-car trains. As part of the project, 25th Street's platforms would have been lengthened from {{Convert|435|feet|meters}} to {{Convert|530|feet|meters}}.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Legislature|first=New York (State)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-ugaAQAAIAAJ&pg=RA3-PA100&dq=%22union+street%22+LENGTHENING&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj8_PLm7tboAhXBhOAKHVx0AzwQ6AEwA3oECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=%22union%20street%22%20LENGTHENING&f=false|title=Second Annual Report of the Transit Commission (For the Calendar Year 1922)|date=1923|publisher=New York State Transit Commission|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=100|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u5kT80_w6rYC&pg=PA1277&dq=%22union+street%22+%22530+feet%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjngqLU7dboAhVLTt8KHapMD8IQ6AEwCHoECAkQAg#v=onepage&q=%22union%20street%22%20%22530%20feet%22&f=false|title=Proceedings of the Transit Commission, State of New York Volume III From January 1 to December 31, 1923|date=1923|publisher=New York State Transit Commission|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=1277|language=en}}</ref> Progress on the extensions did not occur until February 16, 1925, when the [[New York City Board of Transportation]] (NYCBOT) directed its engineers to prepare plans to lengthen the platforms at this and eleven other stations along the Fourth Avenue Line. It estimated the project's cost to be $633,000 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=633000|start_year=1925|r=-3}}). The BMT had been ordered by the Transit Commission to lengthen these platforms since September 1923.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/02/17/archives/12-bm-t-stations-to-be-lengthehed-transportation-board-orders.html|title=12 B-M. T. Stations To Be Lengthened; Transportation Board Orders Engineers to Prepare Contracts for Brooklyn Work. Cost Put At $633,000 Letter to Commission Urges That Company Be Compelled to Buy New Cars.|date=February 17, 1925|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 4, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The NYCBOT received bids for the project on February 25, 1926.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48193500/the-brooklyn-citizen/|title=Board Receives Platform Bids For B.M.T. Lines. Six Companies Submit Prices for Extending Subway Stations|date=1926-02-26|work=The Brooklyn Citizen|access-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live|pages=5}}</ref> The contract was awarded to Corson Construction Company for $345,021 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=345021|start_year=1926|r=-3}}).<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48193684/the-standard-union/|title=Brooklyn Wins Big Improvement Fund|date=1926-03-18|work=Brooklyn Standard Union|access-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live|pages=20}}</ref>\n\n==== 1950s and 1960s ====\nIn July 1959, the [[New York City Transit Authority]] (NYCTA) announced that it would install [[fluorescent lighting]] at the 25th Street station and five other stations along Fourth Avenue for between $175,000 and $200,000. Bids on the project were to be advertised on August 7, 1959 and completed by fall 1960.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47783394/bay-ridge-home-reporter/|title=Our Subway Stations To Be Brighter|date=1959-07-10|work=Bay Ridge Home Reporter|access-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1960s, the [[New York City Transit Authority]] (NYCTA) started a project to lengthen station platforms on its lines in Southern Brooklyn to {{Convert|615|feet|meters|abbr=}} to accommodate 10-car trains.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=New York City Transit Authority Annual Report For The Year June 30, 1960|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=1960|isbn=|location=|pages=16\u201317}}</ref> On July 14, 1967, the NYCTA awarded a contract to conduct test borings at eleven stations on the Fourth Avenue Line, including 25th Street, to W. M. Walsh Corporation for $6,585 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=6585|start_year=1967}}) in preparation of the construction of platform extensions.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=HJTVAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22Union+Street,+9th+Street,%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=borings+JULY|title=Minutes and Proceedings|date=1967|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=379\u2013380|language=en}}</ref> The NYCTA issued an invitation for bids on the project to extend the platforms at stations along the Fourth Avenue Line between [[Pacific Street station (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|Pacific Street]] and [[36th Street station (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|36th Street]], including those at 25th Street, on March 28, 1969.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=-HNIAQAAIAAJ&dq=Group+XXX%E2%80%94Broadway-Fourth+Avenue+Line:+pacific+Street,+Union+Street,+9th+Street&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Group+XXX|title=Engineering News-record|date=1969|publisher=McGraw-Hill|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=63|language=en}}</ref> Funding for the renovation projects came out of the NYCTA's 1969\u20131970 Capital Budget, costing $8,177,890 in total.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=c-gxGpL_JNQC&dq=%22Pacific+Street+to+36th+Street+stations%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=10-car|title=Proceedings of the New York City Transit Authority Relating to Matters Other Than Operation|date=1969|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=280, 435, 487|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs part of the renovation project, the station's platforms were extended,<ref name=\":1\" /> and the station's elaborate mosaic tile walls were covered over with {{convert|8|by|16|in|cm|adj=on}} white cinderblock tiles. The latter change, which was also made to 15 other stations on the [[BMT Broadway Line|BMT Broadway]] and Fourth Avenue Lines, was criticized for being dehumanizing. The NYCTA spokesman stated that the old tiles were in poor condition and that the change was made to improve the appearance of stations and provide uniformity. Furthermore, it did not consider the old mosaics to have \"any great artistic merit\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Burks|first=Edward C.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/02/21/archives/subways-colored-tile-gets-cover-up-job.html|title=Subways' Colored Tile Gets Cover\u2010Up Job|date=1970-02-21|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n== Station layout ==\n{{stack|float=right|\n{{NYCS 4-tracked local station\n|1=Prospect Avenue\n|l1=Prospect Av\n|2=36th Street\n|l2=36 St\n|code=BMT Fourth Avenue Line\n|color=yellow\n|textcolor=black\n|deg=315\n}}\n}}\n{{NYCS Platform Layout IND Fulton Street Line}}\n[[File:25th Street BMT Fourth Avenue 1281.JPG|thumb|right|250px|Original mosaic tiles]]\n\nThis underground station has four tracks and two [[side platform]]s.<ref name=\"tracks2\">{{NYCS const|trackref|trackbook}}</ref> The two center express tracks are used by the D and N trains during daytime hours.<ref name=\"ttd\">{{NYCS const|timetable|d}}</ref><ref name=\"ttn\">{{NYCS const|timetable|n}}</ref> White tiled curtain walls separate the express tracks from the local tracks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/25m/25m7.jpg|title=The Zebra stipes conductors stop boards in the middle of the basically bare Brooklyn-bound platform at 25 Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe platforms have no columns except for a section at the extreme north ends where they were extended in 1970. The ceiling in this area is lower.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Jeremiah |title=Looking towards the Northern end of the Brooklyn-bound platform at 25 Street, where there's an extremely low cieling and lots of columns. This is because this part of the station was added later when platforms were extended. |url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/25m/25m8.jpg |website=subwaynut.com |accessdate=April 19, 2020 |date=June 5, 2009}}</ref> These columns are I-beams and are painted cream colored.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/25m/25m9.jpg|title=Another view of the portion of 25 Street's platform that was added later, with its cream colored columns and very low ceiling.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the station's 1970 renovation, it was finished all in white and marble tile, and it had its own color scheme to allow regular passengers to identify the station based only on the color of the marble trimmings.<ref name=\":10\" /> However, the original trim line is still visible in the fare control areas behind the token booth and [[MetroCard#MetroCard vending machines|MetroCard Vending Machines]]. It is in the standard BMT format with \"25\" number tablets in it at regular intervals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/25m/25m12.jpg|title=The 25 in the trimline of the station entrance|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> Since the renovation, the station walls have consisted of white cinderblock tiles, except for small recesses in the walls, which contain orange-painted cinderblock tiles. The orange cinderblock field contains the station-name signs and white text pointing to the exits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/25m/25m2.jpg|title=A 25 Street sign above a painted arrow that points towards the station exit, on an orange portion of the platform wall.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Exits===\nEach platform has a same-level [[fare control]] area in the center. As a result, there is no free transfer between directions. Each fare control area has a [[turnstile]] bank, token booth, and single street stair.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/25m/25m5.jpg|title=Looking out to the fare control area for the Brooklyn-bound platform at 25 Street. The area is quite small with a single staircase up to the street and a narrow token booth.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> The staircase on the Bay Ridge-bound platform goes up to the southwest corner of 25th Street and Fourth Avenue while the one on the Manhattan-bound side goes up to the southeast corner.<ref name=maps>{{cite web|title=MTA Neighborhood Maps: Sunset Park|url=http://web.mta.info/maps/neighborhoods/bkn/B9-Sunset_Park_2015.pdf|website=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|mta.info]]|publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|accessdate=August 2, 2015|date=2015}}</ref>\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|25th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)}}\n* {{NYCS ref|http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/stations?216:183|BMT 4th Avenue|25th Street}}\n* The Subway Nut \u2014 [http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/25m/index.php 25th Street Pictures]\n* [https://maps.google.com/?ie=UTF8&ll=40.660522,-73.998091&spn=0,359.986567&z=17&lci=transit&layer=c&cbll=40.660579,-73.99819&panoid=RmbAy4q1QnbFxYOuy9eu1Q&cbp=12,243.18,,0,5 25th Street entrance from Google Maps Street View]\n* [https://www.google.com/maps/@40.6603546,-73.998291,3a,75y,267.69h,88.94t/data=!3m7!1e1!3m5!1s--VDhvpTfYIQ%2FWG3KNcfFOOI%2FAAAAAAAAYWM%2FMXHgP2eDhYYxI31gneZgPl3ZBg-mh0uUACLIB!2e4!6s%2F%2Flh6.googleusercontent.com%2F--VDhvpTfYIQ%2FWG3KNcfFOOI%2FAAAAAAAAYWM%2FMXHgP2eDhYYxI31gneZgPl3ZBg-mh0uUACLIB%2Fw203-h100-p-k-no%2F!7i7168!8i3584!4m3!8m2!3m1!1e1 Platform from Google Maps Street View]\n\n{{NYCS stations navbox by service|lr=y}}\n{{NYCS stations navbox by line|4ave=yes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:25th Street (Bmt Fourth Avenue Line)}}\n[[Category:BMT Fourth Avenue Line stations]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations located underground]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in the United States opened in 1915]]\n[[Category:1915 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the demolished station actually at 36th Street & Fifth Avenue|36th Street (BMT Fifth Avenue Line)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Short description|New York City Subway station in Brooklyn}}\n{{Infobox NYCS\n| name = 25 Street\n| font_color = black\n| font_color_2 = white\n| bg_color = #FFC800\n| bg_color_2 = #874F17\n| image = 25th Street BMT Fourth Avenue 1279.JPG\n| image_caption = Southbound platform\n| address = 25th Street &amp; Fourth Avenue<br>Brooklyn, NY 11232<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/doh/downloads/pdf/epi/Brooklyn|title=Borough of Brooklyn, New York City|publisher=[[Government of New York City]]|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n| borough = [[Brooklyn]]\n| locale = [[Greenwood Heights, Brooklyn|Greenwood Heights]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|40.6605|N|73.998|W|display=inline,title}}\n| lat_dir = N\n| lon_dir = W\n| division = BMT\n| line = [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]]\n| service = Fourth center local\n| service_header = Fourth center local header\n| connection = {{bus icon}} '''[[NYCT Bus]]''': {{NYC bus link|B63}} <small>(on Fifth Avenue)</small>; {{NYC bus link|B37}} <small>(on [[Third Avenue (Brooklyn)|Third Avenue]])</small><ref>{{cite NYC bus map|B}}</ref>\n| platforms = 2 [[side platform]]s\n| tracks = 4\n| structure = Underground\n| open_date = {{start date and age|1915|June|22|p=y}}\n| wifi = yes\n| code = 031\n| passengers = 1,149,469<ref name=\"ridership\">{{NYCS const|riderref}}</ref>\n| pass_year = 2018\n| pass_percent = -16.3\n| rank = 333<ref name=\"ridership\"/>\n| next_north = {{NYCS next | station=Prospect Avenue | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | service=Fourth center local}}\n| next_south = {{NYCS next | station=36th Street | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | service=Fourth center local}}\n| legend = {{NYCS infobox legend|allexceptnights}}{{NYCS infobox legend|nightsonly}}{{NYCS infobox legend|rushonly}}{{NYCS infobox legend|rushpeak}}\n}}'''25th Street''' is a local [[metro station|station]] on the [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]] of the [[New York City Subway]]. Located at the intersection of 25th Street and Fourth Avenue in [[Greenwood Heights, Brooklyn]], it is served by the [[R (New York City Subway service)|R]] train at all times. The [[D (New York City Subway service)|D]] and [[N (New York City Subway service)|N]] trains also stop here during late nights, and some rush-hour [[W (New York City Subway service)|W]] trains stop here in the peak direction.\n\nThe 25th Street station was constructed as part of the Fourth Avenue Line, which was approved in 1905. Construction on the segment of the line that includes 25th Street started on December 20, 1909, and was completed in May 1912. The station opened on June 22, 1915 as part of the initial portion of the BMT Fourth Avenue Line to [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]]. The platforms were lengthened in 1925 and again during a renovation in 1968\u20131970.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Construction ===\nThe 25th Street station was constructed as part of the Fourth Avenue Line, the plan for which was initially adopted on June 1, 1905.<ref name=\":123\">{{Cite journal|last=Rogoff|first=David|date=May 1961|title=The Fourth Ave. Subway|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BzKvSWhrQBW4d3pvOGZaSERiZEhpQ24xT19DTktkQUVlLW5j/view|journal=New York Division Bulletin|publisher=Electric Railroaders' Association|volume=|pages=2\u201310|access-date=May 8, 2017|via=}}</ref> The Rapid Transit Commission was succeeded on July 1, 1907, by the [[New York Public Service Commission|New York State Public Service Commission]] (PSC), which approved the plan for the line in late 1907.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XoxBAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA18&dq=4th+Avenue+line#v=onepage&q=4th%20Avenue%20line&f=false|page=18|title=Fourth Avenue Subway, Brooklyn's New Transportation Line: A Part of the Dual System of Rapid Transit of the City of New York|date=June 19, 1915|publisher=Public Service Commission|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48901678/|title=Fourth Avenue Subway Is Sent To A Committee|date=March 20, 1908|work=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=May 4, 2017|pages=1\u20132|language=en}}</ref> The contract for the section of the line that included the 25th Street station, Route 11A3, which extended from 10th Street to 27th Street, was awarded on May 22, 1908, to Tidewater Building Company and Thomas B. Bryson for $2,043,162.31 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=2043162.31|start_year=1908|r=-3}}). The [[New York City Board of Estimate]] approved the contract on October 29, 1909.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/53922207/|title=Fourth Avenue Subway To Be Political Issue|date=December 11, 1908|work=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=May 4, 2017|page=1|language=en}}</ref> Construction on the segment started on December 20, 1909, and was completed in May 1912.<ref name=\":123\"/>\n\nAs part of negotiations between New York City, the [[Brooklyn Rapid Transit Company]] (BRT), and the [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company]] for the expansion of the city's transit network, the line was leased to a subsidiary of the BRT. The agreement, known as Contract 4 of the [[Dual Contracts]], was signed on March 19, 1913.<ref name=\":10\" /> 25th Street opened on June 22, 1915, as part of the initial portion of the Fourth Avenue Line to [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]].<ref name=\"Station Opening22\">{{cite web|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48814840/|title=Through Tube to Coney, 48 Minutes: First Train on Fourth Avenue Route Beats West End Line Eleven Minutes|date=June 22, 1915|publisher=[[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]]|accessdate=June 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Station renovations ===\n\n==== 1920s ====\nOn June 27, 1922, the New York State Transit Commission directed its engineers to prepare plans to lengthen the platforms at 23 stations on the lines of the [[Brooklyn\u2013Manhattan Transit Corporation]] (BMT), the successor to the BRT, to accommodate eight-car trains. As part of the project, 25th Street's platforms would have been lengthened from {{Convert|435|feet|meters}} to {{Convert|530|feet|meters}}.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Legislature|first=New York (State)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-ugaAQAAIAAJ&pg=RA3-PA100&dq=%22union+street%22+LENGTHENING&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj8_PLm7tboAhXBhOAKHVx0AzwQ6AEwA3oECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=%22union%20street%22%20LENGTHENING&f=false|title=Second Annual Report of the Transit Commission (For the Calendar Year 1922)|date=1923|publisher=New York State Transit Commission|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=100|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u5kT80_w6rYC&pg=PA1277&dq=%22union+street%22+%22530+feet%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjngqLU7dboAhVLTt8KHapMD8IQ6AEwCHoECAkQAg#v=onepage&q=%22union%20street%22%20%22530%20feet%22&f=false|title=Proceedings of the Transit Commission, State of New York Volume III From January 1 to December 31, 1923|date=1923|publisher=New York State Transit Commission|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=1277|language=en}}</ref> Progress on the extensions did not occur until February 16, 1925, when the [[New York City Board of Transportation]] (NYCBOT) directed its engineers to prepare plans to lengthen the platforms at this and eleven other stations along the Fourth Avenue Line. It estimated the project's cost to be $633,000 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=633000|start_year=1925|r=-3}}). The BMT had been ordered by the Transit Commission to lengthen these platforms since September 1923.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/02/17/archives/12-bm-t-stations-to-be-lengthehed-transportation-board-orders.html|title=12 B-M. T. Stations To Be Lengthened; Transportation Board Orders Engineers to Prepare Contracts for Brooklyn Work. Cost Put At $633,000 Letter to Commission Urges That Company Be Compelled to Buy New Cars.|date=February 17, 1925|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 4, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The NYCBOT received bids for the project on February 25, 1926.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48193500/the-brooklyn-citizen/|title=Board Receives Platform Bids For B.M.T. Lines. Six Companies Submit Prices for Extending Subway Stations|date=1926-02-26|work=The Brooklyn Citizen|access-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live|pages=5}}</ref> The contract was awarded to Corson Construction Company for $345,021 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=345021|start_year=1926|r=-3}}).<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48193684/the-standard-union/|title=Brooklyn Wins Big Improvement Fund|date=1926-03-18|work=Brooklyn Standard Union|access-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live|pages=20}}</ref>\n\n==== 1950s and 1960s ====\n[[File:25th Street BMT Fourth Avenue 1281.JPG|thumb|250px|Original mosaic tiles|alt=|left]]In July 1959, the [[New York City Transit Authority]] (NYCTA) announced that it would install [[fluorescent lighting]] at the 25th Street station and five other stations along Fourth Avenue for between $175,000 and $200,000. Bids on the project were to be advertised on August 7, 1959 and completed by fall 1960.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47783394/bay-ridge-home-reporter/|title=Our Subway Stations To Be Brighter|date=1959-07-10|work=Bay Ridge Home Reporter|access-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1960s, the [[New York City Transit Authority]] (NYCTA) started a project to lengthen station platforms on its lines in Southern Brooklyn to {{Convert|615|feet|meters|abbr=}} to accommodate 10-car trains.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=New York City Transit Authority Annual Report For The Year June 30, 1960|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=1960|isbn=|location=|pages=16\u201317}}</ref> On July 14, 1967, the NYCTA awarded a contract to conduct test borings at eleven stations on the Fourth Avenue Line, including 25th Street, to W. M. Walsh Corporation for $6,585 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=6585|start_year=1967}}) in preparation of the construction of platform extensions.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=HJTVAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22Union+Street,+9th+Street,%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=borings+JULY|title=Minutes and Proceedings|date=1967|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=379\u2013380|language=en}}</ref> The NYCTA issued an invitation for bids on the project to extend the platforms at stations along the Fourth Avenue Line between [[Pacific Street station (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|Pacific Street]] and [[36th Street station (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|36th Street]], including those at 25th Street, on March 28, 1969.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=-HNIAQAAIAAJ&dq=Group+XXX%E2%80%94Broadway-Fourth+Avenue+Line:+pacific+Street,+Union+Street,+9th+Street&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Group+XXX|title=Engineering News-record|date=1969|publisher=McGraw-Hill|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=63|language=en}}</ref> Funding for the renovation projects came out of the NYCTA's 1969\u20131970 Capital Budget, costing $8,177,890 in total.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=c-gxGpL_JNQC&dq=%22Pacific+Street+to+36th+Street+stations%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=10-car|title=Proceedings of the New York City Transit Authority Relating to Matters Other Than Operation|date=1969|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=280, 435, 487|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs part of the renovation project, the station's platforms were extended,<ref name=\":1\" /> and the station's elaborate mosaic tile walls were covered over with {{convert|8|by|16|in|cm|adj=on}} white cinderblock tiles. The latter change, which was also made to 15 other stations on the [[BMT Broadway Line|BMT Broadway]] and Fourth Avenue Lines, was criticized for being dehumanizing. The NYCTA spokesman stated that the old tiles were in poor condition and that the change was made to improve the appearance of stations and provide uniformity. Furthermore, it did not consider the old mosaics to have \"any great artistic merit\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Burks|first=Edward C.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/02/21/archives/subways-colored-tile-gets-cover-up-job.html|title=Subways' Colored Tile Gets Cover\u2010Up Job|date=1970-02-21|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n== Station layout ==\n{{stack|float=right|\n{{NYCS 4-tracked local station\n|1=Prospect Avenue\n|l1=Prospect Av\n|2=36th Street\n|l2=36 St\n|code=BMT Fourth Avenue Line\n|color=yellow\n|textcolor=black\n|deg=315\n}}\n}}\n{{NYCS Platform Layout IND Fulton Street Line}}\n[[File:25th Street BMT Entrance.JPG|thumb|An entrance to the Manhattan-bound platform]]\nThis underground station has four tracks and two [[side platform]]s.<ref name=\"tracks2\">{{NYCS const|trackref|trackbook}}</ref> The R stops here at all times;<ref name=\"ttr\">{{NYCS const|timetable|r}}</ref> some rush-hour W trains stop here in the peak direction;<ref name=\"ttw\">{{NYCS const|timetable|w}}</ref> and the D and N stop here during late nights, but use the center express tracks to bypass the station during daytime hours.<ref name=\"ttd\">{{NYCS const|timetable|d}}</ref><ref name=\"ttn\">{{NYCS const|timetable|n}}</ref> White tiled curtain walls separate the express tracks from the local tracks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/25m/25m7.jpg|title=The Zebra stipes conductors stop boards in the middle of the basically bare Brooklyn-bound platform at 25 Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe platforms have no columns except for a section at the extreme north ends where they were extended in 1970. The ceiling in this area is lower.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Jeremiah |title=Looking towards the Northern end of the Brooklyn-bound platform at 25 Street, where there's an extremely low cieling and lots of columns. This is because this part of the station was added later when platforms were extended. |url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/25m/25m8.jpg |website=subwaynut.com |accessdate=April 19, 2020 |date=June 5, 2009}}</ref> These columns are I-beams and are painted cream colored.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/25m/25m9.jpg|title=Another view of the portion of 25 Street's platform that was added later, with its cream colored columns and very low ceiling.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the station's 1970 renovation, it was finished all in white and marble tile, and it had its own color scheme to allow regular passengers to identify the station based only on the color of the marble trimmings.<ref name=\":10\" /> However, the original trim line is still visible in the fare control areas behind the token booth and [[MetroCard#MetroCard vending machines|MetroCard Vending Machines]]. It is in the standard BMT format with \"25\" number tablets in it at regular intervals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/25m/25m12.jpg|title=The 25 in the trimline of the station entrance|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> Since the renovation, the station walls have consisted of white cinderblock tiles, except for small recesses in the walls, which contain orange-painted cinderblock tiles. The orange cinderblock field contains the station-name signs and white text pointing to the exits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/25m/25m2.jpg|title=A 25 Street sign above a painted arrow that points towards the station exit, on an orange portion of the platform wall.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Exits===\nEach platform has a same-level [[fare control]] area in the center. As a result, there is no free transfer between directions. Each fare control area has a [[turnstile]] bank, token booth, and single street stair.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/25m/25m5.jpg|title=Looking out to the fare control area for the Brooklyn-bound platform at 25 Street. The area is quite small with a single staircase up to the street and a narrow token booth.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 5, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> The staircase on the Bay Ridge-bound platform goes up to the southwest corner of 25th Street and Fourth Avenue while the one on the Manhattan-bound side goes up to the southeast corner.<ref name=maps>{{cite web|title=MTA Neighborhood Maps: Sunset Park|url=http://web.mta.info/maps/neighborhoods/bkn/B9-Sunset_Park_2015.pdf|website=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|mta.info]]|publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|accessdate=August 2, 2015|date=2015}}</ref>\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|25th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)}}\n* {{NYCS ref|http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/stations?216:183|BMT 4th Avenue|25th Street}}\n* The Subway Nut \u2014 [http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/25m/index.php 25th Street Pictures]\n* [https://maps.google.com/?ie=UTF8&ll=40.660522,-73.998091&spn=0,359.986567&z=17&lci=transit&layer=c&cbll=40.660579,-73.99819&panoid=RmbAy4q1QnbFxYOuy9eu1Q&cbp=12,243.18,,0,5 25th Street entrance from Google Maps Street View]\n* [https://www.google.com/maps/@40.6603546,-73.998291,3a,75y,267.69h,88.94t/data=!3m7!1e1!3m5!1s--VDhvpTfYIQ%2FWG3KNcfFOOI%2FAAAAAAAAYWM%2FMXHgP2eDhYYxI31gneZgPl3ZBg-mh0uUACLIB!2e4!6s%2F%2Flh6.googleusercontent.com%2F--VDhvpTfYIQ%2FWG3KNcfFOOI%2FAAAAAAAAYWM%2FMXHgP2eDhYYxI31gneZgPl3ZBg-mh0uUACLIB%2Fw203-h100-p-k-no%2F!7i7168!8i3584!4m3!8m2!3m1!1e1 Platform from Google Maps Street View]\n\n{{NYCS stations navbox by service|lr=y}}\n{{NYCS stations navbox by line|4ave=yes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:25th Street (Bmt Fourth Avenue Line)}}\n[[Category:BMT Fourth Avenue Line stations]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations located underground]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in the United States opened in 1915]]\n[[Category:1915 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "63.143.194.54", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Undid revision 952169683 byMaterialscientist(talk))", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/25th_Street_station_(BMT_Fourth_Avenue_Line)"}
{"title_page": "2014 Brazilian economic crisis", "text_new": "{{short description|Crisis that began during the presidency of Dilma Rousseff}}\n{{Copy edit|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:Brazil's fall (The Economist).jpg|thumb|January 2016 cover of ''[[The Economist]]'' magazine about the crisis. The cover depicts then-president Dilma Rousseff.]]\n\nFrom mid-2014 onward, [[Brazil]] experienced a severe [[financial crisis#Wider economic crisis|economic crisis]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/02/michel-temer-signs-security-decree-stem-rio-violence-180216183747559.html|title=Michel Temer signs security decree to stem Rio violence|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2018-02-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Barua |first1=Akrur |title=Brazil: Yearning for the good times |url=http://dupress.com/articles/global-economic-outlook-q2-2016-brazil/ |series=Global Economic Outlook, Q2 2016 |publisher=Deloitte University Press |accessdate=21 May 2016 |date=29 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160823114946/http://dupress.com/articles/global-economic-outlook-q2-2016-brazil/ |archive-date=23 August 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The country's [[gross domestic product|Gross Domestic Product]] (GDP) fell by 3.5% in 2015 and 3.3% in 2016, after which an economic recovery began.\n\nThe economic crisis occurred alongside a political crisis that resulted in the impeachment of former president [[Dilma Rousseff]]. Together these events caused mass popular dissatisfaction with the political system. In the first quarter of 2017, Brazil's GDP rose by 1%. This was the first GDP increase to occur in eight consecutive quarters. Finance Minister [[Henrique Meirelles]] announced that Brazil had \"emerged from the greatest crisis of the century\". <ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2017-03/08/c_136110450.htm |title=Brazil GDP falls by 3.6 percent in 2016 |author=Mu Xuequan |date=March 8, 2017}}</ref> However, the rise in GDP marked only the end of a technical recession, not the end of the crisis.\n\nDuring the economic crisis, high unemployment rates were reported throughout the country, and there was widespread uncertainty regarding Brazil's economic future following a series of political scandals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/pib-positivo-e-saida-tecnica-da-recessao-mas-recuperacao-e-incerta-entenda.ghtml|title=PIB positivo \u00e9 'sa\u00edda t\u00e9cnica' da recess\u00e3o, mas recupera\u00e7\u00e3o \u00e9 incerta; entenda|date=2017-06-01|author=Darlan Alvarenga|accessdate=5 June 2017|work=G1}}</ref> The [[recession]] was the second most severe in the country's [[economic history of Brazil|history]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,com-revisao-ultima-recessao-deixa-de-ser-a-maior-da-historia,70002628638|title=Com revis\u00e3o, \u00faltima recess\u00e3o deixa de ser a maior da hist\u00f3ria |work=Estad\u00e3o|accessdate=9 January 2020|date=1 December 2018|author=Vinicius Neder}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://oglobo.globo.com/economia/estagnacao-recessao-ou-depressao-pib-confirma-retomada-mais-fraca-das-ultimas-decadas-23704758|title=Estagna\u00e7\u00e3o, recess\u00e3o ou depress\u00e3o? PIB confirma retomada mais fraca das \u00faltimas d\u00e9cadas  |work=O Globo|accessdate=9 January 2020|date=30 May 2019|author=Gabriel Martins}}</ref><ref name=\"book\" /> and was followed by the slowest recovery.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\n== Context ==\n=== Economic ===\nBrazil's economy is largely dependent on the export of [[commodities]], particularly iron ore, petroleum and soy. From the late 1990s till 2012, prices for these export commodities rose significantly (partly because of increasing demand from [[China]]), resulting in about two decades of economic growth. As a result of the economic crisis, Brazil's GDP dropped sharply, leading to high unemployment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/economia/noticia/2016-05/crise-internacional-e-problemas-internos-sao-causas-do-desemprego-no-brasil|title=Crise internacional e problemas internos s\u00e3o causas do desemprego no Brasil|date=2016-05-01|website=Ag\u00eancia Brasil|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> During [[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva]]'s left-wing presidency from 2003 to 2010, the government redistributed wealth through welfare programs and raised the [[minimum wage]] in order to increase consumption.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite journal|title=Entenda a crise econ\u00f4mica|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/economia/noticia/2016-05/entenda-crise-economica|journal=Ag\u00eancia Brasil |date=15 May 2016 |author=Giselle Garcia |agency=[[Ag\u00eancia Brasil]]}}</ref>\n\nIn response to critics of Lula's [[Socialist economics|socialist economic]] stance, his successor, Dilma Rousseff (president during the crisis), introduced [[Macroeconomics|macroeconomic]] tax exemptions and subsidies. These policies are widely acknowledged as a major factor in the 2014\u201316 economic crisis.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\n=== Political ===\nThe economic crisis was followed and intensified by a political crisis. In 2014, a series of corruption scandals uncovered by [[Operation Car Wash]] engulfed many influential politicians. In the presidential election of the same year, President [[Dilma Rousseff]] was re-elected to a second term, defeating the [[Brazilian Social Democracy Party|PSDB]] candidate [[A\u00e9cio Neves]] by a narrow margin.<ref>{{cite web|title=Na disputa mais acirrada da hist\u00f3ria, Dilma \u00e9 reeleita presidente do Brasil - 26/10/2014 - Poder|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/2014/10/1537894-dilma-e-reeleita-presidente-do-brasil.shtml|work=Folha de S.Paulo|accessdate=2019-06-09}}</ref> The result was not recognized by a section of the opposition and provoked popular discontent.<ref>{{cite web|title=Crise econ\u00f4mica e corrup\u00e7\u00e3o marcar\u00e3o a nova presid\u00eancia|url=https://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2014/10/26/politica/1414356634_215134.html|work=EL PA\u00cdS|date=2014-10-27|accessdate=2019-06-09|first=Antonio Jim\u00e9nez|last=Barca}}</ref> Due to the disputed legitimacy of the election, the Operation Car Wash investigation, and the economic crisis, dissatisfaction with the government became widespread. By 2015, Rousseff's approval rating had plummeted to 8% according to a [[Datafolha]] survey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2015/08/17/brazils-corruption-scandal-economy-drive-rousseffs-ratings-to-record-low/|title=Brazil\u2019s corruption scandal, economy drive Rousseff\u2019s ratings to record low|last=NW|first=1615 L. St|last2=Suite 800Washington|website=Pew Research Center|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31|last3=Inquiries|first3=DC 20036USA202-419-4300 {{!}} Main202-857-8562 {{!}} Fax202-419-4372 {{!}} Media}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=http://media.folha.uol.com.br/datafolha/2015/08/06/avaliacao_dilma_agosto_2015.pdf|title=Avalia\u00e7\u00e3do DO Governo Dilma Rousseff|publisher=Datafolha Instituto|year=2015|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== Causes ==\n===Slowdown of the Chinese economy and fall in commodity prices===\nAccording to Steve Tobin, a researcher at the [[International Labour Organization]] (ILO), decreased external [[demand]] for Brazilian products, particularly from China, plus the fall in commodity prices, contributed to the crisis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/economia/noticia/2016-05/crise-internacional-e-problemas-internos-sao-causas-do-desemprego-no-brasil|title=Crise internacional e problemas internos s\u00e3o causas do desemprego no Brasil|date=2016-05-01|website=Ag\u00eancia Brasil|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Silvia Matos, a researcher at the Brazilian think-tank and university [[Get\u00falio Vargas Foundation]], concluded that external factors were responsible for 30% of the crisis.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=MjY8DwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=A Crise de Crescimento do Brasil|author=FGV|publisher=Elsevier Brasil|language=pt-BR|isbn=9788535266382|date=2016-05-05}}</ref> During the downturn, the Brazilian economy exhibited structural weaknesses that had never been seen before, such as low [[productivity]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Crise internacional e problemas internos s\u00e3o causas do desemprego no Brasil|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/economia/noticia/2016-05/crise-internacional-e-problemas-internos-sao-causas-do-desemprego-no-brasil|journal=Ag\u00eancia Brasil}}</ref>\n=== Macroeconomic policy errors ===\n[[Image:Entrevistas_Diversas_(14879045080).jpg|thumb|[[Guido Mantega]], Finance Minister, during the first Dilma administration. In July 2012, he admitted for the first time that the government had put into practice a new \"macroeconomic matrix\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Mantega indica novo modelo econ\u00f4mico|url=https://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,mantega-indica-novo-modelo-economico-imp-,896017|work=Estad\u00e3o|location=Bras\u00edlia|author=Beatriz Abreu|date=5 July 2012|accessdate=11 December 2019}}</ref>]]\n\nAlthough decreasing prices for Brazil's exports contributed to the economic crisis, there is a consensus that the primary cause was internal. [[Gustavo Franco]], former president of the [[Central Bank of Brazil]], has asserted that the crisis was entirely self-inflicted by a series of \"local macroeconomic measures that went wrong.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=A crise brasileira n\u00e3o vem de fora, ela foi autoinfligida|url=https://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2015/03/25/economia/1427322429_883162.html|work=El Pa\u00eds |date=27 March 2015}}</ref> These measures are collectively known as the ''{{ill|Nova Matriz Econ\u00f4mica|pt|Nova Matriz Econ\u00f4mica|vertical-align=sup}}'' (\"New Economic Matrix\"). \n\nPreviously, the government had played a major role in the expansion of the internal market by stimulating consumption, raising the national minimum wage, transferring wealth and expanding credit. By the end of Lula's administration, entrepreneurs and industrialists began to question the sustainability of these policies. They complained about the national industry's declining share of Brazilian GDP.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\nIn response to these concerns, Rousseff created the New Economic Matrix in an attempt to help the Brazilian industry become more competitive internationally. These measures included tax exemptions and subsidies which ultimately failed to stimulate industry. Productivity, after growing by 2.7% in 2010, fell by 0.9% and 3.7% in the following two years, shrinking government revenues and thus requiring reductions in public investment.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\n=== Political instability ===\nIn the same year the crisis began, a major corruption scheme involving top politicians and major companies such as the oil giant [[Petrobras]] was uncovered by [[Operation Car Wash]]. It is estimated that Operation Car Wash caused Brazil's GDP to contract by 1 to 1.5%.<ref>{{cite journal|date=2017-06-02|title=A Lava Jato est\u00e1 corroendo o PIB. E da\u00ed?|url=https://www.istoedinheiro.com.br/lava-jato-esta-corroendo-o-pib-e-dai/|journal=Isto \u00c9 Dinheiro|publisher=Editora tr\u00eas}}</ref>\n\n== Consequences ==\n=== Unemployment ===\n[[File:Evolu\u00e7\u00e3o do desemprego 2012-2017.png|thumb|355px|The unemployment rate from 2012 to 2017. Each vertical line corresponds to a month.<ref name=\"desemprego\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171106064226/https://br.advfn.com/indicadores/pnad|title=Desemprego {{!}} Pnad {{!}} IBGE|date=2017-11-06|accessdate=2017-11-26}}</ref>]]\nBefore the recession, Brazil's [[unemployment]] rate hovered around 6.8% for most of 2014, but began increasing in February 2015, resulting in a 2015 average of 8.5%. The economy lost more than 1.5 million jobs throughout 2015, fueling public discontent against the political establishment and the political leadership of the [[Workers' Party (Brazil)|Worker's Party]] and President [[Dilma Rousseff]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-03-15/brazil-s-unemployment-jumps-in-2015-adding-to-rousseff-s-woes|title=Brazil's unemployment jumps in 2015, adding to Rousseff's woes|publisher=Bloomberg}}</ref> The unemployment rate continued to rise throughout 2016 to finish the year at 12.0%, with 12.3 million people unemployed and an estimated 2.8 million private-sector jobs cut over the preceding two years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-brazil-economy-employment-idUSKBN15F1LE|title=Brazil's jobless rate ends 2016 at 12 percent with 12.3 million unemployed|publisher=Reuters|date=1 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nYoung people were affected most by the worsening job market. While the overall unemployment rate was 12.7% in the first trimester of 2019, the rate in people from 14 to 17 years was 44.5% and 27.3% for people from 18 to 24 years. \n\nExperts expressed concern for the unintended economic and social repercussions for Brazil's younger population, as the economic crisis decreased social security contributions and depreciated [[human capital]] (caused by the decrease in the technical capacity of future workers).<ref>{{cite web |title=Desemprego deixa heran\u00e7a maldita aos jovens e cicatrizes no pa\u00eds |url=https://exame.abril.com.br/economia/desemprego-deixa-heranca-maldita-aos-jovens-e-cicatrizes-no-pais/ |work=Exame|date=28 June 2019|author=Ligia Tuon|accessdate=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Recession ===\n[[File:Crescimento do PIB do Brasil entre 2010 e 2016.png|355px|thumb|Change in GDP from 2010 to 2016 in Brazil.<ref name=\"oglobo\">{{cite web|title=Economia encolhe 3,6% em 2016 e pa\u00eds tem pior recess\u00e3o da hist\u00f3ria|url=https://oglobo.globo.com/economia/economia-encolhe-36-em-2016-pais-tem-pior-recessao-da-historia-21022917|accessdate=6 June 2017}}</ref> Growth slowed significantly in 2014 which was followed by two consecutive drops.<br /><br />(Note: The values for 2015 and 2016 were later revised to 3,5% and 3,3%, respectively.)]]\n\nAt the end of the second trimester of 2014, the country was in a technical recession. According to some Brazilian economists, a technical recession is negative economic growth for two consecutive quarters. It is different from an actual recession, in which the situation of the country depreciates significantly.<ref>{{cite web |title=Entenda o que a recess\u00e3o t\u00e9cnica significa para a economia|url=https://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,entenda-o-que-a-recessao-tecnica-significa-para-a-economia,384664|work=Estad\u00e3o|author=Alessandra Corr\u00eaa|date=9 June 2009}}</ref> Finance Minister, [[Guido Mantega]], lessened the economic result and, in comparison to Europe, declared that:\n\n{{quote|[In Brazil] we're talking about two trimesters [of negative GDP growth], and we know that the economy is in motion. Recession is when there are rising unemployment and decreasing income. Here we have the opposite.|Guido Mantega, Finance Minister<ref>{{cite web|url=http://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/2014/08/entenda-o-que-e-recessao-tecnica.html|work=G1|date=29 August 2014|accessdate=7 December 2016|title=Entenda o que \u00e9 recess\u00e3o t\u00e9cnica|location=S\u00e3o Paulo}}</ref>|title=|source=}}\n\nRegardless of Mantega's statements, specialists had already spotted signs that a strong recession was well underway, citing the technical recession and later, the small growth of 0.5% at the end of 2014. The expectations were confirmed in the next year when the economy shrunk by 3.5%. In 2016, there was another sharp decrease of 3.3%.<ref>{{cite web|title=Como o Brasil entrou (e pode sair) da maior recess\u00e3o da hist\u00f3ria|url=http://exame.abril.com.br/economia/como-o-brasil-entrou-e-pode-sair-da-maior-recessao-da-historia/|accessdate=24 June 2017|work=EXAME|date=7 March 2017|author=Jo\u00e3o Pedro Caleiro}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Como o Brasil entrou, sozinho, na pior crise da hist\u00f3ria|work=\u00c9poca|accessdate= 24 June 2017|author1=Graziele Oliveira |author2=Marcos Coronato|url=http://epoca.globo.com/ideias/noticia/2016/04/como-o-brasil-entrou-sozinho-na-pior-crise-da-historia.html|date=4 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=3 July 2017|title=Brasil vive a pior recess\u00e3o da hist\u00f3ria|url=http://g1.globo.com/jornal-hoje/noticia/2017/03/brasil-vive-pior-recessao-da-historia.html|accessdate=2017-06-01|work = Jornal Hoje|author1=Renata Capucci |author2=Larissa Castro}}</ref> In the first trimester of 2017, the GDP rose for the first time after eight consecutive trimesters of negative growth.<ref name=\"jn\">{{cite journal|date=2017-06-01|title=PIB do primeiro trimestre cresce 1% ap\u00f3s oito quedas seguidas|language=pt|trans-title=First quarter GDP grows 1% after eight straight falls|url=http://g1.globo.com/jornal-nacional/noticia/2017/06/pib-do-primeiro-trimestre-cresce-1-apos-oito-quedas-seguidas.html|journal=Jornal Nacional|accessdate= 24 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe recession caused a [[fiscal crisis]] and an increasing [[budget deficit]] which, according to Bloomberg, was \"the largest-ever primary budget gap ... as a two-year [[economic recession]] sapped tax collection while expenses grew further.\"<ref>\n{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-03-30/brazil-posts-largest-budget-deficit-for-february-ever\n|title=Brazil posts largest budget deficit for February ever\n|publisher=Bloomberg\n|accessdate=18 May 2016\n}}\n</ref> The government deficit reached 5.8 billion [[Brazilian real|reais]] (US$1.7 billion) in the first three months of 2016, the widest reported since December 2001. The two-year fiscal deterioration can be explained by the decrease in government revenue from taxes as a result of the recession, while government expenses have been growing constantly.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-04-29/brazil-records-worst-ever-first-quarter-budget-deficit|title=Brazil records worst-ever first quarter budget deficit|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=18 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Increase in economic inequality ===\n[[File:Gini da Renda do Trabalho nos Domic\u00edlios per Capita.png|355px|thumb|Evolution of the [[Gini coefficient]] in Brazil from 2012 to 2019. Source:Ibre/FGV<ref name=\"IBRE\" />]]\nA 2019 study by the [[Instituto Brasileiro de Economia]] (Ibre), part of [[Funda\u00e7\u00e3o Get\u00falio Vargas]] (FGV), obtained by the magazine [[Valor Econ\u00f4mico]], showed that the [[Gini coefficient]], which measures the economic inequality in society from 0 to 1, had increased year after year since 2015 and reached its peak in March 2019.\n\nIn 7 years, the accumulated wealth of the top 10% rose by 8.5%, while that of the 40% poorest dropped 14%. The research also showed that people with lower incomes suffered the effects of the crisis more intensely and recovered from the crisis slower. <ref>{{cite web|title=Desigualdade de renda no Brasil atinge o maior patamar j\u00e1 registrado, diz FGV/IBRE|url=https://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/2019/05/21/desigualdade-de-renda-no-brasil-atinge-o-maior-patamar-ja-registrado-diz-fgvibre.ghtml|work=G1|accessdate=2019-05-22|date=21 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Valor\">{{cite web|title=Desigualdade de renda no Brasil sobe pelo 17\u00ba trimestre consecutivo|url=https://www.valor.com.br/brasil/6265917/desigualdade-de-renda-no-brasil-sobe-pelo-17-trimestre-consecutivo|work=Valor Econ\u00f4mico|date=2019-05-19|accessdate=2019-05-22|author=Bruno Villas B\u00f4as|location=Rio de Janeiro}}</ref><ref name=\"IBRE\">{{cite web |title=Levantamento do FGV IBRE aponta desigualdade recorde na renda do trabalho |url=https://portalibre.fgv.br/navegacao-superior/noticias/levantamento-do-fgv-ibre-aponta-desigualdade-recorde-na-renda-do-trabalho.htm |work=IBRE/FGV |accessdate=23 May 2019 |date=21 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to an Ibre researcher, Daniel Duque, the recovery of the job market was concentrated in people with higher qualification and experience, reinforcing the inequality. Many underqualified people gave up trying to get a job, and the loss of hope was \"[...] record high, and it helps to explain why, even after the decrease in unemployment, inequality kept rising.\"<ref name=\"Valor\" />\n\n=== Emigration ===\n{{main article|Brazilian diaspora}}\n[[File:Quantidade de declara\u00e7\u00f5es de sa\u00edda definitiva do Brasil.jpg|thumb|355px|Number of declarations of definite emigration from the country. Source:[[Receita Federal do Brasil|Receita Federal]].<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|title=Cresce n\u00famero de brasileiros que decidem viver no exterior; pa\u00edses oferecem oportunidades de emprego|url=https://g1.globo.com/economia/concursos-e-emprego/noticia/2019/04/03/cresce-numero-de-brasileiros-que-decidem-viver-no-exterior-paises-oferecem-oportunidades-de-emprego.ghtml|work=G1|author=Luiz Guilherme Gerbelli|accessdate=25 October 2019|date=3 April 2019}}</ref>]]\n\nThe number of declarations of definitive departure from the country began to grow in the first year of crisis and has increased steadily ever since, according to [[Receita Federal do Brasil|Receita Federal]]. Among the countries that received the most Brazilian citizens were [[Japan]] and [[Canada]], which, due to low unemployment and aging populations among other reasons, needed a boost to decrease the age of the workforce.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nAccording to a JBJ Partners employee (a company specialized in expatriation to the [[United States]]), many who fled Brazil were qualified workers:\n\n{{quote|We're talking about qualified people. The profile of the immigrant is no longer that of the poor individual looking for better opportunities. They are high executives, who are abandoning their careers to open a business abroad, people with Ph.D., which is sad because the country is losing resources.|Jorge Botrel, a JBJ partner.<ref>{{cite web |title=Com a crise, dispara a quantidade de brasileiros que desistem de viver no Brasil |url=https://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/com-a-crise-dispara-a-quantidade-de-brasileiros-que-desistem-de-viver-no-brasil.ghtml |work=G1|accessdate=25 October 2019|date=17 December 2017|author=Lu\u00edsa Melo}}</ref>}}\n\nAn [[OECD]] report shows a much more elevated number<!-- In comparison to what? -->. In 2016 80,000 Brazilians emigrated legally to one of the member states of the OECD, whereas 99,000 did so in 2017. Similarly, data from Receita Federal shows that the number of people leaving Brazil increased in consecutive years since the beginning of the crisis.<ref>{{cite web |title=Imigra\u00e7\u00e3o de brasileiros para pa\u00edses da OCDE subiu 24%, o terceiro maior aumento |url=https://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2019/09/18/politica/1568843366_553673.html |work=El Pa\u00eds|author=Felipe Betim|accessdate=25 October 2019|date=19 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Credit rating ===\nThis is a table of the credit ratings of the Brazilian economy according to Trading Economics.{{who|date=April 2017}}{{cn|date=April 2017}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Agency !! Rating !! Outlook !! Date\n|-\n| Fitch || BB || negative || May 5, 2016\n|-\n| TE || 34 || negative || Apr 16 2016\n|-\n| Moody's || Ba2 || negative || Feb 24 2016\n|-\n| S&P || BB || negative || Feb 17 2016\n|}\n\n== Anti-crisis measures ==\n[[File:Entrevistas Diversas (30847431200).jpg|[[Henrique Meirelles]], the [[Ministry of Finance (Brazil)|Minister of Finance]] from May 2016 to April 2018.|thumb]]\nSince the impeachment of Dilma Rousseff and [[Michel Temer]]'s subsequent rise to power, several measures, most of which unpopular, were implemented or proposed to get the economy back on track.<ref>{{cite journal|title='Aproveito impopularidade para tomar medidas necess\u00e1rias', diz Temer|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/2016/12/1843702-aproveito-impopularidade-para-tomar-medidas-necessarias-diz-temer.shtml|journal=Folha de S.Paulo|date=22 December 2016|accessdate=17 June 2017|author=Marina Dias Valdo Cruz|location=Bras\u00edlia}}</ref> The most important of which were:\n\n* The {{ill|95\u00ba Constitutional amendment|pt|Emenda Constitucional do Teto dos Gastos P\u00fablicos|vertical-align=sup}} (a.k.a \"new fiscal regime\"): Constitutional amendment which established a \"ceiling\" (upper limit) to government spending for the next 20 years;<ref>{{cite journal|title=Temer elogia aprova\u00e7\u00e3o da PEC do Teto e minimiza menor n\u00famero de votos a favor|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/politica/noticia/2016-12/temer-elogia-aprovacao-da-pec-do-teto-e-minimiza-menor-numero-de-votos|accessdate=17 June 2017|location=Bras\u00edlia|journal= Ag\u00eancia Brasil|date=13 December 2016|author=Paulo Victor Chagas}}</ref>\n* The [[Outsourcing law in Brazil|Outsourcing law]], which allows companies to hire outsourced employees to work on primary activities, and not just secondary activities (such as security or cleaning);<ref>{{cite web|title=Com vetos, Temer sanciona lei que permite terceiriza\u00e7\u00e3o de atividade-fim|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/politica/noticia/2017-03/temer-sanciona-lei-que-permite-terceirizacao-em-atividade-fim-das-empresas|accessdate=17 June 2017|work = Ag\u00eancia Brasil|date=31 March 2017|author=Ivan Richard Esposito|location=Bras\u00edlia}}</ref>\n* The [[Brazil labor reform (2017)|2017 labor reform]], a significant change in the [[Consolidation of Labor Laws]]; and<ref>{{cite web|title=Com flexibiliza\u00e7\u00e3o de v\u00e1rios pontos da CLT, reforma trabalhista divide opini\u00f5es|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/politica/noticia/2017-04/com-flexibilizacao-de-varios-pontos-da-clt-reforma-trabalhista-divide|accessdate=17 June 2017|work = Ag\u00eancia Brasil|location=S\u00e3o Paulo|date=13 April 2017|author=Daniel Mello}}</ref>\n* a pension reform, which the government failed to approve.<ref>{{cite web|title=Governo desiste da vota\u00e7\u00e3o da Previd\u00eancia e anuncia nova pauta priorit\u00e1ria no Congresso|url=https://g1.globo.com/politica/noticia/governo-desiste-da-votacao-da-previdencia-e-anuncia-nova-pauta-prioritaria-no-congresso.ghtml||work = G1|accessdate=26 May 2019|date=19 February 2018|author1=Guilherme Mazui |author2=Roniara Castilhos}}</ref>\n\nOne year after the labor reform was approved, however, it was verified that the decrease in unemployment was minimal, while the contracts of intermittent, outsourced and temporary labor increased.<ref>{{cite web|author=Fabiana Futema|date=10 November 2018|title=Um ano depois, reforma trabalhista n\u00e3o gera empregos esperados|url=https://veja.abril.com.br/economia/um-ano-depois-reforma-trabalhista-nao-gera-empregos-esperados/|work=VEJA.com|accessdate=2019-05-26}}</ref>\n\n== Recovery ==\nIn early 2017, there were already signals that the economy was beginning to recover, however, it was agreed that the process would be long and slow.<ref>{{cite web|title=Recupera\u00e7\u00e3o da economia brasileira ser\u00e1 longa e lenta, aponta 'FT'|url=http://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,recuperacao-da-economia-brasileira-sera-longa-e-lenta-aponta-ft,70001658076}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Recupera\u00e7\u00e3o da economia brasileira ainda \u00e9 lenta, diz presidente do Ita\u00fa|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/mercado/2017/04/1876544-recuperacao-da-economia-brasileira-ainda-e-lenta-diz-presidente-do-itau.shtml}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, a 1% rise in GDP in the first quarter of the year was reported.<ref name=\"jn\"/> It was the first rise of the GDP after eight consecutive falls (two years).<ref name=\":0\">\n{{Cite news|title= PIB do Brasil cresce 1% no 1\u00ba trimestre de 2017, ap\u00f3s 8 quedas seguidas|url=http://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/pib-do-brasil-cresce-10-no-1-trimestre-de-2017.ghtml}}</ref> Minister of Finance [[Henrique Meirelles]] said that the country had left the \"greatest recession of the century.\"<ref>{{citation |title=PIB sobe 1% no 1\u00ba trimestre, ap\u00f3s oito quedas consecutivas|url=http://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,pib-sobe-1-0-no-1-trimestre-apos-oito-quedas-consecutivas,70001821658}}</ref> However, economists say that the growth characterizes only the end of the \"technical recession\" and that it is still too early to claim that the crisis is over, given that unemployment remains high and there's still widespread uncertainty regarding the future of the economy, especially in the aftermath of the recent political scandals.<ref>{{cite web|title=PIB positivo \u00e9 'sa\u00edda t\u00e9cnica' da recess\u00e3o, mas recupera\u00e7\u00e3o \u00e9 incerta; entenda|url=http://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/pib-positivo-e-saida-tecnica-da-recessao-mas-recuperacao-e-incerta-entenda.ghtml|accessdate=5 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Comparisons with other crises ==\n[[Image:Countries_by_Real_GDP_Growth_Rate_(2016).svg|thumb|Real GDP growth in 2016. Source:''CIA World Factbook''<ref>{{cite web|title=The World Factbook \u2014 Central Intelligence Agency|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2003rank.html|work=Central Intelligence Agency (CIA)}}</ref>|355px]]\nIn countries with similar size and wealth, there were a few, but less severe crisis in the same period. In 2015, among [[OECD]] countries, only [[Russia]] went through a recession. Even after the economic sanctions imposed by other countries due to the [[Russian military intervention in Ukraine (2014\u2013present)|conflict in Ukraine]], Russia's GDP fell by only 4% in two years (2015 and 2016). Few other countries in this period were going through a recession, which reinforces the argument that the crisis in Brazil was mainly due to local causes.<ref name=\"book\">{{Cite book|last=Carvalho|first=Laura|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XppWDwAAQBAJ|title=Valsa brasileira: Do boom ao caos econ\u00f4mico|date=2018-05-08|publisher=Editora Todavia S.A|isbn=978-85-93828-63-8|language=pt-BR}}</ref>\n\nIn comparison to other crises in Brazil, it was verified that the 2014 crisis was not the deepest, as previously thought. After the GDP values for 2015 and 2016 were reviewed by the [[Brazilian Institute of Geography and Statistics]] (IBGE), the economy shrank by 8.2% in the period, in contrast to the 8.5% in the 1981 recession. Despite not being the deepest, the crisis was long. It was also followed by the slowest recovery of all.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\nAccording to Codace (committee part of [[Funda\u00e7\u00e3o Get\u00falio Vargas]]), the 1981 crisis lasted nine trimesters, reached its peak in the first trimester of 1983 and, since then, took seven trimesters for the GDP the reach its pre-crisis level. Later, the 1989-1992 crisis lasted 11 trimesters and the recovery time was the same: seven trimesters. This crisis, however, had a lower intensity, with an accumulated decrease in the GDP of 7.7%.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\nIn turn, the GDP after the 2014 crisis will only reach its pre-crisis level in 2022, according to an optimistic estimate, with 20 trimesters of recovery in total. When taking into account not only the GDP, but also the employment rate, the recovery will be even slower. In addition to the sluggish recovery, the new jobs will be of lower quality, including informal and autonomous labor.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Brazil labor reform (2017)]]\n* [[Economy of Brazil]]\n* [[2018 in Brazil]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Government of Michel Temer}}\n{{Financial crises}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2014 Brazilian economic recession}}\n[[Category:2010s economic history]]\n[[Category:2014 in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Economic crises in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Recessions]]\n[[Category:Government of Michel Temer]]\n[[Category:Economic history of Brazil]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Crisis that began during the presidency of Dilma Rousseff}}\n{{Copy edit|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:Brazil's fall (The Economist).jpg|thumb|January 2016 cover of ''[[The Economist]]'' magazine about the crisis. The cover depicts then-president Dilma Rousseff.]]\n\nFrom mid-2014 onward, [[Brazil]] experienced a severe [[financial crisis#Wider economic crisis|economic crisis]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/02/michel-temer-signs-security-decree-stem-rio-violence-180216183747559.html|title=Michel Temer signs security decree to stem Rio violence|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2018-02-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Barua |first1=Akrur |title=Brazil: Yearning for the good times |url=http://dupress.com/articles/global-economic-outlook-q2-2016-brazil/ |series=Global Economic Outlook, Q2 2016 |publisher=Deloitte University Press |accessdate=21 May 2016 |date=29 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160823114946/http://dupress.com/articles/global-economic-outlook-q2-2016-brazil/ |archive-date=23 August 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The country's [[gross domestic product|Gross Domestic Product]] (GDP) fell by 3.5% in 2015 and 3.3% in 2016, after which an economic recovery began.\n\nThe economic crisis occurred alongside a political crisis that resulted in the impeachment of former president [[Dilma Rousseff]]. Together these events caused mass popular dissatisfaction with the political system. In the first quarter of 2017, Brazil's GDP rose by 1%. This was the first GDP increase to occur in eight consecutive quarters. Finance Minister [[Henrique Meirelles]] announced that Brazil had \"emerged from the greatest crisis of the century\". <ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2017-03/08/c_136110450.htm |title=Brazil GDP falls by 3.6 percent in 2016 |author=Mu Xuequan |date=March 8, 2017}}</ref> However, the rise in GDP marked only the end of a technical recession, not the end of the crisis.\n\nDuring the economic crisis, high unemployment rates were reported throughout the country, and there was widespread uncertainty regarding Brazil's economic future following a series of political scandals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/pib-positivo-e-saida-tecnica-da-recessao-mas-recuperacao-e-incerta-entenda.ghtml|title=PIB positivo \u00e9 'sa\u00edda t\u00e9cnica' da recess\u00e3o, mas recupera\u00e7\u00e3o \u00e9 incerta; entenda|date=2017-06-01|author=Darlan Alvarenga|accessdate=5 June 2017|work=G1}}</ref> The [[recession]] was the second most severe in the country's [[economic history of Brazil|history]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,com-revisao-ultima-recessao-deixa-de-ser-a-maior-da-historia,70002628638|title=Com revis\u00e3o, \u00faltima recess\u00e3o deixa de ser a maior da hist\u00f3ria |work=Estad\u00e3o|accessdate=9 January 2020|date=1 December 2018|author=Vinicius Neder}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://oglobo.globo.com/economia/estagnacao-recessao-ou-depressao-pib-confirma-retomada-mais-fraca-das-ultimas-decadas-23704758|title=Estagna\u00e7\u00e3o, recess\u00e3o ou depress\u00e3o? PIB confirma retomada mais fraca das \u00faltimas d\u00e9cadas  |work=O Globo|accessdate=9 January 2020|date=30 May 2019|author=Gabriel Martins}}</ref><ref name=\"book\" /> and was followed by the slowest recovery.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\n== Context ==\n=== Economic ===\nBrazil's economy is largely dependent on the export of [[commodities]], particularly iron ore, petroleum and soy. From the late 1990s till 2012, prices for these export commodities rose significantly (partly because of increasing demand from [[China]]), resulting in about two decades of economic growth. As a result of the economic crisis, Brazil's GDP dropped sharply, leading to high unemployment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/economia/noticia/2016-05/crise-internacional-e-problemas-internos-sao-causas-do-desemprego-no-brasil|title=Crise internacional e problemas internos s\u00e3o causas do desemprego no Brasil|date=2016-05-01|website=Ag\u00eancia Brasil|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> During [[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva]]'s left-wing presidency from 2003 to 2010, the government redistributed wealth through welfare programs and raised the [[minimum wage]] in order to increase consumption.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite journal|title=Entenda a crise econ\u00f4mica|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/economia/noticia/2016-05/entenda-crise-economica|journal=Ag\u00eancia Brasil |date=15 May 2016 |author=Giselle Garcia |agency=[[Ag\u00eancia Brasil]]}}</ref>\n\nIn response to critics of Lula's [[Socialist economics|socialist economic]] stance, his successor, Dilma Rousseff (president during the crisis), introduced [[Macroeconomics|macroeconomic]] tax exemptions and subsidies. These policies are widely acknowledged as a major factor in the 2014\u201316 economic crisis.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\n=== Political ===\nThe economic crisis was followed and intensified by a political crisis. In 2014, a series of corruption scandals uncovered by [[Operation Car Wash]] engulfed many influential politicians. In the presidential election of the same year, President [[Dilma Rousseff]] was re-elected to a second term, defeating the [[Brazilian Social Democracy Party|PSDB]] candidate [[A\u00e9cio Neves]] by a narrow margin.<ref>{{cite web|title=Na disputa mais acirrada da hist\u00f3ria, Dilma \u00e9 reeleita presidente do Brasil - 26/10/2014 - Poder|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/2014/10/1537894-dilma-e-reeleita-presidente-do-brasil.shtml|work=Folha de S.Paulo|accessdate=2019-06-09}}</ref> The result was not recognized by a section of the opposition and provoked popular discontent.<ref>{{cite web|title=Crise econ\u00f4mica e corrup\u00e7\u00e3o marcar\u00e3o a nova presid\u00eancia|url=https://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2014/10/26/politica/1414356634_215134.html|work=EL PA\u00cdS|date=2014-10-27|accessdate=2019-06-09|first=Antonio Jim\u00e9nez|last=Barca}}</ref> Due to the disputed legitimacy of the election, the Operation Car Wash investigation, and the economic crisis, dissatisfaction with the government became widespread. By 2015, Rousseff's approval rating had plummeted to 8% according to a [[Datafolha]] survey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2015/08/17/brazils-corruption-scandal-economy-drive-rousseffs-ratings-to-record-low/|title=Brazil\u2019s corruption scandal, economy drive Rousseff\u2019s ratings to record low|last=NW|first=1615 L. St|last2=Suite 800Washington|website=Pew Research Center|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31|last3=Inquiries|first3=DC 20036USA202-419-4300 {{!}} Main202-857-8562 {{!}} Fax202-419-4372 {{!}} Media}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=http://media.folha.uol.com.br/datafolha/2015/08/06/avaliacao_dilma_agosto_2015.pdf|title=Avalia\u00e7\u00e3do DO Governo Dilma Rousseff|publisher=Datafolha Instituto|year=2015|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== Causes ==\n===Slowdown of the Chinese economy and fall in commodity prices===\nAccording to Steve Tobin, a researcher at the [[International Labour Organization]] (ILO), decreased external [[demand]] for Brazilian products, particularly from China, plus the fall in commodity prices, contributed to the crisis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/economia/noticia/2016-05/crise-internacional-e-problemas-internos-sao-causas-do-desemprego-no-brasil|title=Crise internacional e problemas internos s\u00e3o causas do desemprego no Brasil|date=2016-05-01|website=Ag\u00eancia Brasil|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Silvia Matos, a researcher at the Brazilian think-tank and university [[Get\u00falio Vargas Foundation]], concluded that external factors were responsible for 30% of the crisis.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=MjY8DwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=A Crise de Crescimento do Brasil|author=FGV|publisher=Elsevier Brasil|language=pt-BR|isbn=9788535266382|date=2016-05-05}}</ref> During the downturn, the Brazilian economy exhibited structural weaknesses that had never been seen before, such as low [[productivity]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Crise internacional e problemas internos s\u00e3o causas do desemprego no Brasil|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/economia/noticia/2016-05/crise-internacional-e-problemas-internos-sao-causas-do-desemprego-no-brasil|journal=Ag\u00eancia Brasil}}</ref>\n=== Macroeconomic policy errors ===\n[[Image:Entrevistas_Diversas_(14879045080).jpg|thumb|[[Guido Mantega]], Finance Minister, during the first Dilma administration. In July 2012, he admitted for the first time that the government had put into practice a new \"macroeconomic matrix\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Mantega indica novo modelo econ\u00f4mico|url=https://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,mantega-indica-novo-modelo-economico-imp-,896017|work=Estad\u00e3o|location=Bras\u00edlia|author=Beatriz Abreu|date=5 July 2012|accessdate=11 December 2019}}</ref>]]\n\nAlthough decreasing prices for Brazil's exports contributed to the economic crisis, there is a consensus that the primary cause was internal. [[Gustavo Franco]], former president of the [[Central Bank of Brazil]], has asserted that the crisis was entirely self-inflicted by a series of \"local macroeconomic measures that went wrong.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=A crise brasileira n\u00e3o vem de fora, ela foi autoinfligida|url=https://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2015/03/25/economia/1427322429_883162.html|work=El Pa\u00eds |date=27 March 2015}}</ref> These measures are collectively known as the ''{{ill|Nova Matriz Econ\u00f4mica|pt|Nova Matriz Econ\u00f4mica|vertical-align=sup}}'' (\"New Economic Matrix\"). \n\nPreviously, the government had played a major role in the expansion of the internal market by stimulating consumption, raising the national minimum wage, transferring wealth and expanding credit. By the end of Lula's administration, entrepreneurs and industrialists began to question the sustainability of these policies. They complained about the national industry's declining share of Brazilian GDP.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\nIn response to these concerns, Rousseff created the New Economic Matrix in an attempt to help the Brazilian industry become more competitive internationally. These measures included tax exemptions and subsidies which ultimately failed to stimulate industry. Productivity, after growing by 2.7% in 2010, fell by 0.9% and 3.7% in the following two years, shrinking government revenues and thus requiring reductions in public investment.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\n=== Political instability ===\nIn the same year the crisis began, a major corruption scheme involving top politicians and major companies such as the oil giant [[Petrobras]] was uncovered by [[Operation Car Wash]]. It is estimated that Operation Car Wash caused Brazil's GDP to contract by 1 to 1.5%.<ref>{{cite journal|date=2017-06-02|title=A Lava Jato est\u00e1 corroendo o PIB. E da\u00ed?|url=https://www.istoedinheiro.com.br/lava-jato-esta-corroendo-o-pib-e-dai/|journal=Isto \u00c9 Dinheiro|publisher=Editora tr\u00eas}}</ref>\n\n== Consequences ==\n=== Unemployment ===\n[[File:Evolu\u00e7\u00e3o do desemprego 2012-2017.png|thumb|355px|The unemployment rate from 2012 to 2017. Each vertical line corresponds to a month.<ref name=\"desemprego\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171106064226/https://br.advfn.com/indicadores/pnad|title=Desemprego {{!}} Pnad {{!}} IBGE|date=2017-11-06|accessdate=2017-11-26}}</ref>]]\nBefore the recession, Brazil's [[unemployment]] rate hovered around 6.8% for most of 2014, but began increasing in February 2015, resulting in a 2015 average of 8.5%. The economy lost more than 1.5 million jobs throughout 2015, fueling public discontent against the political establishment and the political leadership of the [[Workers' Party (Brazil)|Worker's Party]] and President [[Dilma Rousseff]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-03-15/brazil-s-unemployment-jumps-in-2015-adding-to-rousseff-s-woes|title=Brazil's unemployment jumps in 2015, adding to Rousseff's woes|publisher=Bloomberg}}</ref> The unemployment rate continued to rise throughout 2016 to finish the year at 12.0%, with 12.3 million people unemployed and an estimated 2.8 million private-sector jobs cut over the preceding two years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-brazil-economy-employment-idUSKBN15F1LE|title=Brazil's jobless rate ends 2016 at 12 percent with 12.3 million unemployed|publisher=Reuters|date=1 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nYoung people were affected most by the worsening job market. While the overall unemployment rate was 12.7% in the first trimester of 2019, the rate in people from 14 to 17 years was 44.5% and 27.3% for people from 18 to 24 years. \n\nExperts expressed concern for the unintended economic and social repercussions for Brazil's younger population, as the economic crisis decreased social security contributions and depreciated [[human capital]] (caused by the decrease in the technical capacity of future workers).<ref>{{cite web |title=Desemprego deixa heran\u00e7a maldita aos jovens e cicatrizes no pa\u00eds |url=https://exame.abril.com.br/economia/desemprego-deixa-heranca-maldita-aos-jovens-e-cicatrizes-no-pais/ |work=Exame|date=28 June 2019|author=Ligia Tuon|accessdate=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Recession ===\n[[File:Crescimento do PIB do Brasil entre 2010 e 2016.png|355px|thumb|Change in GDP from 2010 to 2016 in Brazil.<ref name=\"oglobo\">{{cite web|title=Economia encolhe 3,6% em 2016 e pa\u00eds tem pior recess\u00e3o da hist\u00f3ria|url=https://oglobo.globo.com/economia/economia-encolhe-36-em-2016-pais-tem-pior-recessao-da-historia-21022917|accessdate=6 June 2017}}</ref> Growth slowed significantly in 2014 which was followed by two consecutive drops.<br /><br />(Note: The values for 2015 and 2016 were later revised to 3,5% and 3,3%, respectively.)]]\n\nAt the end of the second trimester of 2014, the country was in a technical recession. According to some Brazilian economists, a technical recession is negative economic growth for two consecutive quarters. It is different from an actual recession, in which the situation of the country depreciates significantly.<ref>{{cite web |title=Entenda o que a recess\u00e3o t\u00e9cnica significa para a economia|url=https://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,entenda-o-que-a-recessao-tecnica-significa-para-a-economia,384664|work=Estad\u00e3o|author=Alessandra Corr\u00eaa|date=9 June 2009}}</ref> Finance Minister, [[Guido Mantega]], lessened the economic result and, in comparison to Europe, declared that:\n\n{{quote|[In Brazil] we're talking about two trimesters [of negative GDP growth], and we know that the economy is in motion. Recession is when there are rising unemployment and decreasing income. Here we have the opposite.|Guido Mantega, Finance Minister<ref>{{cite web|url=http://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/2014/08/entenda-o-que-e-recessao-tecnica.html|work=G1|date=29 August 2014|accessdate=7 December 2016|title=Entenda o que \u00e9 recess\u00e3o t\u00e9cnica|location=S\u00e3o Paulo}}</ref>|title=|source=}}\n\nRegardless of Mantega's statements, specialists had already spotted signs that a strong recession was well underway, citing the technical recession and later, the small growth of 0.5% at the end of 2014. The expectations were confirmed in the next year when the economy shrunk by 3.5%. And in 2016, there was another sharp decrease of 3.3%.<ref>{{cite web|title=Como o Brasil entrou (e pode sair) da maior recess\u00e3o da hist\u00f3ria|url=http://exame.abril.com.br/economia/como-o-brasil-entrou-e-pode-sair-da-maior-recessao-da-historia/|accessdate=24 June 2017|work=EXAME|date=7 March 2017|author=Jo\u00e3o Pedro Caleiro}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Como o Brasil entrou, sozinho, na pior crise da hist\u00f3ria|work=\u00c9poca|accessdate= 24 June 2017|author1=Graziele Oliveira |author2=Marcos Coronato|url=http://epoca.globo.com/ideias/noticia/2016/04/como-o-brasil-entrou-sozinho-na-pior-crise-da-historia.html|date=4 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=3 July 2017|title=Brasil vive a pior recess\u00e3o da hist\u00f3ria|url=http://g1.globo.com/jornal-hoje/noticia/2017/03/brasil-vive-pior-recessao-da-historia.html|accessdate=2017-06-01|work = Jornal Hoje|author1=Renata Capucci |author2=Larissa Castro}}</ref> In the first trimester of 2017, the GDP rose for the first time after eight consecutive trimesters of negative growth.<ref name=\"jn\">{{cite journal|date=2017-06-01|title=PIB do primeiro trimestre cresce 1% ap\u00f3s oito quedas seguidas|language=pt|trans-title=First quarter GDP grows 1% after eight straight falls|url=http://g1.globo.com/jornal-nacional/noticia/2017/06/pib-do-primeiro-trimestre-cresce-1-apos-oito-quedas-seguidas.html|journal=Jornal Nacional|accessdate= 24 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe recession caused a [[fiscal crisis]] and an increasing [[budget deficit]] which, according to Bloomberg, was \"the largest-ever primary budget gap ... as a two-year [[economic recession]] sapped tax collection while expenses grew further.\"<ref>\n{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-03-30/brazil-posts-largest-budget-deficit-for-february-ever\n|title=Brazil posts largest budget deficit for February ever\n|publisher=Bloomberg\n|accessdate=18 May 2016\n}}\n</ref> The government deficit reached 5.8 billion [[Brazilian real|reais]] (US$1.7 billion) in the first three months of 2016, the widest reported since December 2001. The two-year fiscal deterioration can be explained by the decrease in government revenue from taxes as a result of the recession, while government expenses have been growing constantly.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-04-29/brazil-records-worst-ever-first-quarter-budget-deficit|title=Brazil records worst-ever first quarter budget deficit|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=18 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Increase in economic inequality ===\n[[File:Gini da Renda do Trabalho nos Domic\u00edlios per Capita.png|355px|thumb|Evolution of the [[Gini coefficient]] in Brazil from 2012 to 2019. Source:Ibre/FGV<ref name=\"IBRE\" />]]\nA 2019 study by the [[Instituto Brasileiro de Economia]] (Ibre), part of [[Funda\u00e7\u00e3o Get\u00falio Vargas]] (FGV), obtained by the magazine [[Valor Econ\u00f4mico]], showed that the [[Gini coefficient]], which measures the economic inequality in society from 0 to 1, had increased year after year since 2015 and reached its peak in March 2019.\n\nIn 7 years, the accumulated wealth of the top 10% rose by 8.5%, while that of the 40% poorest dropped 14%. The research also showed that people with lower incomes suffered the effects of the crisis more intensely and recovered from the crisis slower. <ref>{{cite web|title=Desigualdade de renda no Brasil atinge o maior patamar j\u00e1 registrado, diz FGV/IBRE|url=https://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/2019/05/21/desigualdade-de-renda-no-brasil-atinge-o-maior-patamar-ja-registrado-diz-fgvibre.ghtml|work=G1|accessdate=2019-05-22|date=21 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Valor\">{{cite web|title=Desigualdade de renda no Brasil sobe pelo 17\u00ba trimestre consecutivo|url=https://www.valor.com.br/brasil/6265917/desigualdade-de-renda-no-brasil-sobe-pelo-17-trimestre-consecutivo|work=Valor Econ\u00f4mico|date=2019-05-19|accessdate=2019-05-22|author=Bruno Villas B\u00f4as|location=Rio de Janeiro}}</ref><ref name=\"IBRE\">{{cite web |title=Levantamento do FGV IBRE aponta desigualdade recorde na renda do trabalho |url=https://portalibre.fgv.br/navegacao-superior/noticias/levantamento-do-fgv-ibre-aponta-desigualdade-recorde-na-renda-do-trabalho.htm |work=IBRE/FGV |accessdate=23 May 2019 |date=21 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to an Ibre researcher, Daniel Duque, the recovery of the job market was concentrated in people with higher qualification and experience, reinforcing the inequality. Many underqualified people gave up trying to get a job, and the loss of hope was \"[...] record high, and it helps to explain why, even after the decrease in unemployment, inequality kept rising.\"<ref name=\"Valor\" />\n\n=== Emigration ===\n{{main article|Brazilian diaspora}}\n[[File:Quantidade de declara\u00e7\u00f5es de sa\u00edda definitiva do Brasil.jpg|thumb|355px|Number of declarations of definite emigration from the country. Source:[[Receita Federal do Brasil|Receita Federal]].<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|title=Cresce n\u00famero de brasileiros que decidem viver no exterior; pa\u00edses oferecem oportunidades de emprego|url=https://g1.globo.com/economia/concursos-e-emprego/noticia/2019/04/03/cresce-numero-de-brasileiros-que-decidem-viver-no-exterior-paises-oferecem-oportunidades-de-emprego.ghtml|work=G1|author=Luiz Guilherme Gerbelli|accessdate=25 October 2019|date=3 April 2019}}</ref>]]\n\nThe number of declarations of definitive departure from the country began to grow in the first year of crisis and has increased steadily ever since, according to [[Receita Federal do Brasil|Receita Federal]]. Among the countries that received the most Brazilian citizens were [[Japan]] and [[Canada]], which, due to low unemployment and aging populations among other reasons, needed a boost to decrease the age of the workforce.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nAccording to a JBJ Partners employee (a company specialized in expatriation to the [[United States]]), many who fled Brazil were qualified workers:\n\n{{quote|We're talking about qualified people. The profile of the immigrant is no longer that of the poor individual looking for better opportunities. They are high executives, who are abandoning their careers to open a business abroad, people with Ph.D., which is sad because the country is losing resources.|Jorge Botrel, a JBJ partner.<ref>{{cite web |title=Com a crise, dispara a quantidade de brasileiros que desistem de viver no Brasil |url=https://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/com-a-crise-dispara-a-quantidade-de-brasileiros-que-desistem-de-viver-no-brasil.ghtml |work=G1|accessdate=25 October 2019|date=17 December 2017|author=Lu\u00edsa Melo}}</ref>}}\n\nAn [[OECD]] report shows a much more elevated number<!-- In comparison to what? -->. In 2016 80,000 Brazilians emigrated legally to one of the member states of the OECD, whereas 99,000 did so in 2017. Similarly, data from Receita Federal shows that the number of people leaving Brazil increased in consecutive years since the beginning of the crisis.<ref>{{cite web |title=Imigra\u00e7\u00e3o de brasileiros para pa\u00edses da OCDE subiu 24%, o terceiro maior aumento |url=https://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2019/09/18/politica/1568843366_553673.html |work=El Pa\u00eds|author=Felipe Betim|accessdate=25 October 2019|date=19 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Credit rating ===\nThis is a table of the credit ratings of the Brazilian economy according to Trading Economics.{{who|date=April 2017}}{{cn|date=April 2017}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Agency !! Rating !! Outlook !! Date\n|-\n| Fitch || BB || negative || May 5, 2016\n|-\n| TE || 34 || negative || Apr 16 2016\n|-\n| Moody's || Ba2 || negative || Feb 24 2016\n|-\n| S&P || BB || negative || Feb 17 2016\n|}\n\n== Anti-crisis measures ==\n[[File:Entrevistas Diversas (30847431200).jpg|[[Henrique Meirelles]], the [[Ministry of Finance (Brazil)|Minister of Finance]] from May 2016 to April 2018.|thumb]]\nSince the impeachment of Dilma Rousseff and [[Michel Temer]]'s subsequent rise to power, several measures, most of which unpopular, were implemented or proposed to get the economy back on track.<ref>{{cite journal|title='Aproveito impopularidade para tomar medidas necess\u00e1rias', diz Temer|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/2016/12/1843702-aproveito-impopularidade-para-tomar-medidas-necessarias-diz-temer.shtml|journal=Folha de S.Paulo|date=22 December 2016|accessdate=17 June 2017|author=Marina Dias Valdo Cruz|location=Bras\u00edlia}}</ref> The most important of which were:\n\n* The {{ill|95\u00ba Constitutional amendment|pt|Emenda Constitucional do Teto dos Gastos P\u00fablicos|vertical-align=sup}} (a.k.a \"new fiscal regime\"): Constitutional amendment which established a \"ceiling\" (upper limit) to government spending for the next 20 years;<ref>{{cite journal|title=Temer elogia aprova\u00e7\u00e3o da PEC do Teto e minimiza menor n\u00famero de votos a favor|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/politica/noticia/2016-12/temer-elogia-aprovacao-da-pec-do-teto-e-minimiza-menor-numero-de-votos|accessdate=17 June 2017|location=Bras\u00edlia|journal= Ag\u00eancia Brasil|date=13 December 2016|author=Paulo Victor Chagas}}</ref>\n* The [[Outsourcing law in Brazil|Outsourcing law]], which allows companies to hire outsourced employees to work on primary activities, and not just secondary activities (such as security or cleaning);<ref>{{cite web|title=Com vetos, Temer sanciona lei que permite terceiriza\u00e7\u00e3o de atividade-fim|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/politica/noticia/2017-03/temer-sanciona-lei-que-permite-terceirizacao-em-atividade-fim-das-empresas|accessdate=17 June 2017|work = Ag\u00eancia Brasil|date=31 March 2017|author=Ivan Richard Esposito|location=Bras\u00edlia}}</ref>\n* The [[Brazil labor reform (2017)|2017 labor reform]], a significant change in the [[Consolidation of Labor Laws]]; and<ref>{{cite web|title=Com flexibiliza\u00e7\u00e3o de v\u00e1rios pontos da CLT, reforma trabalhista divide opini\u00f5es|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/politica/noticia/2017-04/com-flexibilizacao-de-varios-pontos-da-clt-reforma-trabalhista-divide|accessdate=17 June 2017|work = Ag\u00eancia Brasil|location=S\u00e3o Paulo|date=13 April 2017|author=Daniel Mello}}</ref>\n* a pension reform, which the government failed to approve.<ref>{{cite web|title=Governo desiste da vota\u00e7\u00e3o da Previd\u00eancia e anuncia nova pauta priorit\u00e1ria no Congresso|url=https://g1.globo.com/politica/noticia/governo-desiste-da-votacao-da-previdencia-e-anuncia-nova-pauta-prioritaria-no-congresso.ghtml||work = G1|accessdate=26 May 2019|date=19 February 2018|author1=Guilherme Mazui |author2=Roniara Castilhos}}</ref>\n\nOne year after the labor reform was approved, however, it was verified that the decrease in unemployment was minimal, while the contracts of intermittent, outsourced and temporary labor increased.<ref>{{cite web|author=Fabiana Futema|date=10 November 2018|title=Um ano depois, reforma trabalhista n\u00e3o gera empregos esperados|url=https://veja.abril.com.br/economia/um-ano-depois-reforma-trabalhista-nao-gera-empregos-esperados/|work=VEJA.com|accessdate=2019-05-26}}</ref>\n\n== Recovery ==\nIn early 2017, there were already signals that the economy was beginning to recover, however, it was agreed that the process would be long and slow.<ref>{{cite web|title=Recupera\u00e7\u00e3o da economia brasileira ser\u00e1 longa e lenta, aponta 'FT'|url=http://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,recuperacao-da-economia-brasileira-sera-longa-e-lenta-aponta-ft,70001658076}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Recupera\u00e7\u00e3o da economia brasileira ainda \u00e9 lenta, diz presidente do Ita\u00fa|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/mercado/2017/04/1876544-recuperacao-da-economia-brasileira-ainda-e-lenta-diz-presidente-do-itau.shtml}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, a 1% rise in GDP in the first quarter of the year was reported.<ref name=\"jn\"/> It was the first rise of the GDP after eight consecutive falls (two years).<ref name=\":0\">\n{{Cite news|title= PIB do Brasil cresce 1% no 1\u00ba trimestre de 2017, ap\u00f3s 8 quedas seguidas|url=http://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/pib-do-brasil-cresce-10-no-1-trimestre-de-2017.ghtml}}</ref> Minister of Finance [[Henrique Meirelles]] said that the country had left the \"greatest recession of the century.\"<ref>{{citation |title=PIB sobe 1% no 1\u00ba trimestre, ap\u00f3s oito quedas consecutivas|url=http://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,pib-sobe-1-0-no-1-trimestre-apos-oito-quedas-consecutivas,70001821658}}</ref> However, economists say that the growth characterizes only the end of the \"technical recession\" and that it is still too early to claim that the crisis is over, given that unemployment remains high and there's still widespread uncertainty regarding the future of the economy, especially in the aftermath of the recent political scandals.<ref>{{cite web|title=PIB positivo \u00e9 'sa\u00edda t\u00e9cnica' da recess\u00e3o, mas recupera\u00e7\u00e3o \u00e9 incerta; entenda|url=http://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/pib-positivo-e-saida-tecnica-da-recessao-mas-recuperacao-e-incerta-entenda.ghtml|accessdate=5 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Comparisons with other crises ==\n[[Image:Countries_by_Real_GDP_Growth_Rate_(2016).svg|thumb|Real GDP growth in 2016. Source:''CIA World Factbook''<ref>{{cite web|title=The World Factbook \u2014 Central Intelligence Agency|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2003rank.html|work=Central Intelligence Agency (CIA)}}</ref>|355px]]\nIn countries with similar size and wealth, there were a few, but less severe crisis in the same period. In 2015, among [[OECD]] countries, only [[Russia]] went through a recession. Even after the economic sanctions imposed by other countries due to the [[Russian military intervention in Ukraine (2014\u2013present)|conflict in Ukraine]], Russia's GDP fell by only 4% in two years (2015 and 2016). Few other countries in this period were going through a recession, which reinforces the argument that the crisis in Brazil was mainly due to local causes.<ref name=\"book\">{{Cite book|last=Carvalho|first=Laura|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XppWDwAAQBAJ|title=Valsa brasileira: Do boom ao caos econ\u00f4mico|date=2018-05-08|publisher=Editora Todavia S.A|isbn=978-85-93828-63-8|language=pt-BR}}</ref>\n\nIn comparison to other crises in Brazil, it was verified that the 2014 crisis was not the deepest, as previously thought. After the GDP values for 2015 and 2016 were reviewed by the [[Brazilian Institute of Geography and Statistics]] (IBGE), the economy shrank by 8.2% in the period, in contrast to the 8.5% in the 1981 recession. Despite not being the deepest, the crisis was long. It was also followed by the slowest recovery of all.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\nAccording to Codace (committee part of [[Funda\u00e7\u00e3o Get\u00falio Vargas]]), the 1981 crisis lasted nine trimesters, reached its peak in the first trimester of 1983 and, since then, took seven trimesters for the GDP the reach its pre-crisis level. Later, the 1989-1992 crisis lasted 11 trimesters and the recovery time was the same: seven trimesters. This crisis, however, had a lower intensity, with an accumulated decrease in the GDP of 7.7%.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\nIn turn, the GDP after the 2014 crisis will only reach its pre-crisis level in 2022, according to an optimistic estimate, with 20 trimesters of recovery in total. When taking into account not only the GDP, but also the employment rate, the recovery will be even slower. In addition to the sluggish recovery, the new jobs will be of lower quality, including informal and autonomous labor.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Brazil labor reform (2017)]]\n* [[Economy of Brazil]]\n* [[2018 in Brazil]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Government of Michel Temer}}\n{{Financial crises}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2014 Brazilian economic recession}}\n[[Category:2010s economic history]]\n[[Category:2014 in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Economic crises in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Recessions]]\n[[Category:Government of Michel Temer]]\n[[Category:Economic history of Brazil]]\n", "name_user": "20182309L", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2014_Brazilian_economic_crisis"}
